inputs.help: The item being described is intended to assess the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

inputs.name: educationalLevel
inputs.label: Educational Level
inputs.help: The level in terms of progression through an educational or training context. Examples of educational levels include 'beginner', 'intermediate' or 'advanced', and formal sets of level indicators.

inputs.name: teaches
inputs.label: Teaches
inputs.help: The item being described is intended to help a person learn the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

PriceSpecification.name: PriceSpecification
PriceSpecification.help: A structured value representing a price or price range. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup. It is recommended to use [[MonetaryAmount]] to describe independent amounts of money such as a salary, credit card limits, etc.

inputs.name: eligibleQuantity
inputs.label: Eligible Quantity
inputs.help: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

inputs.name: eligibleTransactionVolume
inputs.label: Eligible Transaction Volume
inputs.help: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

inputs.name: maxPrice
inputs.label: Max Price
inputs.help: The highest price if the price is a range.

inputs.name: minPrice
inputs.label: Min Price
inputs.help: The lowest price if the price is a range.

inputs.name: price
inputs.label: Price
inputs.help:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217), e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies, e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Trading Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types, e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similar Unicode symbols.

inputs.name: priceCurrency
inputs.label: Price Currency
inputs.help: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217), e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies, e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Trading Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types, e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.label: Valid From
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.label: Valid Through
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: valueAddedTaxIncluded
inputs.label: Value Added Tax Included
inputs.help: Specifies whether the applicable value-added tax (VAT) is included in the price specification or not.

HowToSupply.name: HowToSupply
HowToSupply.help: A supply consumed when performing the instructions for how to achieve a result.

inputs.name: estimatedCost
inputs.label: Estimated Cost
inputs.help: The estimated cost of the supply or supplies consumed when performing instructions.

SolveMathAction.name: SolveMathAction
SolveMathAction.help: The action that takes in a math expression and directs users to a page potentially capable of solving/simplifying that expression.

inputs.name: eduQuestionType
inputs.label: Edu Question Type
inputs.help: For questions that are part of learning resources (e.g. Quiz), eduQuestionType indicates the format of question being given. Example: "Multiple choice", "Open ended", "Flashcard".

MedicalGuideline.name: MedicalGuideline
MedicalGuideline.help: Any recommendation made by a standard society (e.g. ACC/AHA) or consensus statement that denotes how to diagnose and treat a particular condition. Note: this type should be used to tag the actual guideline recommendation; if the guideline recommendation occurs in a larger scholarly article, use MedicalScholarlyArticle to tag the overall article, not this type. Note also: the organization making the recommendation should be captured in the recognizingAuthority base property of MedicalEntity.

inputs.name: evidenceLevel
inputs.label: Evidence Level
inputs.help: Strength of evidence of the data used to formulate the guideline (enumerated).

inputs.name: evidenceOrigin
inputs.label: Evidence Origin
inputs.help: Source of the data used to formulate the guidance, e.g. RCT, consensus opinion, etc.

inputs.name: guidelineDate
inputs.label: Guideline Date
inputs.help: Date on which this guideline's recommendation was made.

inputs.name: guidelineSubject
inputs.label: Guideline Subject
inputs.help: The medical conditions, treatments, etc. that are the subject of the guideline.

CommunicateAction.name: CommunicateAction
CommunicateAction.help: The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.

inputs.name: about
inputs.label: About
inputs.help: The subject matter of the content.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.label: In Language
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: language
inputs.label: Language
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.label: Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

Schedule.name: Schedule
Schedule.help:
A schedule defines a repeating time period used to describe a regularly occurring [[Event]]. At a minimum a schedule will specify [[repeatFrequency]] which describes the interval between occurrences of the event. Additional information can be provided to specify the schedule more precisely.
      This includes identifying the day(s) of the week or month when the recurring event will take place, in addition to its start and end time. Schedules may also
      have start and end dates to indicate when they are active, e.g. to define a limited calendar of events.

inputs.name: byDay
inputs.label: By Day
inputs.help: Defines the day(s) of the week on which a recurring [[Event]] takes place. May be specified using either [[DayOfWeek]], or alternatively [[Text]] conforming to iCal's syntax for byDay recurrence rules.

inputs.name: byMonth
inputs.label: By Month
inputs.help: Defines the month(s) of the year on which a recurring [[Event]] takes place. Specified as an [[Integer]] between 1-12. January is 1.

inputs.name: byMonthDay
inputs.label: By Month Day
inputs.help: Defines the day(s) of the month on which a recurring [[Event]] takes place. Specified as an [[Integer]] between 1-31.

inputs.name: byMonthWeek
inputs.label: By Month Week
inputs.help: Defines the week(s) of the month on which a recurring Event takes place. Specified as an Integer between 1-5. For clarity, byMonthWeek is best used in conjunction with byDay to indicate concepts like the first and third Mondays of a month.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.label: Duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.label: End Date
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.label: End Time
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: exceptDate
inputs.label: Except Date
inputs.help:
Defines a [[Date]] or [[DateTime]] during which a scheduled [[Event]] will not take place. The property allows exceptions to
      a [[Schedule]] to be specified. If an exception is specified as a [[DateTime]] then only the event that would have started at that specific date and time
      should be excluded from the schedule. If an exception is specified as a [[Date]] then any event that is scheduled for that 24 hour period should be
      excluded from the schedule. This allows a whole day to be excluded from the schedule without having to itemise every scheduled event.

inputs.name: repeatCount
inputs.label: Repeat Count
inputs.help: Defines the number of times a recurring [[Event]] will take place.

inputs.name: repeatFrequency
inputs.label: Repeat Frequency
inputs.help:
Defines the frequency at which [[Event]]s will occur according to a schedule [[Schedule]]. The intervals between
      events should be defined as a [[Duration]] of time.

inputs.name: scheduleTimezone
inputs.label: Schedule Timezone
inputs.help: Indicates the timezone for which the time(s) indicated in the [[Schedule]] are given. The value provided should be among those listed in the IANA Time Zone Database.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.label: Start Date
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.label: Start Time
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

PostalCodeRangeSpecification.name: PostalCodeRangeSpecification
PostalCodeRangeSpecification.help: Indicates a range of postal codes, usually defined as the set of valid codes between [[postalCodeBegin]] and [[postalCodeEnd]], inclusively.

inputs.name: postalCodeBegin
inputs.label: Postal Code Begin
inputs.help: First postal code in a range (included).

inputs.name: postalCodeEnd
inputs.label: Postal Code End
inputs.help: Last postal code in the range (included). Needs to be after [[postalCodeBegin]].

ReserveAction.name: ReserveAction
ReserveAction.help:
Reserving a concrete object.

Related actions:

* [[ScheduleAction]]: Unlike ScheduleAction, ReserveAction reserves concrete objects (e.g. a table, a hotel) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

Chapter.name: Chapter
Chapter.help: One of the sections into which a book is divided. A chapter usually has a section number or a name.

inputs.name: pageEnd
inputs.label: Page End
inputs.help: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

inputs.name: pageStart
inputs.label: Page Start
inputs.help: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

inputs.name: pagination
inputs.label: Pagination
inputs.help: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

ChemicalSubstance.name: ChemicalSubstance
ChemicalSubstance.help: A chemical substance is 'a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types' (source: [ChEBI:59999](https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=59999)).

inputs.name: chemicalComposition
inputs.label: Chemical Composition
inputs.help: The chemical composition describes the identity and relative ratio of the chemical elements that make up the substance.

inputs.name: chemicalRole
inputs.label: Chemical Role
inputs.help: A role played by the BioChemEntity within a chemical context.

inputs.name: potentialUse
inputs.label: Potential Use
inputs.help: Intended use of the BioChemEntity by humans.

Dataset.name: Dataset
Dataset.help: A body of structured information describing some topic(s) of interest.

inputs.name: catalog
inputs.label: Catalog
inputs.help: A data catalog which contains this dataset.

inputs.name: datasetTimeInterval
inputs.label: Dataset Time Interval
inputs.help: The range of temporal applicability of a dataset, e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 (in ISO 8601 time interval format).

inputs.name: distribution
inputs.label: Distribution
inputs.help: A downloadable form of this dataset, at a specific location, in a specific format. This property can be repeated if different variations are available. There is no expectation that different downloadable distributions must contain exactly equivalent information (see also [DCAT](https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-dcat-3/#Class:Distribution) on this point). Different distributions might include or exclude different subsets of the entire dataset, for example.

inputs.name: includedDataCatalog
inputs.label: Included Data Catalog
inputs.help: A data catalog which contains this dataset (this property was previously 'catalog', preferred name is now 'includedInDataCatalog').

inputs.name: includedInDataCatalog
inputs.label: Included In Data Catalog
inputs.help: A data catalog which contains this dataset.

inputs.name: issn
inputs.label: Issn
inputs.help: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

inputs.name: measurementMethod
inputs.label: Measurement Method
inputs.help: A subproperty of [[measurementTechnique]] that can be used for specifying specific methods, in particular via [[MeasurementMethodEnum]].

inputs.name: measurementTechnique
inputs.label: Measurement Technique
inputs.help:
A technique, method or technology used in an [[Observation]], [[StatisticalVariable]] or [[Dataset]] (or [[DataDownload]], [[DataCatalog]]), corresponding to the method used for measuring the corresponding variable(s) (for datasets, described using [[variableMeasured]]; for [[Observation]], a [[StatisticalVariable]]). Often but not necessarily each [[variableMeasured]] will have an explicit representation as (or mapping to) an property such as those defined in Schema.org, or other RDF vocabularies and "knowledge graphs". In that case the subproperty of [[variableMeasured]] called [[measuredProperty]] is applicable.
    
The [[measurementTechnique]] property helps when extra clarification is needed about how a [[measuredProperty]] was measured. This is oriented towards scientific and scholarly dataset publication but may have broader applicability; it is not intended as a full representation of measurement, but can often serve as a high level summary for dataset discovery. 

For example, if [[variableMeasured]] is: molecule concentration, [[measurementTechnique]] could be: "mass spectrometry" or "nmr spectroscopy" or "colorimetry" or "immunofluorescence". If the [[variableMeasured]] is "depression rating", the [[measurementTechnique]] could be "Zung Scale" or "HAM-D" or "Beck Depression Inventory". 

If there are several [[variableMeasured]] properties recorded for some given data object, use a [[PropertyValue]] for each [[variableMeasured]] and attach the corresponding [[measurementTechnique]]. The value can also be from an enumeration, organized as a [[MeasurementMetholdEnumeration]].

inputs.name: variableMeasured
inputs.label: Variable Measured
inputs.help: The variableMeasured property can indicate (repeated as necessary) the  variables that are measured in some dataset, either described as text or as pairs of identifier and description using PropertyValue, or more explicitly as a [[StatisticalVariable]].

inputs.name: calories
inputs.label: Calories
inputs.help: The number of calories.

inputs.name: carbohydrateContent
inputs.label: Carbohydrate Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of carbohydrates.

inputs.name: cholesterolContent
inputs.label: Cholesterol Content
inputs.help: The number of milligrams of cholesterol.

inputs.name: fatContent
inputs.label: Fat Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of fat.

inputs.name: fiberContent
inputs.label: Fiber Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of fiber.

inputs.name: proteinContent
inputs.label: Protein Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of protein.

inputs.name: saturatedFatContent
inputs.label: Saturated Fat Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of saturated fat.

inputs.name: servingSize
inputs.label: Serving Size
inputs.help: The serving size, in terms of the number of volume or mass.

inputs.name: sodiumContent
inputs.label: Sodium Content
inputs.help: The number of milligrams of sodium.

inputs.name: sugarContent
inputs.label: Sugar Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of sugar.

inputs.name: transFatContent
inputs.label: Trans Fat Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of trans fat.

inputs.name: unsaturatedFatContent
inputs.label: Unsaturated Fat Content
inputs.help: The number of grams of unsaturated fat.

SizeSpecification.name: SizeSpecification
SizeSpecification.help: Size related properties of a product, typically a size code ([[name]]) and optionally a [[sizeSystem]], [[sizeGroup]], and product measurements ([[hasMeasurement]]). In addition, the intended audience can be defined through [[suggestedAge]], [[suggestedGender]], and suggested body measurements ([[suggestedMeasurement]]).

inputs.name: hasMeasurement
inputs.label: Has Measurement
inputs.help: A measurement of an item, For example, the inseam of pants, the wheel size of a bicycle, the gauge of a screw, or the carbon footprint measured for certification by an authority. Usually an exact measurement, but can also be a range of measurements for adjustable products, for example belts and ski bindings.

inputs.name: sizeGroup
inputs.label: Size Group
inputs.help: The size group (also known as "size type") for a product's size. Size groups are common in the fashion industry to define size segments and suggested audiences for wearable products. Multiple values can be combined, for example "men's big and tall", "petite maternity" or "regular".

inputs.name: sizeSystem
inputs.label: Size System
inputs.help: The size system used to identify a product's size. Typically either a standard (for example, "GS1" or "ISO-EN13402"), country code (for example "US" or "JP"), or a measuring system (for example "Metric" or "Imperial").

inputs.name: suggestedAge
inputs.label: Suggested Age
inputs.help: The age or age range for the intended audience or person, for example 3-12 months for infants, 1-5 years for toddlers.

inputs.name: suggestedGender
inputs.label: Suggested Gender
inputs.help: The suggested gender of the intended person or audience, for example "male", "female", or "unisex".

inputs.name: suggestedMeasurement
inputs.label: Suggested Measurement
inputs.help: A suggested range of body measurements for the intended audience or person, for example inseam between 32 and 34 inches or height between 170 and 190 cm. Typically found on a size chart for wearable products.

BedType.name: BedType
BedType.help: A type of bed. This is used for indicating the bed or beds available in an accommodation.

Statement.name: Statement
Statement.help: A statement about something, for example a fun or interesting fact. If known, the main entity this statement is about can be indicated using mainEntity. For more formal claims (e.g. in Fact Checking), consider using [[Claim]] instead. Use the [[text]] property to capture the text of the statement.

UserPlays.name: UserPlays
UserPlays.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

MiddleSchool.name: MiddleSchool
MiddleSchool.help: A middle school (typically for children aged around 11-14, although this varies somewhat).

MedicalCause.name: MedicalCause
MedicalCause.help: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.

inputs.name: causeOf
inputs.label: Cause Of
inputs.help: The condition, complication, symptom, sign, etc. caused.

Energy.name: Energy
Energy.help: Properties that take Energy as values are of the form '<Number> <Energy unit of measure>'.

MolecularEntity.name: MolecularEntity
MolecularEntity.help: Any constitutionally or isotopically distinct atom, molecule, ion, ion pair, radical, radical ion, complex, conformer etc., identifiable as a separately distinguishable entity.

inputs.name: chemicalRole
inputs.label: Chemical Role
inputs.help: A role played by the BioChemEntity within a chemical context.

inputs.name: inChI
inputs.label: In Ch I
inputs.help: Non-proprietary identifier for molecular entity that can be used in printed and electronic data sources thus enabling easier linking of diverse data compilations.

inputs.name: inChIKey
inputs.label: In Ch I Key
inputs.help: InChIKey is a hashed version of the full InChI (using the SHA-256 algorithm).

inputs.name: iupacName
inputs.label: Iupac Name
inputs.help: Systematic method of naming chemical compounds as recommended by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC).

inputs.name: molecularFormula
inputs.label: Molecular Formula
inputs.help: The empirical formula is the simplest whole number ratio of all the atoms in a molecule.

inputs.name: molecularWeight
inputs.label: Molecular Weight
inputs.help: This is the molecular weight of the entity being described, not of the parent. Units should be included in the form '<Number> <unit>', for example '12 amu' or as '<QuantitativeValue>.

inputs.name: monoisotopicMolecularWeight
inputs.label: Monoisotopic Molecular Weight
inputs.help: The monoisotopic mass is the sum of the masses of the atoms in a molecule using the unbound, ground-state, rest mass of the principal (most abundant) isotope for each element instead of the isotopic average mass. Please include the units in the form '<Number> <unit>', for example '770.230488 g/mol' or as '<QuantitativeValue>.

inputs.name: potentialUse
inputs.label: Potential Use
inputs.help: Intended use of the BioChemEntity by humans.

inputs.name: smiles
inputs.label: Smiles
inputs.help: A specification in form of a line notation for describing the structure of chemical species using short ASCII strings.  Double bond stereochemistry \ indicators may need to be escaped in the string in formats where the backslash is an escape character.

CivicStructure.name: CivicStructure
CivicStructure.help: A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.

inputs.name: openingHours
inputs.label: Opening Hours
inputs.help: The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'. * Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: ```Mo```, ```Tu```, ```We```, ```Th```, ```Fr```, ```Sa```, ```Su```. * Times are specified using 24:00 format. For example, 3pm is specified as ```15:00```, 10am as ```10:00```. * Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>. * If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

ReservationPackage.name: ReservationPackage
ReservationPackage.help: A group of multiple reservations with common values for all sub-reservations.

inputs.name: subReservation
inputs.label: Sub Reservation
inputs.help: The individual reservations included in the package. Typically a repeated property.

Series.name: Series
Series.help: A Series in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. See also [[CreativeWorkSeries]], [[EventSeries]].

MedicalStudyStatus.name: MedicalStudyStatus
MedicalStudyStatus.help: The status of a medical study. Enumerated type.

Optician.name: Optician
Optician.help: A store that sells reading glasses and similar devices for improving vision.

MedicalDevice.name: MedicalDevice
MedicalDevice.help: Any object used in a medical capacity, such as to diagnose or treat a patient.

inputs.name: adverseOutcome
inputs.label: Adverse Outcome
inputs.help: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or otherwise life-threatening or requiring immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriousAdverseOutcome instead.

inputs.name: contraindication
inputs.label: Contraindication
inputs.help: A contraindication for this therapy.

inputs.name: postOp
inputs.label: Post Op
inputs.help: A description of the postoperative procedures, care, and/or followups for this device.

inputs.name: preOp
inputs.label: Pre Op
inputs.help: A description of the workup, testing, and other preparations required before implanting this device.

inputs.name: procedure
inputs.label: Procedure
inputs.help: A description of the procedure involved in setting up, using, and/or installing the device.

inputs.name: seriousAdverseOutcome
inputs.label: Serious Adverse Outcome
inputs.help: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

MedicalProcedure.name: MedicalProcedure
MedicalProcedure.help: A process of care used in either a diagnostic, therapeutic, preventive or palliative capacity that relies on invasive (surgical), non-invasive, or other techniques.

inputs.name: bodyLocation
inputs.label: Body Location
inputs.help: Location in the body of the anatomical structure.

inputs.name: followup
inputs.label: Followup
inputs.help: Typical or recommended followup care after the procedure is performed.

inputs.name: howPerformed
inputs.label: How Performed
inputs.help: How the procedure is performed.

inputs.name: preparation
inputs.label: Preparation
inputs.help: Typical preparation that a patient must undergo before having the procedure performed.

inputs.name: procedureType
inputs.label: Procedure Type
inputs.help: The type of procedure, for example Surgical, Noninvasive, or Percutaneous.

inputs.name: status
inputs.label: Status
inputs.help: The status of the study (enumerated).

TelevisionChannel.name: TelevisionChannel
TelevisionChannel.help: A unique instance of a television BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

GeospatialGeometry.name: GeospatialGeometry
GeospatialGeometry.help: (Eventually to be defined as) a supertype of GeoShape designed to accommodate definitions from Geo-Spatial best practices.

inputs.name: geoContains
inputs.label: Geo Contains
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a containing geometry to a contained geometry. "a contains b iff no points of b lie in the exterior of a, and at least one point of the interior of b lies in the interior of a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCoveredBy
inputs.label: Geo Covered By
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that covers it. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCovers
inputs.label: Geo Covers
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a covering geometry to a covered geometry. "Every point of b is a point of (the interior or boundary of) a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCrosses
inputs.label: Geo Crosses
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that crosses it: "a crosses b: they have some but not all interior points in common, and the dimension of the intersection is less than that of at least one of them". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoDisjoint
inputs.label: Geo Disjoint
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically disjoint: "they have no point in common. They form a set of disconnected geometries." (A symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).)

inputs.name: geoEquals
inputs.label: Geo Equals
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically equal, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM). "Two geometries are topologically equal if their interiors intersect and no part of the interior or boundary of one geometry intersects the exterior of the other" (a symmetric relationship).

inputs.name: geoIntersects
inputs.label: Geo Intersects
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) have at least one point in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoOverlaps
inputs.label: Geo Overlaps
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that geospatially overlaps it, i.e. they have some but not all points in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoTouches
inputs.label: Geo Touches
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) touch: "they have at least one boundary point in common, but no interior points." (A symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).)

inputs.name: geoWithin
inputs.label: Geo Within
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to one that contains it, i.e. it is inside (i.e. within) its interior. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

VideoObjectSnapshot.name: VideoObjectSnapshot
VideoObjectSnapshot.help: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of a [[VideoObject]]. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. If they have different embedded metadata the files will differ. Different external facts about the files, e.g. creator or dateCreated that aren't represented in their actual content, do not affect this notion of identity.

DeleteAction.name: DeleteAction
DeleteAction.help: The act of editing a recipient by removing one of its objects.

TipAction.name: TipAction
TipAction.help: The act of giving money voluntarily to a beneficiary in recognition of services rendered.

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.label: Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

CurrencyConversionService.name: CurrencyConversionService
CurrencyConversionService.help: A service to convert funds from one currency to another currency.

HyperTocEntry.name: HyperTocEntry
HyperTocEntry.help: A HyperToEntry is an item within a [[HyperToc]], which represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as [[VideoObject]], [[AudioObject]]. The media object itself is indicated using [[associatedMedia]]. Each section of interest within that content can be described with a [[HyperTocEntry]], with associated [[startOffset]] and [[endOffset]]. When several entries are all from the same file, [[associatedMedia]] is used on the overarching [[HyperTocEntry]]; if the content has been split into multiple files, they can be referenced using [[associatedMedia]] on each [[HyperTocEntry]].

inputs.name: associatedMedia
inputs.label: Associated Media
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

inputs.name: tocContinuation
inputs.label: Toc Continuation
inputs.help: A [[HyperTocEntry]] can have a [[tocContinuation]] indicated, which is another [[HyperTocEntry]] that would be the default next item to play or render.

inputs.name: utterances
inputs.label: Utterances
inputs.help: Text of an utterances (spoken words, lyrics etc.) that occurs at a certain section of a media object, represented as a [[HyperTocEntry]].

TVEpisode.name: TVEpisode
TVEpisode.help: A TV episode which can be part of a series or season.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.label: Country Of Origin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: partOfTVSeries
inputs.label: Part Of TV Series
inputs.help: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

inputs.name: subtitleLanguage
inputs.label: Subtitle Language
inputs.help: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: titleEIDR
inputs.label: Title EIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing at the most general/abstract level, a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" has a titleEIDR of  "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J". This title (or work) may have several variants, which EIDR calls "edits". See [[editEIDR]].

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]], [[TVEpisode]], [[TVSeason]], and [[TVSeries]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

DigitalDocumentPermission.name: DigitalDocumentPermission
DigitalDocumentPermission.help: A permission for a particular person or group to access a particular file.

inputs.name: grantee
inputs.label: Grantee
inputs.help: The person, organization, contact point, or audience that has been granted this permission.

inputs.name: permissionType
inputs.label: Permission Type
inputs.help: The type of permission granted the person, organization, or audience.

OccupationalTherapy.name: OccupationalTherapy
OccupationalTherapy.help: A treatment of people with physical, emotional, or social problems, using purposeful activity to help them overcome or learn to deal with their problems.

inputs.name: applicationCategory
inputs.label: Application Category
inputs.help: Type of software application, e.g. 'Game, Multimedia'.

inputs.name: applicationSubCategory
inputs.label: Application Sub Category
inputs.help: Subcategory of the application, e.g. 'Arcade Game'.

inputs.name: applicationSuite
inputs.label: Application Suite
inputs.help: The name of the application suite to which the application belongs (e.g. Excel belongs to Office).

inputs.name: availableOnDevice
inputs.label: Available On Device
inputs.help: Device required to run the application. Used in cases where a specific make/model is required to run the application.

inputs.name: countriesNotSupported
inputs.label: Countries Not Supported
inputs.help: Countries for which the application is not supported. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

inputs.name: countriesSupported
inputs.label: Countries Supported
inputs.help: Countries for which the application is supported. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

inputs.name: device
inputs.label: Device
inputs.help: Device required to run the application. Used in cases where a specific make/model is required to run the application.

inputs.name: downloadUrl
inputs.label: Download Url
inputs.help: If the file can be downloaded, URL to download the binary.

inputs.name: featureList
inputs.label: Feature List
inputs.help: Features or modules provided by this application (and possibly required by other applications).

inputs.name: fileSize
inputs.label: File Size
inputs.help: Size of the application / package (e.g. 18MB). In the absence of a unit (MB, KB etc.), KB will be assumed.

inputs.name: installUrl
inputs.label: Install Url
inputs.help: URL at which the app may be installed, if different from the URL of the item.

inputs.name: memoryRequirements
inputs.label: Memory Requirements
inputs.help: Minimum memory requirements.

inputs.name: operatingSystem
inputs.label: Operating System
inputs.help: Operating systems supported (Windows 7, OS X 10.6, Android 1.6).

inputs.name: permissions
inputs.label: Permissions
inputs.help: Permission(s) required to run the app (for example, a mobile app may require full internet access or may run only on wifi).

inputs.name: processorRequirements
inputs.label: Processor Requirements
inputs.help: Processor architecture required to run the application (e.g. IA64).

inputs.name: releaseNotes
inputs.label: Release Notes
inputs.help: Description of what changed in this version.

inputs.name: requirements
inputs.label: Requirements
inputs.help: Component dependency requirements for application. This includes runtime environments and shared libraries that are not included in the application distribution package, but required to run the application (examples: DirectX, Java or .NET runtime).

inputs.name: screenshot
inputs.label: Screenshot
inputs.help: A link to a screenshot image of the app.

inputs.name: softwareAddOn
inputs.label: Software Add On
inputs.help: Additional content for a software application.

inputs.name: softwareHelp
inputs.label: Software Help
inputs.help: Software application help.

inputs.name: softwareRequirements
inputs.label: Software Requirements
inputs.help: Component dependency requirements for application. This includes runtime environments and shared libraries that are not included in the application distribution package, but required to run the application (examples: DirectX, Java or .NET runtime).

inputs.name: softwareVersion
inputs.label: Software Version
inputs.help: Version of the software instance.

inputs.name: storageRequirements
inputs.label: Storage Requirements
inputs.help: Storage requirements (free space required).

inputs.name: supportingData
inputs.label: Supporting Data
inputs.help: Supporting data for a SoftwareApplication.

ExercisePlan.name: ExercisePlan
ExercisePlan.help: Fitness-related activity designed for a specific health-related purpose, including defined exercise routines as well as activity prescribed by a clinician.

inputs.name: activityDuration
inputs.label: Activity Duration
inputs.help: Length of time to engage in the activity.

inputs.name: activityFrequency
inputs.label: Activity Frequency
inputs.help: How often one should engage in the activity.

inputs.name: additionalVariable
inputs.label: Additional Variable
inputs.help: Any additional component of the exercise prescription that may need to be articulated to the patient. This may include the order of exercises, the number of repetitions of movement, quantitative distance, progressions over time, etc.

inputs.name: exerciseType
inputs.label: Exercise Type
inputs.help: Type(s) of exercise or activity, such as strength training, flexibility training, aerobics, cardiac rehabilitation, etc.

inputs.name: intensity
inputs.label: Intensity
inputs.help: Quantitative measure gauging the degree of force involved in the exercise, for example, heartbeats per minute. May include the velocity of the movement.

inputs.name: repetitions
inputs.label: Repetitions
inputs.help: Number of times one should repeat the activity.

inputs.name: restPeriods
inputs.label: Rest Periods
inputs.help: How often one should break from the activity.

inputs.name: workload
inputs.label: Workload
inputs.help: Quantitative measure of the physiologic output of the exercise; also referred to as energy expenditure.

Landform.name: Landform
Landform.help: A landform or physical feature.  Landform elements include mountains, plains, lakes, rivers, seascape and oceanic waterbody interface features such as bays, peninsulas, seas and so forth, including sub-aqueous terrain features such as submersed mountain ranges, volcanoes, and the great ocean basins.

ApprovedIndication.name: ApprovedIndication
ApprovedIndication.help: An indication for a medical therapy that has been formally specified or approved by a regulatory body that regulates use of the therapy; for example, the US FDA approves indications for most drugs in the US.

OrderItem.name: OrderItem
OrderItem.help: An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.

inputs.name: orderDelivery
inputs.label: Order Delivery
inputs.help: The delivery of the parcel related to this order or order item.

inputs.name: orderItemNumber
inputs.label: Order Item Number
inputs.help: The identifier of the order item.

inputs.name: orderItemStatus
inputs.label: Order Item Status
inputs.help: The current status of the order item.

inputs.name: orderQuantity
inputs.label: Order Quantity
inputs.help: The number of the item ordered. If the property is not set, assume the quantity is one.

inputs.name: orderedItem
inputs.label: Ordered Item
inputs.help: The item ordered.

EmergencyService.name: EmergencyService
EmergencyService.help: An emergency service, such as a fire station or ER.

DrugLegalStatus.name: DrugLegalStatus
DrugLegalStatus.help: The legal availability status of a medical drug.

inputs.name: applicableLocation
inputs.label: Applicable Location
inputs.help: The location in which the status applies.

Quotation.name: Quotation
Quotation.help: A quotation. Often but not necessarily from some written work, attributable to a real world author and - if associated with a fictional character - to any fictional Person. Use [[isBasedOn]] to link to source/origin. The [[recordedIn]] property can be used to reference a Quotation from an [[Event]].

inputs.name: spokenByCharacter
inputs.label: Spoken By Character
inputs.help: The (e.g. fictional) character, Person or Organization to whom the quotation is attributed within the containing CreativeWork.

EndorsementRating.name: EndorsementRating
EndorsementRating.help:
An EndorsementRating is a rating that expresses some level of endorsement, for example inclusion in a "critic's pick" blog, a
"Like" or "+1" on a social network. It can be considered the [[result]] of an [[EndorseAction]] in which the [[object]] of the action is rated positively by
some [[agent]]. As is common elsewhere in schema.org, it is sometimes more useful to describe the results of such an action without explicitly describing the [[Action]].

An [[EndorsementRating]] may be part of a numeric scale or organized system, but this is not required: having an explicit type for indicating a positive,
endorsement rating is particularly useful in the absence of numeric scales as it helps consumers understand that the rating is broadly positive.

inputs.name: caption
inputs.label: Caption
inputs.help: The caption for this object. For downloadable machine formats (closed caption, subtitles etc.) use MediaObject and indicate the [[encodingFormat]].

inputs.name: embeddedTextCaption
inputs.label: Embedded Text Caption
inputs.help: Represents textual captioning from a [[MediaObject]], e.g. text of a 'meme'.

inputs.name: exifData
inputs.label: Exif Data
inputs.help: exif data for this object.

inputs.name: representativeOfPage
inputs.label: Representative Of Page
inputs.help: Indicates whether this image is representative of the content of the page.

HomeAndConstructionBusiness.name: HomeAndConstructionBusiness
HomeAndConstructionBusiness.help:
A construction business.

A HomeAndConstructionBusiness is a [[LocalBusiness]] that provides services around homes and buildings.

As a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).

SteeringPositionValue.name: SteeringPositionValue
SteeringPositionValue.help: A value indicating a steering position.

Hotel.name: Hotel
Hotel.help:
A hotel is an establishment that provides lodging paid on a short-term basis (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotel).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

TakeAction.name: TakeAction
TakeAction.help:
The act of gaining ownership of an object from an origin. Reciprocal of GiveAction.

Related actions:

* [[GiveAction]]: The reciprocal of TakeAction.
* [[ReceiveAction]]: Unlike ReceiveAction, TakeAction implies that ownership has been transferred.

Season.name: Season
Season.help: A media season, e.g. TV, radio, video game etc.

RVPark.name: RVPark
RVPark.help: A place offering space for "Recreational Vehicles", Caravans, mobile homes and the like.

EventSeries.name: EventSeries
EventSeries.help:
A series of [[Event]]s. Included events can relate with the series using the [[superEvent]] property.

An EventSeries is a collection of events that share some unifying characteristic. For example, "The Olympic Games" is a series, which
is repeated regularly. The "2012 London Olympics" can be presented both as an [[Event]] in the series "Olympic Games", and as an
[[EventSeries]] that included a number of sporting competitions as Events.

The nature of the association between the events in an [[EventSeries]] can vary, but typical examples could
include a thematic event series (e.g. topical meetups or classes), or a series of regular events that share a location, attendee group and/or organizers.

EventSeries has been defined as a kind of Event to make it easy for publishers to use it in an Event context without
worrying about which kinds of series are really event-like enough to call an Event. In general an EventSeries
may seem more Event-like when the period of time is compact and when aspects such as location are fixed, but
it may also sometimes prove useful to describe a longer-term series as an Event.

InformAction.name: InformAction
InformAction.help: The act of notifying someone of information pertinent to them, with no expectation of a response.

inputs.name: event
inputs.label: Event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

ItemPage.name: ItemPage
ItemPage.help: A page devoted to a single item, such as a particular product or hotel.

ExchangeRateSpecification.name: ExchangeRateSpecification
ExchangeRateSpecification.help: A structured value representing exchange rate.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.label: Currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217), e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies, e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Trading Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types, e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: currentExchangeRate
inputs.label: Current Exchange Rate
inputs.help: The current price of a currency.

inputs.name: exchangeRateSpread
inputs.label: Exchange Rate Spread
inputs.help: The difference between the price at which a broker or other intermediary buys and sells foreign currency.

SocialMediaPosting.name: SocialMediaPosting
SocialMediaPosting.help: A post to a social media platform, including blog posts, tweets, Facebook posts, etc.

inputs.name: sharedContent
inputs.label: Shared Content
inputs.help: A CreativeWork such as an image, video, or audio clip shared as part of this posting.

APIReference.name: APIReference
APIReference.help: Reference documentation for application programming interfaces (APIs).

inputs.name: assembly
inputs.label: Assembly
inputs.help: Library file name, e.g., mscorlib.dll, system.web.dll.

inputs.name: assemblyVersion
inputs.label: Assembly Version
inputs.help: Associated product/technology version. E.g., .NET Framework 4.5.

inputs.name: executableLibraryName
inputs.label: Executable Library Name
inputs.help: Library file name, e.g., mscorlib.dll, system.web.dll.

inputs.name: programmingModel
inputs.label: Programming Model
inputs.help: Indicates whether API is managed or unmanaged.

inputs.name: targetPlatform
inputs.label: Target Platform
inputs.help: Type of app development: phone, Metro style, desktop, XBox, etc.

HowToItem.name: HowToItem
HowToItem.help: An item used as either a tool or supply when performing the instructions for how to achieve a result.

inputs.name: requiredQuantity
inputs.label: Required Quantity
inputs.help: The required quantity of the item(s).

OfferCatalog.name: OfferCatalog
OfferCatalog.help: An OfferCatalog is an ItemList that contains related Offers and/or further OfferCatalogs that are offeredBy the same provider.

PresentationDigitalDocument.name: PresentationDigitalDocument
PresentationDigitalDocument.help: A file containing slides or used for a presentation.

ArchiveOrganization.name: ArchiveOrganization
ArchiveOrganization.help: An organization with archival holdings. An organization which keeps and preserves archival material and typically makes it accessible to the public.

inputs.name: archiveHeld
inputs.label: Archive Held
inputs.help: Collection, [fonds](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fonds), or item held, kept or maintained by an [[ArchiveOrganization]].

inputs.name: aircraft
inputs.label: Aircraft
inputs.help: The kind of aircraft (e.g., "Boeing 747").

inputs.name: arrivalAirport
inputs.label: Arrival Airport
inputs.help: The airport where the flight terminates.

inputs.name: arrivalGate
inputs.label: Arrival Gate
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's arrival gate.

inputs.name: arrivalTerminal
inputs.label: Arrival Terminal
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's arrival terminal.

inputs.name: boardingPolicy
inputs.label: Boarding Policy
inputs.help: The type of boarding policy used by the airline (e.g. zone-based or group-based).

inputs.name: carrier
inputs.label: Carrier
inputs.help: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

inputs.name: departureAirport
inputs.label: Departure Airport
inputs.help: The airport where the flight originates.

inputs.name: departureGate
inputs.label: Departure Gate
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's departure gate.

inputs.name: departureTerminal
inputs.label: Departure Terminal
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's departure terminal.

inputs.name: estimatedFlightDuration
inputs.label: Estimated Flight Duration
inputs.help: The estimated time the flight will take.

inputs.name: flightDistance
inputs.label: Flight Distance
inputs.help: The distance of the flight.

inputs.name: flightNumber
inputs.label: Flight Number
inputs.help: The unique identifier for a flight including the airline IATA code. For example, if describing United flight 110, where the IATA code for United is 'UA', the flightNumber is 'UA110'.

inputs.name: mealService
inputs.label: Meal Service
inputs.help: Description of the meals that will be provided or available for purchase.

inputs.name: seller
inputs.label: Seller
inputs.help: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

inputs.name: webCheckinTime
inputs.label: Web Checkin Time
inputs.help: The time when a passenger can check into the flight online.

ParkingFacility.name: ParkingFacility
ParkingFacility.help: A parking lot or other parking facility.

Taxon.name: Taxon
Taxon.help: A set of organisms asserted to represent a natural cohesive biological unit.

inputs.name: childTaxon
inputs.label: Child Taxon
inputs.help: Closest child taxa of the taxon in question.

inputs.name: hasDefinedTerm
inputs.label: Has Defined Term
inputs.help: A Defined Term contained in this term set.

inputs.name: parentTaxon
inputs.label: Parent Taxon
inputs.help: Closest parent taxon of the taxon in question.

inputs.name: taxonRank
inputs.label: Taxon Rank
inputs.help: The taxonomic rank of this taxon given preferably as a URI from a controlled vocabulary – typically the ranks from TDWG TaxonRank ontology or equivalent Wikidata URIs.

MedicalScholarlyArticle.name: MedicalScholarlyArticle
MedicalScholarlyArticle.help: A scholarly article in the medical domain.

inputs.name: publicationType
inputs.label: Publication Type
inputs.help: The type of the medical article, taken from the US NLM MeSH publication type catalog. See also [MeSH documentation](http://www.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/pubtypes.html).

HealthInsurancePlan.name: HealthInsurancePlan
HealthInsurancePlan.help: A US-style health insurance plan, including PPOs, EPOs, and HMOs.

inputs.name: benefitsSummaryUrl
inputs.label: Benefits Summary Url
inputs.help: The URL that goes directly to the summary of benefits and coverage for the specific standard plan or plan variation.

inputs.name: contactPoint
inputs.label: Contact Point
inputs.help: A contact point for a person or organization.

inputs.name: healthPlanDrugOption
inputs.label: Health Plan Drug Option
inputs.help: TODO.

inputs.name: healthPlanDrugTier
inputs.label: Health Plan Drug Tier
inputs.help: The tier(s) of drugs offered by this formulary or insurance plan.

inputs.name: healthPlanId
inputs.label: Health Plan Id
inputs.help: The 14-character, HIOS-generated Plan ID number. (Plan IDs must be unique, even across different markets.)

inputs.name: healthPlanMarketingUrl
inputs.label: Health Plan Marketing Url
inputs.help: The URL that goes directly to the plan brochure for the specific standard plan or plan variation.

inputs.name: includesHealthPlanFormulary
inputs.label: Includes Health Plan Formulary
inputs.help: Formularies covered by this plan.

inputs.name: includesHealthPlanNetwork
inputs.label: Includes Health Plan Network
inputs.help: Networks covered by this plan.

inputs.name: usesHealthPlanIdStandard
inputs.label: Uses Health Plan Id Standard
inputs.help: The standard for interpreting the Plan ID. The preferred is "HIOS". See the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services for more details.

RadiationTherapy.name: RadiationTherapy
RadiationTherapy.help: A process of care using radiation aimed at improving a health condition.

inputs.name: athlete
inputs.label: Athlete
inputs.help: A person that acts as performing member of a sports team; a player as opposed to a coach.

inputs.name: coach
inputs.label: Coach
inputs.help: A person that acts in a coaching role for a sports team.

inputs.name: gender
inputs.label: Gender
inputs.help: Gender of something, typically a [[Person]], but possibly also fictional characters, animals, etc. While http://schema.org/Male and http://schema.org/Female may be used, text strings are also acceptable for people who do not identify as a binary gender. The [[gender]] property can also be used in an extended sense to cover e.g. the gender of sports teams. As with the gender of individuals, we do not try to enumerate all possibilities. A mixed-gender [[SportsTeam]] can be indicated with a text value of "Mixed".

CreditCard.name: CreditCard
CreditCard.help:
A card payment method of a particular brand or name.  Used to mark up a particular payment method and/or the financial product/service that supplies the card account.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA

LikeAction.name: LikeAction
LikeAction.help: The act of expressing a positive sentiment about the object. An agent likes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

CompoundPriceSpecification.name: CompoundPriceSpecification
CompoundPriceSpecification.help: A compound price specification is one that bundles multiple prices that all apply in combination for different dimensions of consumption. Use the name property of the attached unit price specification for indicating the dimension of a price component (e.g. "electricity" or "final cleaning").

inputs.name: priceComponent
inputs.label: Price Component
inputs.help: This property links to all [[UnitPriceSpecification]] nodes that apply in parallel for the [[CompoundPriceSpecification]] node.

inputs.name: priceType
inputs.label: Price Type
inputs.help: Defines the type of a price specified for an offered product, for example a list price, a (temporary) sale price or a manufacturer suggested retail price. If multiple prices are specified for an offer the [[priceType]] property can be used to identify the type of each such specified price. The value of priceType can be specified as a value from enumeration PriceTypeEnumeration or as a free form text string for price types that are not already predefined in PriceTypeEnumeration.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.label: Actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.label: Actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: caption
inputs.label: Caption
inputs.help: The caption for this object. For downloadable machine formats (closed caption, subtitles etc.) use MediaObject and indicate the [[encodingFormat]].

inputs.name: director
inputs.label: Director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.label: Directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: embeddedTextCaption
inputs.label: Embedded Text Caption
inputs.help: Represents textual captioning from a [[MediaObject]], e.g. text of a 'meme'.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.label: Music By
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: transcript
inputs.label: Transcript
inputs.help: If this MediaObject is an AudioObject or VideoObject, the transcript of that object.

inputs.name: videoFrameSize
inputs.label: Video Frame Size
inputs.help: The frame size of the video.

inputs.name: videoQuality
inputs.label: Video Quality
inputs.help: The quality of the video.

InsertAction.name: InsertAction
InsertAction.help: The act of adding at a specific location in an ordered collection.

inputs.name: toLocation
inputs.label: To Location
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

MedicalTherapy.name: MedicalTherapy
MedicalTherapy.help: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.

inputs.name: contraindication
inputs.label: Contraindication
inputs.help: A contraindication for this therapy.

inputs.name: duplicateTherapy
inputs.label: Duplicate Therapy
inputs.help: A therapy that duplicates or overlaps this one.

inputs.name: seriousAdverseOutcome
inputs.label: Serious Adverse Outcome
inputs.help: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

BusinessFunction.name: BusinessFunction
BusinessFunction.help:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy

Barcode.name: Barcode
Barcode.help: An image of a visual machine-readable code such as a barcode or QR code.

WearableSizeGroupEnumeration.name: WearableSizeGroupEnumeration
WearableSizeGroupEnumeration.help: Enumerates common size groups (also known as "size types") for wearable products.

AskPublicNewsArticle.name: AskPublicNewsArticle
AskPublicNewsArticle.help: A [[NewsArticle]] expressing an open call by a [[NewsMediaOrganization]] asking the public for input, insights, clarifications, anecdotes, documentation, etc., on an issue, for reporting purposes.

SpeakableSpecification.name: SpeakableSpecification
SpeakableSpecification.help: A SpeakableSpecification indicates (typically via [[xpath]] or [[cssSelector]]) sections of a document that are highlighted as particularly [[speakable]]. Instances of this type are expected to be used primarily as values of the [[speakable]] property.

inputs.name: cssSelector
inputs.label: Css Selector
inputs.help: A CSS selector, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

inputs.name: xpath
inputs.label: Xpath
inputs.help: An XPath, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

TouristDestination.name: TouristDestination
TouristDestination.help:
A tourist destination. In principle any [[Place]] can be a [[TouristDestination]] from a [[City]], Region or [[Country]] to an [[AmusementPark]] or [[Hotel]]. This Type can be used on its own to describe a general [[TouristDestination]], or be used as an [[additionalType]] to add tourist relevant properties to any other [[Place]].  A [[TouristDestination]] is defined as a [[Place]] that contains, or is colocated with, one or more [[TouristAttraction]]s, often linked by a similar theme or interest to a particular [[touristType]]. The [UNWTO](http://www2.unwto.org/) defines Destination (main destination of a tourism trip) as the place visited that is central to the decision to take the trip.
  (See examples below.)

inputs.name: includesAttraction
inputs.label: Includes Attraction
inputs.help: Attraction located at destination.

inputs.name: touristType
inputs.label: Tourist Type
inputs.help: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. E.g. children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

Vessel.name: Vessel
Vessel.help: A component of the human body circulatory system comprised of an intricate network of hollow tubes that transport blood throughout the entire body.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.label: Actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.label: Actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.label: Country Of Origin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: director
inputs.label: Director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.label: Directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.label: Duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.label: Music By
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.label: Production Company
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item, e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: subtitleLanguage
inputs.label: Subtitle Language
inputs.help: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: titleEIDR
inputs.label: Title EIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing at the most general/abstract level, a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" has a titleEIDR of  "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J". This title (or work) may have several variants, which EIDR calls "edits". See [[editEIDR]].

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]], [[TVEpisode]], [[TVSeason]], and [[TVSeries]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.label: Trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or TV/radio series, season, episode, etc.

Class.name: Class
Class.help: A class, also often called a 'Type'; equivalent to rdfs:Class.

inputs.name: supersededBy
inputs.label: Superseded By
inputs.help: Relates a term (i.e. a property, class or enumeration) to one that supersedes it.

GiveAction.name: GiveAction
GiveAction.help:
The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction.

Related actions:

* [[TakeAction]]: Reciprocal of GiveAction.
* [[SendAction]]: Unlike SendAction, GiveAction implies that ownership is being transferred (e.g. I may send my laptop to you, but that doesn't mean I'm giving it to you).

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.label: Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

DrawAction.name: DrawAction
DrawAction.help: The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.

Gene.name: Gene
Gene.help: A discrete unit of inheritance which affects one or more biological traits (Source: [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene)). Examples include FOXP2 (Forkhead box protein P2), SCARNA21 (small Cajal body-specific RNA 21), A- (agouti genotype).

inputs.name: alternativeOf
inputs.label: Alternative Of
inputs.help: Another gene which is a variation of this one.

inputs.name: encodesBioChemEntity
inputs.label: Encodes Bio Chem Entity
inputs.help: Another BioChemEntity encoded by this one.

inputs.name: expressedIn
inputs.label: Expressed In
inputs.help: Tissue, organ, biological sample, etc in which activity of this gene has been observed experimentally. For example brain, digestive system.

inputs.name: hasBioPolymerSequence
inputs.label: Has Bio Polymer Sequence
inputs.help: A symbolic representation of a BioChemEntity. For example, a nucleotide sequence of a Gene or an amino acid sequence of a Protein.

CompleteDataFeed.name: CompleteDataFeed
CompleteDataFeed.help:
A [[CompleteDataFeed]] is a [[DataFeed]] whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving [RFC 5005](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5005), for example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e.g. "Top Twenty Records") there is no need to have newer entries mixed in alongside older, obsolete entries. By marking this feed as a CompleteDataFeed, old entries can be safely discarded when the feed is refreshed, since we can assume the feed has provided descriptions for all current items.

ImageObjectSnapshot.name: ImageObjectSnapshot
ImageObjectSnapshot.help: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of an [[ImageObject]]. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. If they have different embedded metadata (e.g. XMP, EXIF) the files will differ. Different external facts about the files, e.g. creator or dateCreated that aren't represented in their actual content, do not affect this notion of identity.

Syllabus.name: Syllabus
Syllabus.help: A syllabus that describes the material covered in a course, often with several such sections per [[Course]] so that a distinct [[timeRequired]] can be provided for that section of the [[Course]].

RentalCarReservation.name: RentalCarReservation
RentalCarReservation.help: A reservation for a rental car.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

inputs.name: dropoffLocation
inputs.label: Dropoff Location
inputs.help: Where a rental car can be dropped off.

inputs.name: dropoffTime
inputs.label: Dropoff Time
inputs.help: When a rental car can be dropped off.

inputs.name: pickupLocation
inputs.label: Pickup Location
inputs.help: Where a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

inputs.name: pickupTime
inputs.label: Pickup Time
inputs.help: When a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

CreativeWorkSeries.name: CreativeWorkSeries
CreativeWorkSeries.help:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike [[ItemList]] which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as TV, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing [[TVSeries]], [[RadioSeries]], [[MovieSeries]], [[BookSeries]], [[Periodical]] and [[VideoGameSeries]]. In each case, the [[hasPart]] / [[isPartOf]] properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.label: End Date
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: issn
inputs.label: Issn
inputs.help: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.label: Start Date
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

MusicAlbumReleaseType.name: MusicAlbumReleaseType
MusicAlbumReleaseType.help: The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.

inputs.name: browserRequirements
inputs.label: Browser Requirements
inputs.help: Specifies browser requirements in human-readable text. For example, 'requires HTML5 support'.

MedicalConditionStage.name: MedicalConditionStage
MedicalConditionStage.help: A stage of a medical condition, such as 'Stage IIIa'.

inputs.name: stageAsNumber
inputs.label: Stage As Number
inputs.help: The stage represented as a number, e.g. 3.

inputs.name: subStageSuffix
inputs.label: Sub Stage Suffix
inputs.help: The substage, e.g. 'a' for Stage IIIa.

Quiz.name: Quiz
Quiz.help: Quiz: A test of knowledge, skills and abilities.

Language.name: Language
Language.help: Natural languages such as Spanish, Tamil, Hindi, English, etc. Formal language code tags expressed in [BCP 47](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IETF_language_tag) can be used via the [[alternateName]] property. The Language type previously also covered programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp, which are now best represented using [[ComputerLanguage]].

UseAction.name: UseAction
UseAction.help: The act of applying an object to its intended purpose.

Project.name: Project
Project.help:
An enterprise (potentially individual but typically collaborative), planned to achieve a particular aim.
Use properties from [[Organization]], [[subOrganization]]/[[parentOrganization]] to indicate project sub-structures.

AdultOrientedEnumeration.name: AdultOrientedEnumeration
AdultOrientedEnumeration.help: Enumeration of considerations that make a product relevant or potentially restricted for adults only.

HealthAspectEnumeration.name: HealthAspectEnumeration
HealthAspectEnumeration.help: HealthAspectEnumeration enumerates several aspects of health content online, each of which might be described using [[hasHealthAspect]] and [[HealthTopicContent]].

CheckAction.name: CheckAction
CheckAction.help: An agent inspects, determines, investigates, inquires, or examines an object's accuracy, quality, condition, or state.

TVClip.name: TVClip
TVClip.help: A short TV program or a segment/part of a TV program.

inputs.name: partOfTVSeries
inputs.label: Part Of TV Series
inputs.help: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

TouristAttraction.name: TouristAttraction
TouristAttraction.help: A tourist attraction.  In principle any Thing can be a [[TouristAttraction]], from a [[Mountain]] and [[LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings]] to a [[LocalBusiness]].  This Type can be used on its own to describe a general [[TouristAttraction]], or be used as an [[additionalType]] to add tourist attraction properties to any other type.  (See examples below)

inputs.name: availableLanguage
inputs.label: Available Language
inputs.help: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]].

inputs.name: touristType
inputs.label: Tourist Type
inputs.help: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. E.g. children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

PawnShop.name: PawnShop
PawnShop.help: A shop that will buy, or lend money against the security of, personal possessions.

ItemList.name: ItemList
ItemList.help: A list of items of any sort—for example, Top 10 Movies About Weathermen, or Top 100 Party Songs. Not to be confused with HTML lists, which are often used only for formatting.

inputs.name: itemListElement
inputs.label: Item List Element
inputs.help:
For itemListElement values, you can use simple strings (e.g. "Peter", "Paul", "Mary"), existing entities, or use ListItem.

Text values are best if the elements in the list are plain strings. Existing entities are best for a simple, unordered list of existing things in your data. ListItem is used with ordered lists when you want to provide additional context about the element in that list or when the same item might be in different places in different lists.

Note: The order of elements in your mark-up is not sufficient for indicating the order or elements.  Use ListItem with a 'position' property in such cases.

inputs.name: itemListOrder
inputs.label: Item List Order
inputs.help: Type of ordering (e.g. Ascending, Descending, Unordered).

inputs.name: numberOfItems
inputs.label: Number Of Items
