inputs.help: The number of items in an ItemList. Note that some descriptions might not fully describe all items in a list (e.g., multi-page pagination); in such cases, the numberOfItems would be for the entire list.

RiverBodyOfWater.name: RiverBodyOfWater
RiverBodyOfWater.help: A river (for example, the broad majestic Shannon).

SubscribeAction.name: SubscribeAction
SubscribeAction.help:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates pushed to.

Related actions:

* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, SubscribeAction implies that the subscriber acts as a passive agent being constantly/actively pushed for updates.
* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, SubscribeAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, SubscribeAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.

ParcelDelivery.name: ParcelDelivery
ParcelDelivery.help: The delivery of a parcel either via the postal service or a commercial service.

inputs.name: carrier
inputs.label: Carrier
inputs.help: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

inputs.name: deliveryAddress
inputs.label: Delivery Address
inputs.help: Destination address.

inputs.name: deliveryStatus
inputs.label: Delivery Status
inputs.help: New entry added as the package passes through each leg of its journey (from shipment to final delivery).

inputs.name: expectedArrivalFrom
inputs.label: Expected Arrival From
inputs.help: The earliest date the package may arrive.

inputs.name: expectedArrivalUntil
inputs.label: Expected Arrival Until
inputs.help: The latest date the package may arrive.

inputs.name: hasDeliveryMethod
inputs.label: Has Delivery Method
inputs.help: Method used for delivery or shipping.

inputs.name: itemShipped
inputs.label: Item Shipped
inputs.help: Item(s) being shipped.

inputs.name: originAddress
inputs.label: Origin Address
inputs.help: Shipper's address.

inputs.name: partOfOrder
inputs.label: Part Of Order
inputs.help: The overall order the items in this delivery were included in.

inputs.name: provider
inputs.label: Provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: trackingNumber
inputs.label: Tracking Number
inputs.help: Shipper tracking number.

inputs.name: trackingUrl
inputs.label: Tracking Url
inputs.help: Tracking url for the parcel delivery.

MenuSection.name: MenuSection
MenuSection.help: A sub-grouping of food or drink items in a menu. E.g. courses (such as 'Dinner', 'Breakfast', etc.), specific type of dishes (such as 'Meat', 'Vegan', 'Drinks', etc.), or some other classification made by the menu provider.

inputs.name: hasMenuItem
inputs.label: Has Menu Item
inputs.help: A food or drink item contained in a menu or menu section.

inputs.name: hasMenuSection
inputs.label: Has Menu Section
inputs.help: A subgrouping of the menu (by dishes, course, serving time period, etc.).

inputs.name: hasDigitalDocumentPermission
inputs.label: Has Digital Document Permission
inputs.help: A permission related to the access to this document (e.g. permission to read or write an electronic document). For a public document, specify a grantee with an Audience with audienceType equal to "public".

PreventionIndication.name: PreventionIndication
PreventionIndication.help: An indication for preventing an underlying condition, symptom, etc.

CreativeWork.name: CreativeWork
CreativeWork.help: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.

inputs.name: about
inputs.label: About
inputs.help: The subject matter of the content.

inputs.name: abstract
inputs.label: Abstract
inputs.help: An abstract is a short description that summarizes a [[CreativeWork]].

inputs.name: accessMode
inputs.label: Access Mode
inputs.help: The human sensory perceptual system or cognitive faculty through which a person may process or perceive information. Values should be drawn from the [approved vocabulary](https://www.w3.org/2021/a11y-discov-vocab/latest/#accessMode-vocabulary).

inputs.name: accessModeSufficient
inputs.label: Access Mode Sufficient
inputs.help: A list of single or combined accessModes that are sufficient to understand all the intellectual content of a resource. Values should be drawn from the [approved vocabulary](https://www.w3.org/2021/a11y-discov-vocab/latest/#accessModeSufficient-vocabulary).

inputs.name: accessibilityAPI
inputs.label: Accessibility API
inputs.help: Indicates that the resource is compatible with the referenced accessibility API. Values should be drawn from the [approved vocabulary](https://www.w3.org/2021/a11y-discov-vocab/latest/#accessibilityAPI-vocabulary).

inputs.name: accessibilityControl
inputs.label: Accessibility Control
inputs.help: Identifies input methods that are sufficient to fully control the described resource. Values should be drawn from the [approved vocabulary](https://www.w3.org/2021/a11y-discov-vocab/latest/#accessibilityControl-vocabulary).

inputs.name: accessibilityFeature
inputs.label: Accessibility Feature
inputs.help: Content features of the resource, such as accessible media, alternatives and supported enhancements for accessibility. Values should be drawn from the [approved vocabulary](https://www.w3.org/2021/a11y-discov-vocab/latest/#accessibilityFeature-vocabulary).

inputs.name: accessibilityHazard
inputs.label: Accessibility Hazard
inputs.help: A characteristic of the described resource that is physiologically dangerous to some users. Related to WCAG 2.0 guideline 2.3. Values should be drawn from the [approved vocabulary](https://www.w3.org/2021/a11y-discov-vocab/latest/#accessibilityHazard-vocabulary).

inputs.name: accessibilitySummary
inputs.label: Accessibility Summary
inputs.help: A human-readable summary of specific accessibility features or deficiencies, consistent with the other accessibility metadata but expressing subtleties such as "short descriptions are present but long descriptions will be needed for non-visual users" or "short descriptions are present and no long descriptions are needed".

inputs.name: accountablePerson
inputs.label: Accountable Person
inputs.help: Specifies the Person that is legally accountable for the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: acquireLicensePage
inputs.label: Acquire License Page
inputs.help: Indicates a page documenting how licenses can be purchased or otherwise acquired, for the current item.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.label: Aggregate Rating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: alternativeHeadline
inputs.label: Alternative Headline
inputs.help: A secondary title of the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: annotator
inputs.label: Annotator
inputs.help: The participant produced an annotation of this or a related resource.

inputs.name: archivedAt
inputs.label: Archived At
inputs.help: Indicates a page or other link involved in archival of a [[CreativeWork]]. In the case of [[MediaReview]], the items in a [[MediaReviewItem]] may often become inaccessible, but be archived by archival, journalistic, activist, or law enforcement organizations. In such cases, the referenced page may not directly publish the content.

inputs.name: assesses
inputs.label: Assesses
inputs.help: The item being described is intended to assess the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

inputs.name: associatedMedia
inputs.label: Associated Media
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

inputs.name: audience
inputs.label: Audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: audio
inputs.label: Audio
inputs.help: An embedded audio object.

inputs.name: author
inputs.label: Author
inputs.help: The author of this content or rating. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.

inputs.name: author
inputs.label: Author
inputs.help: The participant contributed original writings to the resource.

inputs.name: award
inputs.label: Award
inputs.help: An award won by or for this item.

inputs.name: awards
inputs.label: Awards
inputs.help: Awards won by or for this item.

inputs.name: character
inputs.label: Character
inputs.help: Fictional person connected with a creative work.

inputs.name: citation
inputs.label: Citation
inputs.help: A citation or reference to another creative work, such as another publication, web page, scholarly article, etc.

inputs.name: comment
inputs.label: Comment
inputs.help: Comments, typically from users.

inputs.name: commentCount
inputs.label: Comment Count
inputs.help: The number of comments this CreativeWork (e.g. Article, Question or Answer) has received. This is most applicable to works published in Web sites with commenting system; additional comments may exist elsewhere.

inputs.name: compiler
inputs.label: Compiler
inputs.help: The participant is responsible for collecting the sub-parts of the resource together.

inputs.name: conditionsOfAccess
inputs.label: Conditions Of Access
inputs.help: Conditions that affect the availability of, or method(s) of access to, an item. Typically used for real world items such as an [[ArchiveComponent]] held by an [[ArchiveOrganization]]. This property is not suitable for use as a general Web access control mechanism. It is expressed only in natural language.\n\nFor example "Available by appointment from the Reading Room" or "Accessible only from logged-in accounts ".

inputs.name: consultant
inputs.label: Consultant
inputs.help: The participant contributes expertise to the creation of a work.

inputs.name: contentLocation
inputs.label: Content Location
inputs.help: The location depicted or described in the content. For example, the location in a photograph or painting.

inputs.name: contentRating
inputs.label: Content Rating
inputs.help: Official rating of a piece of content—for example, 'MPAA PG-13'.

inputs.name: contentReferenceTime
inputs.label: Content Reference Time
inputs.help: The specific time described by a creative work, for works (e.g. articles, video objects etc.) that emphasise a particular moment within an Event.

inputs.name: contributor
inputs.label: Contributor
inputs.help: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

inputs.name: copyrightHolder
inputs.label: Copyright Holder
inputs.help: The party holding the legal copyright to the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: copyrightNotice
inputs.label: Copyright Notice
inputs.help: Text of a notice appropriate for describing the copyright aspects of this Creative Work, ideally indicating the owner of the copyright for the Work.

inputs.name: copyrightYear
inputs.label: Copyright Year
inputs.help: The year during which the claimed copyright for the CreativeWork was first asserted.

inputs.name: correction
inputs.label: Correction
inputs.help: Indicates a correction to a [[CreativeWork]], either via a [[CorrectionComment]], textually or in another document.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.label: Country Of Origin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: creativeWorkStatus
inputs.label: Creative Work Status
inputs.help: The status of a creative work in terms of its stage in a lifecycle. Example terms include Incomplete, Draft, Published, Obsolete. Some organizations define a set of terms for the stages of their publication lifecycle.

inputs.name: creator
inputs.label: Creator
inputs.help: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

inputs.name: creditText
inputs.label: Credit Text
inputs.help: Text that can be used to credit person(s) and/or organization(s) associated with a published Creative Work.

inputs.name: data_inputter
inputs.label: Data Inputter
inputs.help: The participant was responsible for entering, re-typing, and/or structuring the data contained in the resource.

inputs.name: dateCreated
inputs.label: Date Created
inputs.help: The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.

inputs.name: dateModified
inputs.label: Date Modified
inputs.help: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified or when the item's entry was modified within a DataFeed.

inputs.name: datePublished
inputs.label: Date Published
inputs.help: Date of first publication or broadcast. For example the date a [[CreativeWork]] was broadcast or a [[Certification]] was issued.

inputs.name: depositor
inputs.label: Depositor
inputs.help: The participant was responsible for depositing the resource in an archive.

inputs.name: developer
inputs.label: Developer
inputs.help: The participant developed the methodology or tools that constitute the resource, or that were used to create the resource.

inputs.name: digitalSourceType
inputs.label: Digital Source Type
inputs.help: Indicates an IPTCDigitalSourceEnumeration code indicating the nature of the digital source(s) for some [[CreativeWork]].

inputs.name: discussionUrl
inputs.label: Discussion Url
inputs.help: A link to the page containing the comments of the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: editEIDR
inputs.label: Edit EIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing a specific edit / edition for a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" whose [[titleEIDR]] is "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J" has several edits, e.g. "10.5240/1F2A-E1C5-680A-14C6-E76B-I" and "10.5240/8A35-3BEE-6497-5D12-9E4F-3".

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]] and [[TVEpisode]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

inputs.name: editor
inputs.label: Editor
inputs.help: Specifies the Person who edited the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: editor
inputs.label: Editor
inputs.help: The participant reviewed, corrected, and/or tested the resource.

inputs.name: educationalAlignment
inputs.label: Educational Alignment
inputs.help:
An alignment to an established educational framework.

This property should not be used where the nature of the alignment can be described using a simple property, for example to express that a resource [[teaches]] or [[assesses]] a competency.

inputs.name: educationalLevel
inputs.label: Educational Level
inputs.help: The level in terms of progression through an educational or training context. Examples of educational levels include 'beginner', 'intermediate' or 'advanced', and formal sets of level indicators.

inputs.name: educationalUse
inputs.label: Educational Use
inputs.help: The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.

inputs.name: encoding
inputs.label: Encoding
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for associatedMedia.

inputs.name: encodingFormat
inputs.label: Encoding Format
inputs.help:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml) and [MDN reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types)), e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.

In cases where a [[CreativeWork]] has several media type representations, [[encoding]] can be used to indicate each [[MediaObject]] alongside particular [[encodingFormat]] information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

inputs.name: encodings
inputs.label: Encodings
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork.

inputs.name: exampleOfWork
inputs.label: Example Of Work
inputs.help: A creative work that this work is an example/instance/realization/derivation of.

inputs.name: expires
inputs.label: Expires
inputs.help: Date the content expires and is no longer useful or available. For example a [[VideoObject]] or [[NewsArticle]] whose availability or relevance is time-limited, a [[ClaimReview]] fact check whose publisher wants to indicate that it may no longer be relevant (or helpful to highlight) after some date, or a [[Certification]] the validity has expired.

inputs.name: fileFormat
inputs.label: File Format
inputs.help: Media type, typically MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml)) of the content, e.g. application/zip of a SoftwareApplication binary. In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, 'encoding' can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular fileFormat information. Unregistered or niche file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia entry.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.label: Funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inputs.name: funding
inputs.label: Funding
inputs.help: A [[Grant]] that directly or indirectly provide funding or sponsorship for this item. See also [[ownershipFundingInfo]].

inputs.name: genre
inputs.label: Genre
inputs.help: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

inputs.name: hasPart
inputs.label: Has Part
inputs.help: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that is part of this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense).

inputs.name: headline
inputs.label: Headline
inputs.help: Headline of the article.

inputs.name: illustrator
inputs.label: Illustrator
inputs.help: The participant contributed drawings or other illustrations to the resource.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.label: In Language
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: interactionStatistic
inputs.label: Interaction Statistic
inputs.help: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication. The most specific child type of InteractionCounter should be used.

inputs.name: interactivityType
inputs.label: Interactivity Type
inputs.help: The predominant mode of learning supported by the learning resource. Acceptable values are 'active', 'expositive', or 'mixed'.

inputs.name: interpretedAsClaim
inputs.label: Interpreted As Claim
inputs.help: Used to indicate a specific claim contained, implied, translated or refined from the content of a [[MediaObject]] or other [[CreativeWork]]. The interpreting party can be indicated using [[claimInterpreter]].

inputs.name: interpreter
inputs.label: Interpreter
inputs.help: The participant translates in real-time or explains the discourse recorded in the resource.

inputs.name: interviewer
inputs.label: Interviewer
inputs.help: The participant conducted an interview that forms part of the resource.

inputs.name: isAccessibleForFree
inputs.label: Is Accessible For Free
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

inputs.name: isBasedOn
inputs.label: Is Based On
inputs.help: A resource from which this work is derived or from which it is a modification or adaptation.

inputs.name: isBasedOnUrl
inputs.label: Is Based On Url
inputs.help: A resource that was used in the creation of this resource. This term can be repeated for multiple sources. For example, http://example.com/great-multiplication-intro.html.

inputs.name: isFamilyFriendly
inputs.label: Is Family Friendly
inputs.help: Indicates whether this content is family friendly.

inputs.name: isPartOf
inputs.label: Is Part Of
inputs.help: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense), is part of.

inputs.name: keywords
inputs.label: Keywords
inputs.help: Keywords or tags used to describe some item. Multiple textual entries in a keywords list are typically delimited by commas, or by repeating the property.

inputs.name: learningResourceType
inputs.label: Learning Resource Type
inputs.help: The predominant type or kind characterizing the learning resource. For example, 'presentation', 'handout'.

inputs.name: license
inputs.label: License
inputs.help: A license document that applies to this content, typically indicated by URL.

inputs.name: locationCreated
inputs.label: Location Created
inputs.help: The location where the CreativeWork was created, which may not be the same as the location depicted in the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: mainEntity
inputs.label: Main Entity
inputs.help: Indicates the primary entity described in some page or other CreativeWork.

inputs.name: maintainer
inputs.label: Maintainer
inputs.help: A maintainer of a [[Dataset]], software package ([[SoftwareApplication]]), or other [[Project]]. A maintainer is a [[Person]] or [[Organization]] that manages contributions to, and/or publication of, some (typically complex) artifact. It is common for distributions of software and data to be based on "upstream" sources. When [[maintainer]] is applied to a specific version of something e.g. a particular version or packaging of a [[Dataset]], it is always  possible that the upstream source has a different maintainer. The [[isBasedOn]] property can be used to indicate such relationships between datasets to make the different maintenance roles clear. Similarly in the case of software, a package may have dedicated maintainers working on integration into software distributions such as Ubuntu, as well as upstream maintainers of the underlying work.

inputs.name: material
inputs.label: Material
inputs.help: A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.

inputs.name: materialExtent
inputs.label: Material Extent
inputs.help: The quantity of the materials being described or an expression of the physical space they occupy.

inputs.name: mentions
inputs.label: Mentions
inputs.help: Indicates that the CreativeWork contains a reference to, but is not necessarily about a concept.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.label: Offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: participant
inputs.label: Participant
inputs.help: The participant was present during the creation of the resource, but did not contribute substantially to its content.

inputs.name: pattern
inputs.label: Pattern
inputs.help: A pattern that something has, for example 'polka dot', 'striped', 'Canadian flag'. Values are typically expressed as text, although links to controlled value schemes are also supported.

inputs.name: performer
inputs.label: Performer
inputs.help: The participant performed some portion of a recorded, filmed, or transcribed resource.

inputs.name: photographer
inputs.label: Photographer
inputs.help: The participant took the photograph, or shot the film, that appears in or constitutes the resource.

inputs.name: position
inputs.label: Position
inputs.help: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

inputs.name: producer
inputs.label: Producer
inputs.help: The person or organization who produced the work (e.g. music album, movie, TV/radio series etc.).

inputs.name: provider
inputs.label: Provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: publication
inputs.label: Publication
inputs.help: A publication event associated with the item.

inputs.name: publisher
inputs.label: Publisher
inputs.help: The publisher of the creative work.

inputs.name: publisherImprint
inputs.label: Publisher Imprint
inputs.help: The publishing division which published the comic.

inputs.name: publishingPrinciples
inputs.label: Publishing Principles
inputs.help:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via [[URL]]) a document describing the editorial principles of an [[Organization]] (or individual, e.g. a [[Person]] writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a [[CreativeWork]] (e.g. [[NewsArticle]]) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the [[CreativeWork]].

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a [[funder]]) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

inputs.name: recordedAt
inputs.label: Recorded At
inputs.help: The Event where the CreativeWork was recorded. The CreativeWork may capture all or part of the event.

inputs.name: recorder
inputs.label: Recorder
inputs.help: The participant operated the recording machinery used to create the resource.

inputs.name: releasedEvent
inputs.label: Released Event
inputs.help: The place and time the release was issued, expressed as a PublicationEvent.

inputs.name: research_participant
inputs.label: Research Participant
inputs.help: The participant acted as a research subject or responded to a questionnaire, the results of which study form the basis of the resource.

inputs.name: researcher
inputs.label: Researcher
inputs.help: The resource was created as part of the participant's research, or the research presents interim or final results from the participant's research.

inputs.name: responder
inputs.label: Responder
inputs.help: The participant was an interlocutor in some sort of discourse event.

inputs.name: review
inputs.label: Review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: reviews
inputs.label: Reviews
inputs.help: Review of the item.

inputs.name: schemaVersion
inputs.label: Schema Version
inputs.help:
Indicates (by URL or string) a particular version of a schema used in some CreativeWork. This property was created primarily to
    indicate the use of a specific schema.org release, e.g. ```10.0``` as a simple string, or more explicitly via URL, ```http://schema.org/docs/releases.html#v10.0```. There may be situations in which other schemas might usefully be referenced this way, e.g. ```http://dublincore.org/specifications/dublin-core/dces/1999-07-02/``` but this has not been carefully explored in the community.

inputs.name: sdDatePublished
inputs.label: Sd Date Published
inputs.help: Indicates the date on which the current structured data was generated / published. Typically used alongside [[sdPublisher]].

inputs.name: sdLicense
inputs.label: Sd License
inputs.help: A license document that applies to this structured data, typically indicated by URL.

inputs.name: sdPublisher
inputs.label: Sd Publisher
inputs.help:
Indicates the party responsible for generating and publishing the current structured data markup, typically in cases where the structured data is derived automatically from existing published content but published on a different site. For example, student projects and open data initiatives often re-publish existing content with more explicitly structured metadata. The
[[sdPublisher]] property helps make such practices more explicit.

inputs.name: signer
inputs.label: Signer
inputs.help: The participant was a principal signer in a resource that consists of a recording, a film, or a transcription of a recorded resource.

inputs.name: singer
inputs.label: Singer
inputs.help: The participant sang, either individually or as part of a group, in a resource that consists of a recording, a film, or a transcription of a recorded resource.

inputs.name: size
inputs.label: Size
inputs.help: A standardized size of a product or creative work, specified either through a simple textual string (for example 'XL', '32Wx34L'), a  QuantitativeValue with a unitCode, or a comprehensive and structured [[SizeSpecification]]; in other cases, the [[width]], [[height]], [[depth]] and [[weight]] properties may be more applicable.

inputs.name: sourceOrganization
inputs.label: Source Organization
inputs.help: The Organization on whose behalf the creator was working.

inputs.name: spatial
inputs.label: Spatial
inputs.help:
The "spatial" property can be used in cases when more specific properties
(e.g. [[locationCreated]], [[spatialCoverage]], [[contentLocation]]) are not known to be appropriate.

inputs.name: spatialCoverage
inputs.label: Spatial Coverage
inputs.help:
The spatialCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the place(s) which are the focus of the content. It is a subproperty of
      contentLocation intended primarily for more technical and detailed materials. For example with a Dataset, it indicates
      areas that the dataset describes: a dataset of New York weather would have spatialCoverage which was the place: the state of New York.

inputs.name: speaker
inputs.label: Speaker
inputs.help: The participant was a principal speaker in a resource that consists of a recording, a film, or a transcription of a recorded resource.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.label: Sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. E.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.label: Sponsor
inputs.help: The participant contributed financial support to the creation of the resource.

inputs.name: teaches
inputs.label: Teaches
inputs.help: The item being described is intended to help a person learn the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

inputs.name: temporal
inputs.label: Temporal
inputs.help:
The "temporal" property can be used in cases where more specific properties
(e.g. [[temporalCoverage]], [[dateCreated]], [[dateModified]], [[datePublished]]) are not known to be appropriate.

inputs.name: temporalCoverage
inputs.label: Temporal Coverage
inputs.help:
The temporalCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the period that the content applies to, i.e. that it describes, either as a DateTime or as a textual string indicating a time period in [ISO 8601 time interval format](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601#Time_intervals). In
      the case of a Dataset it will typically indicate the relevant time period in a precise notation (e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 would be written "2011/2012"). Other forms of content, e.g. ScholarlyArticle, Book, TVSeries or TVEpisode, may indicate their temporalCoverage in broader terms - textually or via well-known URL.
      Written works such as books may sometimes have precise temporal coverage too, e.g. a work set in 1939 - 1945 can be indicated in ISO 8601 interval format format via "1939/1945".

Open-ended date ranges can be written with ".." in place of the end date. For example, "2015-11/.." indicates a range beginning in November 2015 and with no specified final date. This is tentative and might be updated in future when ISO 8601 is officially updated.

inputs.name: text
inputs.label: Text
inputs.help: The textual content of this CreativeWork.

inputs.name: thumbnail
inputs.label: Thumbnail
inputs.help: Thumbnail image for an image or video.

inputs.name: thumbnailUrl
inputs.label: Thumbnail Url
inputs.help: A thumbnail image relevant to the Thing.

inputs.name: timeRequired
inputs.label: Time Required
inputs.help: Approximate or typical time it usually takes to work with or through the content of this work for the typical or target audience.

inputs.name: transcriber
inputs.label: Transcriber
inputs.help: The participant produced a transcription of this or a related resource.

inputs.name: translationOfWork
inputs.label: Translation Of Work
inputs.help: The work that this work has been translated from. E.g. 物种起源 is a translationOf “On the Origin of Species”.

inputs.name: translator
inputs.label: Translator
inputs.help: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.

inputs.name: translator
inputs.label: Translator
inputs.help: The participant produced a translation of this or a related resource.

inputs.name: typicalAgeRange
inputs.label: Typical Age Range
inputs.help: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

inputs.name: usageInfo
inputs.label: Usage Info
inputs.help:
The schema.org [[usageInfo]] property indicates further information about a [[CreativeWork]]. This property is applicable both to works that are freely available and to those that require payment or other transactions. It can reference additional information, e.g. community expectations on preferred linking and citation conventions, as well as purchasing details. For something that can be commercially licensed, usageInfo can provide detailed, resource-specific information about licensing options.

This property can be used alongside the license property which indicates license(s) applicable to some piece of content. The usageInfo property can provide information about other licensing options, e.g. acquiring commercial usage rights for an image that is also available under non-commercial creative commons licenses.

inputs.name: version
inputs.label: Version
inputs.help: The version of the CreativeWork embodied by a specified resource.

inputs.name: video
inputs.label: Video
inputs.help: An embedded video object.

inputs.name: workExample
inputs.label: Work Example
inputs.help: Example/instance/realization/derivation of the concept of this creative work. E.g. the paperback edition, first edition, or e-book.

inputs.name: workTranslation
inputs.label: Work Translation
inputs.help: A work that is a translation of the content of this work. E.g. 西遊記 has an English workTranslation “Journey to the West”, a German workTranslation “Monkeys Pilgerfahrt” and a Vietnamese  translation Tây du ký bình khảo.

LocationFeatureSpecification.name: LocationFeatureSpecification
LocationFeatureSpecification.help: Specifies a location feature by providing a structured value representing a feature of an accommodation as a property-value pair of varying degrees of formality.

inputs.name: hoursAvailable
inputs.label: Hours Available
inputs.help: The hours during which this service or contact is available.

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.label: Valid From
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.label: Valid Through
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

HowToTool.name: HowToTool
HowToTool.help: A tool used (but not consumed) when performing instructions for how to achieve a result.

HealthTopicContent.name: HealthTopicContent
HealthTopicContent.help: [[HealthTopicContent]] is [[WebContent]] that is about some aspect of a health topic, e.g. a condition, its symptoms or treatments. Such content may be comprised of several parts or sections and use different types of media. Multiple instances of [[WebContent]] (and hence [[HealthTopicContent]]) can be related using [[hasPart]] / [[isPartOf]] where there is some kind of content hierarchy, and their content described with [[about]] and [[mentions]] e.g. building upon the existing [[MedicalCondition]] vocabulary.

inputs.name: hasHealthAspect
inputs.label: Has Health Aspect
inputs.help: Indicates the aspect or aspects specifically addressed in some [[HealthTopicContent]]. For example, that the content is an overview, or that it talks about treatment, self-care, treatments or their side-effects.

HVACBusiness.name: HVACBusiness
HVACBusiness.help: A business that provides Heating, Ventilation and Air Conditioning services.

AggregateRating.name: AggregateRating
AggregateRating.help: The average rating based on multiple ratings or reviews.

inputs.name: itemReviewed
inputs.label: Item Reviewed
inputs.help: The item that is being reviewed/rated.

inputs.name: ratingCount
inputs.label: Rating Count
inputs.help: The count of total number of ratings.

inputs.name: reviewCount
inputs.label: Review Count
inputs.help: The count of total number of reviews.

MonetaryAmountDistribution.name: MonetaryAmountDistribution
MonetaryAmountDistribution.help: A statistical distribution of monetary amounts.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.label: Currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217), e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies, e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Trading Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types, e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

BookFormatType.name: BookFormatType
BookFormatType.help: The publication format of the book.

ReviewNewsArticle.name: ReviewNewsArticle
ReviewNewsArticle.help: A [[NewsArticle]] and [[CriticReview]] providing a professional critic's assessment of a service, product, performance, or artistic or literary work.

ProductModel.name: ProductModel
ProductModel.help: A datasheet or vendor specification of a product (in the sense of a prototypical description).

inputs.name: isVariantOf
inputs.label: Is Variant Of
inputs.help: Indicates the kind of product that this is a variant of. In the case of [[ProductModel]], this is a pointer (from a ProductModel) to a base product from which this product is a variant. It is safe to infer that the variant inherits all product features from the base model, unless defined locally. This is not transitive. In the case of a [[ProductGroup]], the group description also serves as a template, representing a set of Products that vary on explicitly defined, specific dimensions only (so it defines both a set of variants, as well as which values distinguish amongst those variants). When used with [[ProductGroup]], this property can apply to any [[Product]] included in the group.

inputs.name: predecessorOf
inputs.label: Predecessor Of
inputs.help: A pointer from a previous, often discontinued variant of the product to its newer variant.

inputs.name: successorOf
inputs.label: Successor Of
inputs.help: A pointer from a newer variant of a product  to its previous, often discontinued predecessor.

Event.name: Event
Event.help: An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the [[offers]] property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.

inputs.name: about
inputs.label: About
inputs.help: The subject matter of the content.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.label: Actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.label: Aggregate Rating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: attendee
inputs.label: Attendee
inputs.help: A person or organization attending the event.

inputs.name: attendees
inputs.label: Attendees
inputs.help: A person attending the event.

inputs.name: audience
inputs.label: Audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: composer
inputs.label: Composer
inputs.help: The person or organization who wrote a composition, or who is the composer of a work performed at some event.

inputs.name: contributor
inputs.label: Contributor
inputs.help: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

inputs.name: director
inputs.label: Director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: doorTime
inputs.label: Door Time
inputs.help: The time admission will commence.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.label: Duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.label: End Date
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: eventAttendanceMode
inputs.label: Event Attendance Mode
inputs.help: The eventAttendanceMode of an event indicates whether it occurs online, offline, or a mix.

inputs.name: eventSchedule
inputs.label: Event Schedule
inputs.help:
Associates an [[Event]] with a [[Schedule]]. There are circumstances where it is preferable to share a schedule for a series of
      repeating events rather than data on the individual events themselves. For example, a website or application might prefer to publish a schedule for a weekly
      gym class rather than provide data on every event. A schedule could be processed by applications to add forthcoming events to a calendar. An [[Event]] that
      is associated with a [[Schedule]] using this property should not have [[startDate]] or [[endDate]] properties. These are instead defined within the associated
      [[Schedule]], this avoids any ambiguity for clients using the data. The property might have repeated values to specify different schedules, e.g. for different months
      or seasons.

inputs.name: eventStatus
inputs.label: Event Status
inputs.help: An eventStatus of an event represents its status; particularly useful when an event is cancelled or rescheduled.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.label: Funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inputs.name: funding
inputs.label: Funding
inputs.help: A [[Grant]] that directly or indirectly provide funding or sponsorship for this item. See also [[ownershipFundingInfo]].

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.label: In Language
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: isAccessibleForFree
inputs.label: Is Accessible For Free
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

inputs.name: keywords
inputs.label: Keywords
inputs.help: Keywords or tags used to describe some item. Multiple textual entries in a keywords list are typically delimited by commas, or by repeating the property.

inputs.name: location
inputs.label: Location
inputs.help: The location of, for example, where an event is happening, where an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

inputs.name: maximumAttendeeCapacity
inputs.label: Maximum Attendee Capacity
inputs.help: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.

inputs.name: maximumPhysicalAttendeeCapacity
inputs.label: Maximum Physical Attendee Capacity
inputs.help: The maximum physical attendee capacity of an [[Event]] whose [[eventAttendanceMode]] is [[OfflineEventAttendanceMode]] (or the offline aspects, in the case of a [[MixedEventAttendanceMode]]).

inputs.name: maximumVirtualAttendeeCapacity
inputs.label: Maximum Virtual Attendee Capacity
inputs.help: The maximum virtual attendee capacity of an [[Event]] whose [[eventAttendanceMode]] is [[OnlineEventAttendanceMode]] (or the online aspects, in the case of a [[MixedEventAttendanceMode]]).

inputs.name: offers
inputs.label: Offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: organizer
inputs.label: Organizer
inputs.help: An organizer of an Event.

inputs.name: performer
inputs.label: Performer
inputs.help: A performer at the event—for example, a presenter, musician, musical group or actor.

inputs.name: performers
inputs.label: Performers
inputs.help: The main performer or performers of the event—for example, a presenter, musician, or actor.

inputs.name: previousStartDate
inputs.label: Previous Start Date
inputs.help: Used in conjunction with eventStatus for rescheduled or cancelled events. This property contains the previously scheduled start date. For rescheduled events, the startDate property should be used for the newly scheduled start date. In the (rare) case of an event that has been postponed and rescheduled multiple times, this field may be repeated.

inputs.name: recordedIn
inputs.label: Recorded In
inputs.help: The CreativeWork that captured all or part of this Event.

inputs.name: remainingAttendeeCapacity
inputs.label: Remaining Attendee Capacity
inputs.help: The number of attendee places for an event that remain unallocated.

inputs.name: review
inputs.label: Review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.label: Sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. E.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.label: Start Date
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: subEvent
inputs.label: Sub Event
inputs.help: An Event that is part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each of which is a subEvent of the conference.

inputs.name: subEvents
inputs.label: Sub Events
inputs.help: Events that are a part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each subEvents of the conference.

inputs.name: superEvent
inputs.label: Super Event
inputs.help: An event that this event is a part of. For example, a collection of individual music performances might each have a music festival as their superEvent.

inputs.name: translator
inputs.label: Translator
inputs.help: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.

inputs.name: typicalAgeRange
inputs.label: Typical Age Range
inputs.help: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

inputs.name: workFeatured
inputs.label: Work Featured
inputs.help:
A work featured in some event, e.g. exhibited in an ExhibitionEvent.
       Specific subproperties are available for workPerformed (e.g. a play), or a workPresented (a Movie at a ScreeningEvent).

inputs.name: workPerformed
inputs.label: Work Performed
inputs.help: A work performed in some event, for example a play performed in a TheaterEvent.

ProductGroup.name: ProductGroup
ProductGroup.help:
A ProductGroup represents a group of [[Product]]s that vary only in certain well-described ways, such as by [[size]], [[color]], [[material]] etc.

While a ProductGroup itself is not directly offered for sale, the various varying products that it represents can be. The ProductGroup serves as a prototype or template, standing in for all of the products who have an [[isVariantOf]] relationship to it. As such, properties (including additional types) can be applied to the ProductGroup to represent characteristics shared by each of the (possibly very many) variants. Properties that reference a ProductGroup are not included in this mechanism; neither are the following specific properties [[variesBy]], [[hasVariant]], [[url]].

inputs.name: hasVariant
inputs.label: Has Variant
inputs.help: Indicates a [[Product]] that is a member of this [[ProductGroup]] (or [[ProductModel]]).

inputs.name: productGroupID
inputs.label: Product Group ID
inputs.help: Indicates a textual identifier for a ProductGroup.

inputs.name: variesBy
inputs.label: Varies By
inputs.help: Indicates the property or properties by which the variants in a [[ProductGroup]] vary, e.g. their size, color etc. Schema.org properties can be referenced by their short name e.g. "color"; terms defined elsewhere can be referenced with their URIs.

Claim.name: Claim
Claim.help:
A [[Claim]] in Schema.org represents a specific, factually-oriented claim that could be the [[itemReviewed]] in a [[ClaimReview]]. The content of a claim can be summarized with the [[text]] property. Variations on well known claims can have their common identity indicated via [[sameAs]] links, and summarized with a [[name]]. Ideally, a [[Claim]] description includes enough contextual information to minimize the risk of ambiguity or inclarity. In practice, many claims are better understood in the context in which they appear or the interpretations provided by claim reviews.

  Beyond [[ClaimReview]], the Claim type can be associated with related creative works - for example a [[ScholarlyArticle]] or [[Question]] might be [[about]] some [[Claim]].

  At this time, Schema.org does not define any types of relationship between claims. This is a natural area for future exploration.

inputs.name: appearance
inputs.label: Appearance
inputs.help: Indicates an occurrence of a [[Claim]] in some [[CreativeWork]].

inputs.name: claimInterpreter
inputs.label: Claim Interpreter
inputs.help: For a [[Claim]] interpreted from [[MediaObject]] content, the [[interpretedAsClaim]] property can be used to indicate a claim contained, implied or refined from the content of a [[MediaObject]].

inputs.name: firstAppearance
inputs.label: First Appearance
inputs.help: Indicates the first known occurrence of a [[Claim]] in some [[CreativeWork]].

DietarySupplement.name: DietarySupplement
DietarySupplement.help: A product taken by mouth that contains a dietary ingredient intended to supplement the diet. Dietary ingredients may include vitamins, minerals, herbs or other botanicals, amino acids, and substances such as enzymes, organ tissues, glandulars and metabolites.

inputs.name: activeIngredient
inputs.label: Active Ingredient
inputs.help: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

inputs.name: isProprietary
inputs.label: Is Proprietary
inputs.help: True if this item's name is a proprietary/brand name (vs. generic name).

inputs.name: legalStatus
inputs.label: Legal Status
inputs.help: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

inputs.name: maximumIntake
inputs.label: Maximum Intake
inputs.help: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

inputs.name: mechanismOfAction
inputs.label: Mechanism Of Action
inputs.help: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.

inputs.name: nonProprietaryName
inputs.label: Non Proprietary Name
inputs.help: The generic name of this drug or supplement.

inputs.name: proprietaryName
inputs.label: Proprietary Name
inputs.help: Proprietary name given to the diet plan, typically by its originator or creator.

inputs.name: recommendedIntake
inputs.label: Recommended Intake
inputs.help: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

inputs.name: safetyConsideration
inputs.label: Safety Consideration
inputs.help: Any potential safety concern associated with the supplement. May include interactions with other drugs and foods, pregnancy, breastfeeding, known adverse reactions, and documented efficacy of the supplement.

inputs.name: targetPopulation
inputs.label: Target Population
inputs.help: Characteristics of the population for which this is intended, or which typically uses it, e.g. 'adults'.

TrainTrip.name: TrainTrip
TrainTrip.help: A trip on a commercial train line.

inputs.name: arrivalPlatform
inputs.label: Arrival Platform
inputs.help: The platform where the train arrives.

inputs.name: arrivalStation
inputs.label: Arrival Station
inputs.help: The station where the train trip ends.

inputs.name: departurePlatform
inputs.label: Departure Platform
inputs.help: The platform from which the train departs.

inputs.name: departureStation
inputs.label: Departure Station
inputs.help: The station from which the train departs.

inputs.name: trainName
inputs.label: Train Name
inputs.help: The name of the train (e.g. The Orient Express).

inputs.name: trainNumber
inputs.label: Train Number
inputs.help: The unique identifier for the train.

VideoGameClip.name: VideoGameClip
VideoGameClip.help: A short segment/part of a video game.

FloorPlan.name: FloorPlan
FloorPlan.help: A FloorPlan is an explicit representation of a collection of similar accommodations, allowing the provision of common information (room counts, sizes, layout diagrams) and offers for rental or sale. In typical use, some [[ApartmentComplex]] has an [[accommodationFloorPlan]] which is a [[FloorPlan]].  A FloorPlan is always in the context of a particular place, either a larger [[ApartmentComplex]] or a single [[Apartment]]. The visual/spatial aspects of a floor plan (i.e. room layout, [see wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floor_plan)) can be indicated using [[image]].

inputs.name: amenityFeature
inputs.label: Amenity Feature
inputs.help: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

inputs.name: floorSize
inputs.label: Floor Size
inputs.help:
The size of the accommodation, e.g. in square meter or squarefoot.
Typical unit code(s): MTK for square meter, FTK for square foot, or YDK for square yard.

inputs.name: isPlanForApartment
inputs.label: Is Plan For Apartment
inputs.help: Indicates some accommodation that this floor plan describes.

inputs.name: layoutImage
inputs.label: Layout Image
inputs.help: A schematic image showing the floorplan layout.

inputs.name: numberOfAccommodationUnits
inputs.label: Number Of Accommodation Units
inputs.help: Indicates the total (available plus unavailable) number of accommodation units in an [[ApartmentComplex]], or the number of accommodation units for a specific [[FloorPlan]] (within its specific [[ApartmentComplex]]). See also [[numberOfAvailableAccommodationUnits]].

inputs.name: numberOfAvailableAccommodationUnits
inputs.label: Number Of Available Accommodation Units
inputs.help: Indicates the number of available accommodation units in an [[ApartmentComplex]], or the number of accommodation units for a specific [[FloorPlan]] (within its specific [[ApartmentComplex]]). See also [[numberOfAccommodationUnits]].

inputs.name: numberOfBathroomsTotal
inputs.label: Number Of Bathrooms Total
inputs.help: The total integer number of bathrooms in some [[Accommodation]], following real estate conventions as [documented in RESO](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/BathroomsTotalInteger+Field): "The simple sum of the number of bathrooms. For example for a property with two Full Bathrooms and one Half Bathroom, the Bathrooms Total Integer will be 3.". See also [[numberOfRooms]].

inputs.name: numberOfBedrooms
inputs.label: Number Of Bedrooms
inputs.help: The total integer number of bedrooms in a some [[Accommodation]], [[ApartmentComplex]] or [[FloorPlan]].

inputs.name: numberOfFullBathrooms
inputs.label: Number Of Full Bathrooms
inputs.help: Number of full bathrooms - The total number of full and ¾ bathrooms in an [[Accommodation]]. This corresponds to the [BathroomsFull field in RESO](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/BathroomsFull+Field).

inputs.name: numberOfPartialBathrooms
inputs.label: Number Of Partial Bathrooms
inputs.help: Number of partial bathrooms - The total number of half and ¼ bathrooms in an [[Accommodation]]. This corresponds to the [BathroomsPartial field in RESO](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/BathroomsPartial+Field).

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.label: Number Of Rooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: petsAllowed
inputs.label: Pets Allowed
inputs.help: Indicates whether pets are allowed to enter the accommodation or lodging business. More detailed information can be put in a text value.

SearchAction.name: SearchAction
SearchAction.help:
The act of searching for an object.

Related actions:

* [[FindAction]]: SearchAction generally leads to a FindAction, but not necessarily.

inputs.name: query
inputs.label: Query
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The query used on this action.

AskAction.name: AskAction
AskAction.help:
The act of posing a question / favor to someone.

Related actions:

* [[ReplyAction]]: Appears generally as a response to AskAction.

inputs.name: question
inputs.label: Question
inputs.help: A sub property of object. A question.

BookSeries.name: BookSeries
BookSeries.help: A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.

AllocateAction.name: AllocateAction
AllocateAction.help: The act of organizing tasks/objects/events by associating resources to it.

Recipe.name: Recipe
Recipe.help: A recipe. For dietary restrictions covered by the recipe, a few common restrictions are enumerated via [[suitableForDiet]]. The [[keywords]] property can also be used to add more detail.

inputs.name: cookTime
inputs.label: Cook Time
inputs.help: The time it takes to actually cook the dish, in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: cookingMethod
inputs.label: Cooking Method
inputs.help: The method of cooking, such as Frying, Steaming, ...

inputs.name: ingredients
inputs.label: Ingredients
inputs.help: A single ingredient used in the recipe, e.g. sugar, flour or garlic.

inputs.name: nutrition
inputs.label: Nutrition
inputs.help: Nutrition information about the recipe or menu item.

inputs.name: recipeCategory
inputs.label: Recipe Category
inputs.help: The category of the recipe—for example, appetizer, entree, etc.

inputs.name: recipeCuisine
inputs.label: Recipe Cuisine
inputs.help: The cuisine of the recipe (for example, French or Ethiopian).

inputs.name: recipeIngredient
inputs.label: Recipe Ingredient
inputs.help: A single ingredient used in the recipe, e.g. sugar, flour or garlic.

inputs.name: recipeInstructions
inputs.label: Recipe Instructions
inputs.help: A step in making the recipe, in the form of a single item (document, video, etc.) or an ordered list with HowToStep and/or HowToSection items.

inputs.name: recipeYield
inputs.label: Recipe Yield
inputs.help: The quantity produced by the recipe (for example, number of people served, number of servings, etc).

inputs.name: suitableForDiet
inputs.label: Suitable For Diet
inputs.help: Indicates a dietary restriction or guideline for which this recipe or menu item is suitable, e.g. diabetic, halal etc.

PerformanceRole.name: PerformanceRole
PerformanceRole.help: A PerformanceRole is a Role that some entity places with regard to a theatrical performance, e.g. in a Movie, TVSeries etc.

inputs.name: characterName
inputs.label: Character Name
inputs.help: The name of a character played in some acting or performing role, i.e. in a PerformanceRole.

Action.name: Action
Action.help: An action performed by a direct agent and indirect participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies the exact expectation of each argument/role.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/04/announcing-schemaorg-actions.html) and [Actions overview document](http://schema.org/docs/actions.html).

inputs.name: actionStatus
inputs.label: Action Status
inputs.help: Indicates the current disposition of the Action.

inputs.name: agent
inputs.label: Agent
inputs.help: The direct performer or driver of the action (animate or inanimate). E.g. *John* wrote a book.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.label: End Time
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: error
inputs.label: Error
inputs.help: For failed actions, more information on the cause of the failure.

inputs.name: instrument
inputs.label: Instrument
inputs.help: The object that helped the agent perform the action. E.g. John wrote a book with *a pen*.

inputs.name: location
inputs.label: Location
inputs.help: The location of, for example, where an event is happening, where an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

inputs.name: object
inputs.label: Object
inputs.help: The object upon which the action is carried out, whose state is kept intact or changed. Also known as the semantic roles patient, affected or undergoer (which change their state) or theme (which doesn't). E.g. John read *a book*.

inputs.name: participant
inputs.label: Participant
inputs.help: Other co-agents that participated in the action indirectly. E.g. John wrote a book with *Steve*.

inputs.name: provider
inputs.label: Provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: result
inputs.label: Result
inputs.help: The result produced in the action. E.g. John wrote *a book*.

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.label: Start Time
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: target
inputs.label: Target
inputs.help: Indicates a target EntryPoint, or url, for an Action.

ComicStory.name: ComicStory
ComicStory.help:
The term "story" is any indivisible, re-printable
    	unit of a comic, including the interior stories, covers, and backmatter. Most
    	comics have at least two stories: a cover (ComicCoverArt) and an interior story.

inputs.name: artist
inputs.label: Artist
inputs.help:
The primary artist for a work
    	in a medium other than pencils or digital line art--for example, if the
    	primary artwork is done in watercolors or digital paints.

inputs.name: colorist
inputs.label: Colorist
inputs.help: The individual who adds color to inked drawings.

inputs.name: inker
inputs.label: Inker
inputs.help: The individual who traces over the pencil drawings in ink after pencils are complete.

inputs.name: letterer
inputs.label: Letterer
inputs.help: The individual who adds lettering, including speech balloons and sound effects, to artwork.

inputs.name: penciler
inputs.label: Penciler
inputs.help: The individual who draws the primary narrative artwork.

OfferShippingDetails.name: OfferShippingDetails
OfferShippingDetails.help:
OfferShippingDetails represents information about shipping destinations.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping rates for different destinations:

One entity for Alaska/Hawaii. A different one for continental US. A different one for all France.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping costs and delivery times.

Two entities that are identical but differ in rate and time:

E.g. Cheaper and slower: $5 in 5-7 days
or Fast and expensive: $15 in 1-2 days.

inputs.name: deliveryTime
inputs.label: Delivery Time
inputs.help: The total delay between the receipt of the order and the goods reaching the final customer.

inputs.name: depth
inputs.label: Depth
inputs.help: The depth of the item.

inputs.name: doesNotShip
inputs.label: Does Not Ship
inputs.help: Indicates when shipping to a particular [[shippingDestination]] is not available.

inputs.name: height
inputs.label: Height
inputs.help: The height of the item.

inputs.name: shippingDestination
inputs.label: Shipping Destination
inputs.help: indicates (possibly multiple) shipping destinations. These can be defined in several ways, e.g. postalCode ranges.

inputs.name: shippingLabel
inputs.label: Shipping Label
inputs.help: Label to match an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with a [[ShippingRateSettings]] (within the context of a [[shippingSettingsLink]] cross-reference).

inputs.name: shippingOrigin
inputs.label: Shipping Origin
inputs.help: Indicates the origin of a shipment, i.e. where it should be coming from.

inputs.name: shippingRate
inputs.label: Shipping Rate
inputs.help: The shipping rate is the cost of shipping to the specified destination. Typically, the maxValue and currency values (of the [[MonetaryAmount]]) are most appropriate.

inputs.name: shippingSettingsLink
inputs.label: Shipping Settings Link
inputs.help: Link to a page containing [[ShippingRateSettings]] and [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] details.

inputs.name: transitTimeLabel
inputs.label: Transit Time Label
inputs.help: Label to match an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with a [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] (within the context of a [[shippingSettingsLink]] cross-reference).

inputs.name: weight
inputs.label: Weight
inputs.help: The weight of the product or person.

inputs.name: width
inputs.label: Width
inputs.help: The width of the item.

MedicalEntity.name: MedicalEntity
MedicalEntity.help: The most generic type of entity related to health and the practice of medicine.

inputs.name: code
inputs.label: Code
inputs.help: A medical code for the entity, taken from a controlled vocabulary or ontology such as ICD-9, DiseasesDB, MeSH, SNOMED-CT, RxNorm, etc.

inputs.name: funding
inputs.label: Funding
inputs.help: A [[Grant]] that directly or indirectly provide funding or sponsorship for this item. See also [[ownershipFundingInfo]].

inputs.name: guideline
inputs.label: Guideline
inputs.help: A medical guideline related to this entity.

inputs.name: legalStatus
inputs.label: Legal Status
inputs.help: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

inputs.name: medicineSystem
inputs.label: Medicine System
inputs.help: The system of medicine that includes this MedicalEntity, for example 'evidence-based', 'homeopathic', 'chiropractic', etc.

inputs.name: recognizingAuthority
inputs.label: Recognizing Authority
inputs.help: If applicable, the organization that officially recognizes this entity as part of its endorsed system of medicine.

inputs.name: relevantSpecialty
inputs.label: Relevant Specialty
inputs.help: If applicable, a medical specialty in which this entity is relevant.

inputs.name: study
inputs.label: Study
inputs.help: A medical study or trial related to this entity.

BoatTrip.name: BoatTrip
BoatTrip.help: A trip on a commercial ferry line.

inputs.name: arrivalBoatTerminal
inputs.label: Arrival Boat Terminal
inputs.help: The terminal or port from which the boat arrives.

inputs.name: departureBoatTerminal
inputs.label: Departure Boat Terminal
inputs.help: The terminal or port from which the boat departs.

WebAPI.name: WebAPI
WebAPI.help: An application programming interface accessible over Web/Internet technologies.

inputs.name: documentation
inputs.label: Documentation
inputs.help: Further documentation describing the Web API in more detail.

LodgingReservation.name: LodgingReservation
LodgingReservation.help: A reservation for lodging at a hotel, motel, inn, etc.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

inputs.name: checkinTime
inputs.label: Checkin Time
inputs.help: The earliest someone may check into a lodging establishment.

inputs.name: checkoutTime
inputs.label: Checkout Time
inputs.help: The latest someone may check out of a lodging establishment.

inputs.name: lodgingUnitDescription
inputs.label: Lodging Unit Description
inputs.help: A full description of the lodging unit.

inputs.name: lodgingUnitType
inputs.label: Lodging Unit Type
inputs.help: Textual description of the unit type (including suite vs. room, size of bed, etc.).

inputs.name: numAdults
inputs.label: Num Adults
inputs.help: The number of adults staying in the unit.

inputs.name: numChildren
inputs.label: Num Children
inputs.help: The number of children staying in the unit.

TouristTrip.name: TouristTrip
TouristTrip.help:
A tourist trip. A created itinerary of visits to one or more places of interest ([[TouristAttraction]]/[[TouristDestination]]) often linked by a similar theme, geographic area, or interest to a particular [[touristType]]. The [UNWTO](http://www2.unwto.org/) defines tourism trip as the Trip taken by visitors.
  (See examples below.)

inputs.name: touristType
inputs.label: Tourist Type
inputs.help: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. E.g. children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

VideoGallery.name: VideoGallery
VideoGallery.help: Web page type: Video gallery page.

TVSeries.name: TVSeries
TVSeries.help: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.label: Actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.label: Actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: containsSeason
inputs.label: Contains Season
inputs.help: A season that is part of the media series.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.label: Country Of Origin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: director
inputs.label: Director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.label: Directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: episode
inputs.label: Episode
inputs.help: An episode of a TV, radio or game media within a series or season.

inputs.name: episodes
inputs.label: Episodes
inputs.help: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.label: Music By
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: numberOfEpisodes
inputs.label: Number Of Episodes
inputs.help: The number of episodes in this season or series.

inputs.name: numberOfSeasons
inputs.label: Number Of Seasons
inputs.help: The number of seasons in this series.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.label: Production Company
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item, e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: season
inputs.label: Season
inputs.help: A season in a media series.

inputs.name: seasons
inputs.label: Seasons
inputs.help: A season in a media series.

inputs.name: titleEIDR
inputs.label: Title EIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing at the most general/abstract level, a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" has a titleEIDR of  "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J". This title (or work) may have several variants, which EIDR calls "edits". See [[editEIDR]].

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]], [[TVEpisode]], [[TVSeason]], and [[TVSeries]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.label: Trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or TV/radio series, season, episode, etc.

LegislationObject.name: LegislationObject
LegislationObject.help: A specific object or file containing a Legislation. Note that the same Legislation can be published in multiple files. For example, a digitally signed PDF, a plain PDF and an HTML version.

inputs.name: legislationLegalValue
inputs.label: Legislation Legal Value
inputs.help: The legal value of this legislation file. The same legislation can be written in multiple files with different legal values. Typically a digitally signed PDF have a "stronger" legal value than the HTML file of the same act.

RefundTypeEnumeration.name: RefundTypeEnumeration
RefundTypeEnumeration.help: Enumerates several kinds of product return refund types.

MediaReviewItem.name: MediaReviewItem
MediaReviewItem.help: Represents an item or group of closely related items treated as a unit for the sake of evaluation in a [[MediaReview]]. Authorship etc. apply to the items rather than to the curation/grouping or reviewing party.

inputs.name: mediaItemAppearance
inputs.label: Media Item Appearance
inputs.help: In the context of a [[MediaReview]], indicates specific media item(s) that are grouped using a [[MediaReviewItem]].

Table.name: Table
Table.help: A table on a Web page.

MarryAction.name: MarryAction
MarryAction.help: The act of marrying a person.

AlignmentObject.name: AlignmentObject
AlignmentObject.help:
An intangible item that describes an alignment between a learning resource and a node in an educational framework.

Should not be used where the nature of the alignment can be described using a simple property, for example to express that a resource [[teaches]] or [[assesses]] a competency.

inputs.name: alignmentType
inputs.label: Alignment Type
inputs.help: A category of alignment between the learning resource and the framework node. Recommended values include: 'requires', 'textComplexity', 'readingLevel', and 'educationalSubject'.

inputs.name: educationalFramework
inputs.label: Educational Framework
inputs.help: The framework to which the resource being described is aligned.

inputs.name: targetDescription
inputs.label: Target Description
inputs.help: The description of a node in an established educational framework.

inputs.name: targetName
inputs.label: Target Name
inputs.help: The name of a node in an established educational framework.

inputs.name: targetUrl
inputs.label: Target Url
inputs.help: The URL of a node in an established educational framework.

MedicalRiskCalculator.name: MedicalRiskCalculator
MedicalRiskCalculator.help: A complex mathematical calculation requiring an online calculator, used to assess prognosis. Note: use the url property of Thing to record any URLs for online calculators.

PlayAction.name: PlayAction
PlayAction.help:
The act of playing/exercising/training/performing for enjoyment, leisure, recreation, competition or exercise.

Related actions:

* [[ListenAction]]: Unlike ListenAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to performing for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming music.
* [[WatchAction]]: Unlike WatchAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to showing/displaying for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming visual content.

inputs.name: audience
inputs.label: Audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: event
inputs.label: Event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

ProgramMembership.name: ProgramMembership
ProgramMembership.help: Used to describe membership in a loyalty programs (e.g. "StarAliance"), traveler clubs (e.g. "AAA"), purchase clubs ("Safeway Club"), etc.

inputs.name: hostingOrganization
inputs.label: Hosting Organization
inputs.help: The organization (airline, travelers' club, etc.) the membership is made with.

inputs.name: member
inputs.label: Member
inputs.help: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.

inputs.name: members
inputs.label: Members
inputs.help: A member of this organization.

inputs.name: membershipNumber
inputs.label: Membership Number
inputs.help: A unique identifier for the membership.

inputs.name: membershipPointsEarned
inputs.label: Membership Points Earned
inputs.help: The number of membership points earned by the member. If necessary, the unitText can be used to express the units the points are issued in. (E.g. stars, miles, etc.)

inputs.name: programName
inputs.label: Program Name
inputs.help: The program providing the membership.

PodcastSeries.name: PodcastSeries
PodcastSeries.help: A podcast is an episodic series of digital audio or video files which a user can download and listen to.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.label: Actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: webFeed
inputs.label: Web Feed
inputs.help: The URL for a feed, e.g. associated with a podcast series, blog, or series of date-stamped updates. This is usually RSS or Atom.

SearchRescueOrganization.name: SearchRescueOrganization
