inputs.label: Dose Schedule
inputs.help: A dosing schedule for the drug for a given population, either observed, recommended, or maximum dose based on the type used.

inputs.name: drugClass
inputs.label: Drug Class
inputs.help: The class of drug this belongs to (e.g., statins).

inputs.name: drugUnit
inputs.label: Drug Unit
inputs.help: The unit in which the drug is measured, e.g. '5 mg tablet'.

inputs.name: foodWarning
inputs.label: Food Warning
inputs.help: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to consumption of specific foods while taking this drug.

inputs.name: includedInHealthInsurancePlan
inputs.label: Included In Health Insurance Plan
inputs.help: The insurance plans that cover this drug.

inputs.name: interactingDrug
inputs.label: Interacting Drug
inputs.help: Another drug that is known to interact with this drug in a way that impacts the effect of this drug or causes a risk to the patient. Note: disease interactions are typically captured as contraindications.

inputs.name: isAvailableGenerically
inputs.label: Is Available Generically
inputs.help: True if the drug is available in a generic form (regardless of name).

inputs.name: isProprietary
inputs.label: Is Proprietary
inputs.help: True if this item's name is a proprietary/brand name (vs. generic name).

inputs.name: labelDetails
inputs.label: Label Details
inputs.help: Link to the drug's label details.

inputs.name: legalStatus
inputs.label: Legal Status
inputs.help: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

inputs.name: maximumIntake
inputs.label: Maximum Intake
inputs.help: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

inputs.name: mechanismOfAction
inputs.label: Mechanism Of Action
inputs.help: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.

inputs.name: nonProprietaryName
inputs.label: Non Proprietary Name
inputs.help: The generic name of this drug or supplement.

inputs.name: overdosage
inputs.label: Overdosage
inputs.help: Any information related to overdose on a drug, including signs or symptoms, treatments, contact information for emergency response.

inputs.name: pregnancyCategory
inputs.label: Pregnancy Category
inputs.help: Pregnancy category of this drug.

inputs.name: pregnancyWarning
inputs.label: Pregnancy Warning
inputs.help: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use during pregnancy.

inputs.name: prescribingInfo
inputs.label: Prescribing Info
inputs.help: Link to prescribing information for the drug.

inputs.name: prescriptionStatus
inputs.label: Prescription Status
inputs.help: Indicates the status of drug prescription, e.g. local catalogs classifications or whether the drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter, etc.

inputs.name: proprietaryName
inputs.label: Proprietary Name
inputs.help: Proprietary name given to the diet plan, typically by its originator or creator.

inputs.name: relatedDrug
inputs.label: Related Drug
inputs.help: Any other drug related to this one, for example commonly-prescribed alternatives.

inputs.name: rxcui
inputs.label: Rxcui
inputs.help: The RxCUI drug identifier from RXNORM.

inputs.name: warning
inputs.label: Warning
inputs.help: Any FDA or other warnings about the drug (text or URL).

PhysicalTherapy.name: PhysicalTherapy
PhysicalTherapy.help: A process of progressive physical care and rehabilitation aimed at improving a health condition.

Ticket.name: Ticket
Ticket.help: Used to describe a ticket to an event, a flight, a bus ride, etc.

inputs.name: dateIssued
inputs.label: Date Issued
inputs.help: The date the ticket was issued.

inputs.name: issuedBy
inputs.label: Issued By
inputs.help: The organization issuing the item, for example a [[Permit]], [[Ticket]], or [[Certification]].

inputs.name: priceCurrency
inputs.label: Price Currency
inputs.help: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217), e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies, e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Trading Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types, e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: ticketNumber
inputs.label: Ticket Number
inputs.help: The unique identifier for the ticket.

inputs.name: ticketToken
inputs.label: Ticket Token
inputs.help: Reference to an asset (e.g., Barcode, QR code image or PDF) usable for entrance.

inputs.name: ticketedSeat
inputs.label: Ticketed Seat
inputs.help: The seat associated with the ticket.

inputs.name: totalPrice
inputs.label: Total Price
inputs.help:
The total price for the reservation or ticket, including applicable taxes, shipping, etc.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: underName
inputs.label: Under Name
inputs.help: The person or organization the reservation or ticket is for.

LoanOrCredit.name: LoanOrCredit
LoanOrCredit.help: A financial product for the loaning of an amount of money, or line of credit, under agreed terms and charges.

inputs.name: amount
inputs.label: Amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.label: Currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217), e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies, e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Trading Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types, e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: gracePeriod
inputs.label: Grace Period
inputs.help: The period of time after any due date that the borrower has to fulfil its obligations before a default (failure to pay) is deemed to have occurred.

inputs.name: loanRepaymentForm
inputs.label: Loan Repayment Form
inputs.help: A form of paying back money previously borrowed from a lender. Repayment usually takes the form of periodic payments that normally include part principal plus interest in each payment.

inputs.name: loanTerm
inputs.label: Loan Term
inputs.help: The duration of the loan or credit agreement.

inputs.name: loanType
inputs.label: Loan Type
inputs.help: The type of a loan or credit.

inputs.name: recourseLoan
inputs.label: Recourse Loan
inputs.help: The only way you get the money back in the event of default is the security. Recourse is where you still have the opportunity to go back to the borrower for the rest of the money.

inputs.name: renegotiableLoan
inputs.label: Renegotiable Loan
inputs.help: Whether the terms for payment of interest can be renegotiated during the life of the loan.

inputs.name: requiredCollateral
inputs.label: Required Collateral
inputs.help: Assets required to secure loan or credit repayments. It may take form of third party pledge, goods, financial instruments (cash, securities, etc.)

BloodTest.name: BloodTest
BloodTest.help: A medical test performed on a sample of a patient's blood.

ReturnAction.name: ReturnAction
ReturnAction.help: The act of returning to the origin that which was previously received (concrete objects) or taken (ownership).

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.label: Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

TieAction.name: TieAction
TieAction.help: The act of reaching a draw in a competitive activity.

Room.name: Room
Room.help:
A room is a distinguishable space within a structure, usually separated from other spaces by interior walls (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Room).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

InviteAction.name: InviteAction
InviteAction.help: The act of asking someone to attend an event. Reciprocal of RsvpAction.

inputs.name: event
inputs.label: Event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

RadioChannel.name: RadioChannel
RadioChannel.help: A unique instance of a radio BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

CancelAction.name: CancelAction
CancelAction.help:
The act of asserting that a future event/action is no longer going to happen.

Related actions:

* [[ConfirmAction]]: The antonym of CancelAction.

FinancialProduct.name: FinancialProduct
FinancialProduct.help: A product provided to consumers and businesses by financial institutions such as banks, insurance companies, brokerage firms, consumer finance companies, and investment companies which comprise the financial services industry.

inputs.name: annualPercentageRate
inputs.label: Annual Percentage Rate
inputs.help: The annual rate that is charged for borrowing (or made by investing), expressed as a single percentage number that represents the actual yearly cost of funds over the term of a loan. This includes any fees or additional costs associated with the transaction.

inputs.name: feesAndCommissionsSpecification
inputs.label: Fees And Commissions Specification
inputs.help: Description of fees, commissions, and other terms applied either to a class of financial product, or by a financial service organization.

inputs.name: interestRate
inputs.label: Interest Rate
inputs.help: The interest rate, charged or paid, applicable to the financial product. Note: This is different from the calculated annualPercentageRate.

BusinessAudience.name: BusinessAudience
BusinessAudience.help: A set of characteristics belonging to businesses, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

inputs.name: numberOfEmployees
inputs.label: Number Of Employees
inputs.help: The number of employees in an organization, e.g. business.

inputs.name: yearlyRevenue
inputs.label: Yearly Revenue
inputs.help: The size of the business in annual revenue.

inputs.name: yearsInOperation
inputs.label: Years In Operation
inputs.help: The age of the business.

ReadAction.name: ReadAction
ReadAction.help: The act of consuming written content.

DatedMoneySpecification.name: DatedMoneySpecification
DatedMoneySpecification.help: A DatedMoneySpecification represents monetary values with optional start and end dates. For example, this could represent an employee's salary over a specific period of time. __Note:__ This type has been superseded by [[MonetaryAmount]], use of that type is recommended.

inputs.name: amount
inputs.label: Amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.label: Currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217), e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies, e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Trading Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types, e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.label: End Date
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.label: Start Date
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

VideoGame.name: VideoGame
VideoGame.help: A video game is an electronic game that involves human interaction with a user interface to generate visual feedback on a video device.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.label: Actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.label: Actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: cheatCode
inputs.label: Cheat Code
inputs.help: Cheat codes to the game.

inputs.name: director
inputs.label: Director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.label: Directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: gameEdition
inputs.label: Game Edition
inputs.help: The edition of a video game.

inputs.name: gamePlatform
inputs.label: Game Platform
inputs.help: The electronic systems used to play video games.

inputs.name: gameServer
inputs.label: Game Server
inputs.help: The server on which  it is possible to play the game.

inputs.name: gameTip
inputs.label: Game Tip
inputs.help: Links to tips, tactics, etc.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.label: Music By
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: playMode
inputs.label: Play Mode
inputs.help: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.label: Trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or TV/radio series, season, episode, etc.

Message.name: Message
Message.help: A single message from a sender to one or more organizations or people.

inputs.name: bccRecipient
inputs.label: Bcc Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of recipient. The recipient blind copied on a message.

inputs.name: ccRecipient
inputs.label: Cc Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of recipient. The recipient copied on a message.

inputs.name: dateRead
inputs.label: Date Read
inputs.help: The date/time at which the message has been read by the recipient if a single recipient exists.

inputs.name: dateReceived
inputs.label: Date Received
inputs.help: The date/time the message was received if a single recipient exists.

inputs.name: dateSent
inputs.label: Date Sent
inputs.help: The date/time at which the message was sent.

inputs.name: messageAttachment
inputs.label: Message Attachment
inputs.help: A CreativeWork attached to the message.

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.label: Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

inputs.name: sender
inputs.label: Sender
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the sending end of the action.

inputs.name: toRecipient
inputs.label: To Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of recipient. The recipient who was directly sent the message.

OfferForLease.name: OfferForLease
OfferForLease.help:
An [[OfferForLease]] in Schema.org represents an [[Offer]] to lease out something, i.e. an [[Offer]] whose
  [[businessFunction]] is [lease out](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut.). See [Good Relations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GoodRelations) for
  background on the underlying concepts.

XPathType.name: XPathType
XPathType.help: Text representing an XPath (typically but not necessarily version 1.0).

NoteDigitalDocument.name: NoteDigitalDocument
NoteDigitalDocument.help: A file containing a note, primarily for the author.

EducationalOccupationalCredential.name: EducationalOccupationalCredential
EducationalOccupationalCredential.help: An educational or occupational credential. A diploma, academic degree, certification, qualification, badge, etc., that may be awarded to a person or other entity that meets the requirements defined by the credentialer.

inputs.name: competencyRequired
inputs.label: Competency Required
inputs.help: Knowledge, skill, ability or personal attribute that must be demonstrated by a person or other entity in order to do something such as earn an Educational Occupational Credential or understand a LearningResource.

inputs.name: credentialCategory
inputs.label: Credential Category
inputs.help: The category or type of credential being described, for example "degree”, “certificate”, “badge”, or more specific term.

inputs.name: educationalLevel
inputs.label: Educational Level
inputs.help: The level in terms of progression through an educational or training context. Examples of educational levels include 'beginner', 'intermediate' or 'advanced', and formal sets of level indicators.

inputs.name: recognizedBy
inputs.label: Recognized By
inputs.help: An organization that acknowledges the validity, value or utility of a credential. Note: recognition may include a process of quality assurance or accreditation.

inputs.name: validFor
inputs.label: Valid For
inputs.help: The duration of validity of a permit or similar thing.

inputs.name: validIn
inputs.label: Valid In
inputs.help: The geographic area where the item is valid. Applies for example to a [[Permit]], a [[Certification]], or an [[EducationalOccupationalCredential]].

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.label: Number Of Rooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.label: Occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person.

MedicalAudienceType.name: MedicalAudienceType
MedicalAudienceType.help: Target audiences types for medical web pages. Enumerated type.

CourseInstance.name: CourseInstance
CourseInstance.help: An instance of a [[Course]] which is distinct from other instances because it is offered at a different time or location or through different media or modes of study or to a specific section of students.

inputs.name: courseMode
inputs.label: Course Mode
inputs.help: The medium or means of delivery of the course instance or the mode of study, either as a text label (e.g. "online", "onsite" or "blended"; "synchronous" or "asynchronous"; "full-time" or "part-time") or as a URL reference to a term from a controlled vocabulary (e.g. https://ceds.ed.gov/element/001311#Asynchronous).

inputs.name: courseSchedule
inputs.label: Course Schedule
inputs.help: Represents the length and pace of a course, expressed as a [[Schedule]].

inputs.name: courseWorkload
inputs.label: Course Workload
inputs.help: The amount of work expected of students taking the course, often provided as a figure per week or per month, and may be broken down by type. For example, "2 hours of lectures, 1 hour of lab work and 3 hours of independent study per week".

inputs.name: instructor
inputs.label: Instructor
inputs.help: A person assigned to instruct or provide instructional assistance for the [[CourseInstance]].

MaximumDoseSchedule.name: MaximumDoseSchedule
MaximumDoseSchedule.help: The maximum dosing schedule considered safe for a drug or supplement as recommended by an authority or by the drug/supplement's manufacturer. Capture the recommending authority in the recognizingAuthority property of MedicalEntity.

ScheduleAction.name: ScheduleAction
ScheduleAction.help:
Scheduling future actions, events, or tasks.

Related actions:

* [[ReserveAction]]: Unlike ReserveAction, ScheduleAction allocates future actions (e.g. an event, a task, etc) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

DDxElement.name: DDxElement
DDxElement.help: An alternative, closely-related condition typically considered later in the differential diagnosis process along with the signs that are used to distinguish it.

inputs.name: diagnosis
inputs.label: Diagnosis
inputs.help: One or more alternative conditions considered in the differential diagnosis process as output of a diagnosis process.

inputs.name: distinguishingSign
inputs.label: Distinguishing Sign
inputs.help: One of a set of signs and symptoms that can be used to distinguish this diagnosis from others in the differential diagnosis.

NewsArticle.name: NewsArticle
NewsArticle.help:
A NewsArticle is an article whose content reports news, or provides background context and supporting materials for understanding the news.

A more detailed overview of [schema.org News markup](/docs/news.html) is also available.

inputs.name: dateline
inputs.label: Dateline
inputs.help:
A [dateline](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dateline) is a brief piece of text included in news articles that describes where and when the story was written or filed though the date is often omitted. Sometimes only a placename is provided.

Structured representations of dateline-related information can also be expressed more explicitly using [[locationCreated]] (which represents where a work was created, e.g. where a news report was written).  For location depicted or described in the content, use [[contentLocation]].

Dateline summaries are oriented more towards human readers than towards automated processing, and can vary substantially. Some examples: "BEIRUT, Lebanon, June 2.", "Paris, France", "December 19, 2017 11:43AM Reporting from Washington", "Beijing/Moscow", "QUEZON CITY, Philippines".

inputs.name: printColumn
inputs.label: Print Column
inputs.help: The number of the column in which the NewsArticle appears in the print edition.

inputs.name: printEdition
inputs.label: Print Edition
inputs.help: The edition of the print product in which the NewsArticle appears.

inputs.name: printPage
inputs.label: Print Page
inputs.help: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the name of the page on which the article is found. Please note that this field is intended for the exact page name (e.g. A5, B18).

inputs.name: printSection
inputs.label: Print Section
inputs.help: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the print section in which the article appeared.

ContactPointOption.name: ContactPointOption
ContactPointOption.help: Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.

GovernmentPermit.name: GovernmentPermit
GovernmentPermit.help: A permit issued by a government agency.

CreativeWorkSeason.name: CreativeWorkSeason
CreativeWorkSeason.help: A media season, e.g. TV, radio, video game etc.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.label: Actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in TV, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: director
inputs.label: Director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. TV, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.label: End Date
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: episode
inputs.label: Episode
inputs.help: An episode of a TV, radio or game media within a series or season.

inputs.name: episodes
inputs.label: Episodes
inputs.help: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

inputs.name: numberOfEpisodes
inputs.label: Number Of Episodes
inputs.help: The number of episodes in this season or series.

inputs.name: partOfSeries
inputs.label: Part Of Series
inputs.help: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.label: Production Company
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item, e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: seasonNumber
inputs.label: Season Number
inputs.help: Position of the season within an ordered group of seasons.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.label: Start Date
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.label: Trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or TV/radio series, season, episode, etc.

TrackAction.name: TrackAction
TrackAction.help:
An agent tracks an object for updates.

Related actions:

* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, TrackAction refers to the interest on the location of innanimates objects.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, TrackAction refers to  the interest on the location of innanimate objects.

inputs.name: deliveryMethod
inputs.label: Delivery Method
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

Grant.name: Grant
Grant.help:
A grant, typically financial or otherwise quantifiable, of resources. Typically a [[funder]] sponsors some [[MonetaryAmount]] to an [[Organization]] or [[Person]],
    sometimes not necessarily via a dedicated or long-lived [[Project]], resulting in one or more outputs, or [[fundedItem]]s. For financial sponsorship, indicate the [[funder]] of a [[MonetaryGrant]]. For non-financial support, indicate [[sponsor]] of [[Grant]]s of resources (e.g. office space).

Grants support  activities directed towards some agreed collective goals, often but not always organized as [[Project]]s. Long-lived projects are sometimes sponsored by a variety of grants over time, but it is also common for a project to be associated with a single grant.

The amount of a [[Grant]] is represented using [[amount]] as a [[MonetaryAmount]].

inputs.name: fundedItem
inputs.label: Funded Item
inputs.help: Indicates something directly or indirectly funded or sponsored through a [[Grant]]. See also [[ownershipFundingInfo]].

inputs.name: funder
inputs.label: Funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.label: Sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. E.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

SatiricalArticle.name: SatiricalArticle
SatiricalArticle.help: An [[Article]] whose content is primarily [[satirical]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satire) in nature, i.e. unlikely to be literally true. A satirical article is sometimes but not necessarily also a [[NewsArticle]]. [[ScholarlyArticle]]s are also sometimes satirized.

VirtualLocation.name: VirtualLocation
VirtualLocation.help: An online or virtual location for attending events. For example, one may attend an online seminar or educational event. While a virtual location may be used as the location of an event, virtual locations should not be confused with physical locations in the real world.

LodgingBusiness.name: LodgingBusiness
LodgingBusiness.help: A lodging business, such as a motel, hotel, or inn.

inputs.name: amenityFeature
inputs.label: Amenity Feature
inputs.help: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

inputs.name: audience
inputs.label: Audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: availableLanguage
inputs.label: Available Language
inputs.help: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]].

inputs.name: checkinTime
inputs.label: Checkin Time
inputs.help: The earliest someone may check into a lodging establishment.

inputs.name: checkoutTime
inputs.label: Checkout Time
inputs.help: The latest someone may check out of a lodging establishment.

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.label: Number Of Rooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: petsAllowed
inputs.label: Pets Allowed
inputs.help: Indicates whether pets are allowed to enter the accommodation or lodging business. More detailed information can be put in a text value.

inputs.name: starRating
inputs.label: Star Rating
inputs.help: An official rating for a lodging business or food establishment, e.g. from national associations or standards bodies. Use the author property to indicate the rating organization, e.g. as an Organization with name such as (e.g. HOTREC, DEHOGA, WHR, or Hotelstars).

WatchAction.name: WatchAction
WatchAction.help: The act of consuming dynamic/moving visual content.

InteractionCounter.name: InteractionCounter
InteractionCounter.help: A summary of how users have interacted with this CreativeWork. In most cases, authors will use a subtype to specify the specific type of interaction.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.label: End Time
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: interactionService
inputs.label: Interaction Service
inputs.help: The WebSite or SoftwareApplication where the interactions took place.

inputs.name: interactionType
inputs.label: Interaction Type
inputs.help: The Action representing the type of interaction. For up votes, +1s, etc. use [[LikeAction]]. For down votes use [[DislikeAction]]. Otherwise, use the most specific Action.

inputs.name: location
inputs.label: Location
inputs.help: The location of, for example, where an event is happening, where an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.label: Start Time
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: userInteractionCount
inputs.label: User Interaction Count
inputs.help: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication.

LendAction.name: LendAction
LendAction.help:
The act of providing an object under an agreement that it will be returned at a later date. Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

Related actions:

* [[BorrowAction]]: Reciprocal of LendAction.

inputs.name: borrower
inputs.label: Borrower
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The person that borrows the object being lent.

SpecialAnnouncement.name: SpecialAnnouncement
SpecialAnnouncement.help:
A SpecialAnnouncement combines a simple date-stamped textual information update
      with contextualized Web links and other structured data.  It represents an information update made by a
      locally-oriented organization, for example schools, pharmacies, healthcare providers,  community groups, police,
      local government.

For work in progress guidelines on Coronavirus-related markup see [this doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/14ikaGCKxo50rRM7nvKSlbUpjyIk2WMQd3IkB1lItlrM/edit#).

The motivating scenario for SpecialAnnouncement is the [Coronavirus pandemic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic), and the initial vocabulary is oriented to this urgent situation. Schema.org
expect to improve the markup iteratively as it is deployed and as feedback emerges from use. In addition to our
usual [Github entry](https://github.com/schemaorg/schemaorg/issues/2490), feedback comments can also be provided in [this document](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fpdFFxk8s87CWwACs53SGkYv3aafSxz_DTtOQxMrBJQ/edit#).


While this schema is designed to communicate urgent crisis-related information, it is not the same as an emergency warning technology like [CAP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Alerting_Protocol), although there may be overlaps. The intent is to cover
the kinds of everyday practical information being posted to existing websites during an emergency situation.

Several kinds of information can be provided:

We encourage the provision of "name", "text", "datePosted", "expires" (if appropriate), "category" and
"url" as a simple baseline. It is important to provide a value for "category" where possible, most ideally as a well known
URL from Wikipedia or Wikidata. In the case of the 2019-2020 Coronavirus pandemic, this should be "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2019-20\_coronavirus\_pandemic" or "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q81068910".

For many of the possible properties, values can either be simple links or an inline description, depending on whether a summary is available. For a link, provide just the URL of the appropriate page as the property's value. For an inline description, use a [[WebContent]] type, and provide the url as a property of that, alongside at least a simple "[[text]]" summary of the page. It is
unlikely that a single SpecialAnnouncement will need all of the possible properties simultaneously.

We expect that in many cases the page referenced might contain more specialized structured data, e.g. contact info, [[openingHours]], [[Event]], [[FAQPage]] etc. By linking to those pages from a [[SpecialAnnouncement]] you can help make it clearer that the events are related to the situation (e.g. Coronavirus) indicated by the [[category]] property of the [[SpecialAnnouncement]].

Many [[SpecialAnnouncement]]s will relate to particular regions and to identifiable local organizations. Use [[spatialCoverage]] for the region, and [[announcementLocation]] to indicate specific [[LocalBusiness]]es and [[CivicStructure]]s. If the announcement affects both a particular region and a specific location (for example, a library closure that serves an entire region), use both [[spatialCoverage]] and [[announcementLocation]].

The [[about]] property can be used to indicate entities that are the focus of the announcement. We now recommend using [[about]] only
for representing non-location entities (e.g. a [[Course]] or a [[RadioStation]]). For places, use [[announcementLocation]] and [[spatialCoverage]]. Consumers of this markup should be aware that the initial design encouraged the use of [[about]] for locations too.

The basic content of [[SpecialAnnouncement]] is similar to that of an [RSS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSS) or [Atom](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom_(Web_standard)) feed. For publishers without such feeds, basic feed-like information can be shared by posting
[[SpecialAnnouncement]] updates in a page, e.g. using JSON-LD. For sites with Atom/RSS functionality, you can point to a feed
with the [[webFeed]] property. This can be a simple URL, or an inline [[DataFeed]] object, with [[encodingFormat]] providing
media type information, e.g. "application/rss+xml" or "application/atom+xml".

inputs.name: announcementLocation
inputs.label: Announcement Location
inputs.help: Indicates a specific [[CivicStructure]] or [[LocalBusiness]] associated with the SpecialAnnouncement. For example, a specific testing facility or business with special opening hours. For a larger geographic region like a quarantine of an entire region, use [[spatialCoverage]].

inputs.name: category
inputs.label: Category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

inputs.name: datePosted
inputs.label: Date Posted
inputs.help: Publication date of an online listing.

inputs.name: diseasePreventionInfo
inputs.label: Disease Prevention Info
inputs.help: Information about disease prevention.

inputs.name: diseaseSpreadStatistics
inputs.label: Disease Spread Statistics
inputs.help:
Statistical information about the spread of a disease, either as [[WebContent]], or
  described directly as a [[Dataset]], or the specific [[Observation]]s in the dataset. When a [[WebContent]] URL is
  provided, the page indicated might also contain more such markup.

inputs.name: gettingTestedInfo
inputs.label: Getting Tested Info
inputs.help: Information about getting tested (for a [[MedicalCondition]]), e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: governmentBenefitsInfo
inputs.label: Government Benefits Info
inputs.help: governmentBenefitsInfo provides information about government benefits associated with a SpecialAnnouncement.

inputs.name: newsUpdatesAndGuidelines
inputs.label: News Updates And Guidelines
inputs.help: Indicates a page with news updates and guidelines. This could often be (but is not required to be) the main page containing [[SpecialAnnouncement]] markup on a site.

inputs.name: publicTransportClosuresInfo
inputs.label: Public Transport Closures Info
inputs.help: Information about public transport closures.

inputs.name: quarantineGuidelines
inputs.label: Quarantine Guidelines
inputs.help: Guidelines about quarantine rules, e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: schoolClosuresInfo
inputs.label: School Closures Info
inputs.help: Information about school closures.

inputs.name: travelBans
inputs.label: Travel Bans
inputs.help: Information about travel bans, e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: webFeed
inputs.label: Web Feed
inputs.help: The URL for a feed, e.g. associated with a podcast series, blog, or series of date-stamped updates. This is usually RSS or Atom.

LinkRole.name: LinkRole
LinkRole.help: A Role that represents a Web link, e.g. as expressed via the 'url' property. Its linkRelationship property can indicate URL-based and plain textual link types, e.g. those in IANA link registry or others such as 'amphtml'. This structure provides a placeholder where details from HTML's link element can be represented outside of HTML, e.g. in JSON-LD feeds.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.label: In Language
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: linkRelationship
inputs.label: Link Relationship
inputs.help: Indicates the relationship type of a Web link.

PaymentMethod.name: PaymentMethod
PaymentMethod.help:
A payment method is a standardized procedure for transferring the monetary amount for a purchase. Payment methods are characterized by the legal and technical structures used, and by the organization or group carrying out the transaction.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByBankTransferInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByInvoice
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Cash
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#CheckInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#COD
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DirectDebit
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#GoogleCheckout
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PayPal
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PaySwarm

RestrictedDiet.name: RestrictedDiet
RestrictedDiet.help: A diet restricted to certain foods or preparations for cultural, religious, health or lifestyle reasons.

SeekToAction.name: SeekToAction
SeekToAction.help: This is the [[Action]] of navigating to a specific [[startOffset]] timestamp within a [[VideoObject]], typically represented with a URL template structure.

inputs.name: startOffset
inputs.label: Start Offset
inputs.help: The start time of the clip expressed as the number of seconds from the beginning of the work.

BoatTerminal.name: BoatTerminal
BoatTerminal.help: A terminal for boats, ships, and other water vessels.

UserBlocks.name: UserBlocks
UserBlocks.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

DrugStrength.name: DrugStrength
DrugStrength.help: A specific strength in which a medical drug is available in a specific country.

inputs.name: activeIngredient
inputs.label: Active Ingredient
inputs.help: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

inputs.name: availableIn
inputs.label: Available In
inputs.help: The location in which the strength is available.

inputs.name: maximumIntake
inputs.label: Maximum Intake
inputs.help: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

inputs.name: strengthUnit
inputs.label: Strength Unit
inputs.help: The units of an active ingredient's strength, e.g. mg.

inputs.name: strengthValue
inputs.label: Strength Value
inputs.help: The value of an active ingredient's strength, e.g. 325.

MedicalDevicePurpose.name: MedicalDevicePurpose
MedicalDevicePurpose.help: Categories of medical devices, organized by the purpose or intended use of the device.

inputs.name: amount
inputs.label: Amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.label: Funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

SiteNavigationElement.name: SiteNavigationElement
SiteNavigationElement.help: A navigation element of the page.

WearableSizeSystemEnumeration.name: WearableSizeSystemEnumeration
WearableSizeSystemEnumeration.help: Enumerates common size systems specific for wearable products.

RecommendedDoseSchedule.name: RecommendedDoseSchedule
RecommendedDoseSchedule.help: A recommended dosing schedule for a drug or supplement as prescribed or recommended by an authority or by the drug/supplement's manufacturer. Capture the recommending authority in the recognizingAuthority property of MedicalEntity.

PaintAction.name: PaintAction
PaintAction.help: The act of producing a painting, typically with paint and canvas as instruments.

Hostel.name: Hostel
Hostel.help:
A hostel - cheap accommodation, often in shared dormitories.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

MedicalSpecialty.name: MedicalSpecialty
MedicalSpecialty.help: Any specific branch of medical science or practice. Medical specialities include clinical specialties that pertain to particular organ systems and their respective disease states, as well as allied health specialties. Enumerated type.

MusicPlaylist.name: MusicPlaylist
MusicPlaylist.help: A collection of music tracks in playlist form.

inputs.name: numTracks
inputs.label: Num Tracks
inputs.help: The number of tracks in this album or playlist.

inputs.name: track
inputs.label: Track
inputs.help: A music recording (track)—usually a single song. If an ItemList is given, the list should contain items of type MusicRecording.

inputs.name: tracks
inputs.label: Tracks
inputs.help: A music recording (track)—usually a single song.

SurgicalProcedure.name: SurgicalProcedure
SurgicalProcedure.help: A medical procedure involving an incision with instruments; performed for diagnose, or therapeutic purposes.

AggregateOffer.name: AggregateOffer
AggregateOffer.help: When a single product is associated with multiple offers (for example, the same pair of shoes is offered by different merchants), then AggregateOffer can be used.\n\nNote: AggregateOffers are normally expected to associate multiple offers that all share the same defined [[businessFunction]] value, or default to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell if businessFunction is not explicitly defined.

inputs.name: highPrice
inputs.label: High Price
inputs.help:
The highest price of all offers available.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: lowPrice
inputs.label: Low Price
inputs.help:
The lowest price of all offers available.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: offerCount
inputs.label: Offer Count
inputs.help: The number of offers for the product.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.label: Offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

InstallAction.name: InstallAction
InstallAction.help: The act of installing an application.

ReceiveAction.name: ReceiveAction
ReceiveAction.help:
The act of physically/electronically taking delivery of an object that has been transferred from an origin to a destination. Reciprocal of SendAction.

Related actions:

* [[SendAction]]: The reciprocal of ReceiveAction.
* [[TakeAction]]: Unlike TakeAction, ReceiveAction does not imply that the ownership has been transferred (e.g. I can receive a package, but it does not mean the package is now mine).

inputs.name: deliveryMethod
inputs.label: Delivery Method
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

inputs.name: sender
inputs.label: Sender
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the sending end of the action.

Diet.name: Diet
Diet.help: A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.

inputs.name: dietFeatures
inputs.label: Diet Features
inputs.help: Nutritional information specific to the dietary plan. May include dietary recommendations on what foods to avoid, what foods to consume, and specific alterations/deviations from the USDA or other regulatory body's approved dietary guidelines.

inputs.name: endorsers
inputs.label: Endorsers
inputs.help: People or organizations that endorse the plan.

inputs.name: expertConsiderations
inputs.label: Expert Considerations
inputs.help: Medical expert advice related to the plan.

inputs.name: physiologicalBenefits
inputs.label: Physiological Benefits
inputs.help: Specific physiologic benefits associated to the plan.

inputs.name: risks
inputs.label: Risks
inputs.help: Specific physiologic risks associated to the diet plan.

PublicationEvent.name: PublicationEvent
PublicationEvent.help: A PublicationEvent corresponds indifferently to the event of publication for a CreativeWork of any type, e.g. a broadcast event, an on-demand event, a book/journal publication via a variety of delivery media.

inputs.name: free
inputs.label: Free
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

inputs.name: publishedBy
inputs.label: Published By
inputs.help: An agent associated with the publication event.

inputs.name: publishedOn
inputs.label: Published On
inputs.help: A broadcast service associated with the publication event.

WPHeader.name: WPHeader
WPHeader.help: The header section of the page.

MedicalSignOrSymptom.name: MedicalSignOrSymptom
MedicalSignOrSymptom.help: Any feature associated or not with a medical condition. In medicine a symptom is generally subjective while a sign is objective.

inputs.name: possibleTreatment
inputs.label: Possible Treatment
inputs.help: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

Campground.name: Campground
Campground.help:
A camping site, campsite, or [[Campground]] is a place used for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically containing individual [[CampingPitch]] locations. \n\n
In British English a campsite is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites (source: Wikipedia, see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite)).\n\n

See also the dedicated [document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations](/docs/hotels.html).

TaxiReservation.name: TaxiReservation
TaxiReservation.help: A reservation for a taxi.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

inputs.name: partySize
inputs.label: Party Size
inputs.help: Number of people the reservation should accommodate.

inputs.name: pickupLocation
inputs.label: Pickup Location
inputs.help: Where a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

inputs.name: pickupTime
inputs.label: Pickup Time
inputs.help: When a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

Article.name: Article
Article.help: An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

inputs.name: articleBody
inputs.label: Article Body
inputs.help: The actual body of the article.

inputs.name: articleSection
inputs.label: Article Section
inputs.help: Articles may belong to one or more 'sections' in a magazine or newspaper, such as Sports, Lifestyle, etc.

inputs.name: backstory
inputs.label: Backstory
inputs.help: For an [[Article]], typically a [[NewsArticle]], the backstory property provides a textual summary giving a brief explanation of why and how an article was created. In a journalistic setting this could include information about reporting process, methods, interviews, data sources, etc.

inputs.name: pageEnd
inputs.label: Page End
inputs.help: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

inputs.name: pageStart
inputs.label: Page Start
inputs.help: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

inputs.name: pagination
inputs.label: Pagination
inputs.help: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

inputs.name: speakable
inputs.label: Speakable
inputs.help:
Indicates sections of a Web page that are particularly 'speakable' in the sense of being highlighted as being especially appropriate for text-to-speech conversion. Other sections of a page may also be usefully spoken in particular circumstances; the 'speakable' property serves to indicate the parts most likely to be generally useful for speech.

The *speakable* property can be repeated an arbitrary number of times, with three kinds of possible 'content-locator' values:

1.) *id-value* URL references - uses *id-value* of an element in the page being annotated. The simplest use of *speakable* has (potentially relative) URL values, referencing identified sections of the document concerned.

2.) CSS Selectors - addresses content in the annotated page, e.g. via class attribute. Use the [[cssSelector]] property.

3.)  XPaths - addresses content via XPaths (assuming an XML view of the content). Use the [[xpath]] property.


For more sophisticated markup of speakable sections beyond simple ID references, either CSS selectors or XPath expressions to pick out document section(s) as speakable. For this
we define a supporting type, [[SpeakableSpecification]]  which is defined to be a possible value of the *speakable* property.

inputs.name: wordCount
inputs.label: Word Count
inputs.help: The number of words in the text of the Article.

Vein.name: Vein
Vein.help: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood to the heart.

inputs.name: drainsTo
inputs.label: Drains To
inputs.help: The vasculature that the vein drains into.

inputs.name: regionDrained
inputs.label: Region Drained
inputs.help: The anatomical or organ system drained by this vessel; generally refers to a specific part of an organ.

inputs.name: tributary
inputs.label: Tributary
inputs.help: The anatomical or organ system that the vein flows into; a larger structure that the vein connects to.

SizeGroupEnumeration.name: SizeGroupEnumeration
SizeGroupEnumeration.help: Enumerates common size groups for various product categories.

Observation.name: Observation
Observation.help:
Instances of the class [[Observation]] are used to specify observations about an entity at a particular time. The principal properties of an [[Observation]] are [[observationAbout]], [[measuredProperty]], [[statType]], [[value] and [[observationDate]]  and [[measuredProperty]]. Some but not all Observations represent a [[QuantitativeValue]]. Quantitative observations can be about a [[StatisticalVariable]], which is an abstract specification about which we can make observations that are grounded at a particular location and time. 
    
Observations can also encode a subset of simple RDF-like statements (its observationAbout, a StatisticalVariable, defining the measuredPoperty; its observationAbout property indicating the entity the statement is about, and [[value]] )

In the context of a quantitative knowledge graph, typical properties could include [[measuredProperty]], [[observationAbout]], [[observationDate]], [[value]], [[unitCode]], [[unitText]], [[measurementMethod]].

inputs.name: marginOfError
inputs.label: Margin Of Error
inputs.help: A [[marginOfError]] for an [[Observation]].

inputs.name: measuredProperty
inputs.label: Measured Property
inputs.help: The measuredProperty of an [[Observation]], typically via its [[StatisticalVariable]]. There are various kinds of applicable [[Property]]: a schema.org property, a property from other RDF-compatible systems, e.g. W3C RDF Data Cube, Data Commons, Wikidata, or schema.org extensions such as [GS1's](https://www.gs1.org/voc/?show=properties).

inputs.name: measurementDenominator
inputs.label: Measurement Denominator
inputs.help: Identifies the denominator variable when an observation represents a ratio or percentage.

inputs.name: measurementMethod
inputs.label: Measurement Method
inputs.help: A subproperty of [[measurementTechnique]] that can be used for specifying specific methods, in particular via [[MeasurementMethodEnum]].

inputs.name: measurementQualifier
inputs.label: Measurement Qualifier
inputs.help: Provides additional qualification to an observation. For example, a GDP observation measures the Nominal value.

inputs.name: measurementTechnique
inputs.label: Measurement Technique
inputs.help:
A technique, method or technology used in an [[Observation]], [[StatisticalVariable]] or [[Dataset]] (or [[DataDownload]], [[DataCatalog]]), corresponding to the method used for measuring the corresponding variable(s) (for datasets, described using [[variableMeasured]]; for [[Observation]], a [[StatisticalVariable]]). Often but not necessarily each [[variableMeasured]] will have an explicit representation as (or mapping to) an property such as those defined in Schema.org, or other RDF vocabularies and "knowledge graphs". In that case the subproperty of [[variableMeasured]] called [[measuredProperty]] is applicable.
    
The [[measurementTechnique]] property helps when extra clarification is needed about how a [[measuredProperty]] was measured. This is oriented towards scientific and scholarly dataset publication but may have broader applicability; it is not intended as a full representation of measurement, but can often serve as a high level summary for dataset discovery. 

For example, if [[variableMeasured]] is: molecule concentration, [[measurementTechnique]] could be: "mass spectrometry" or "nmr spectroscopy" or "colorimetry" or "immunofluorescence". If the [[variableMeasured]] is "depression rating", the [[measurementTechnique]] could be "Zung Scale" or "HAM-D" or "Beck Depression Inventory". 

If there are several [[variableMeasured]] properties recorded for some given data object, use a [[PropertyValue]] for each [[variableMeasured]] and attach the corresponding [[measurementTechnique]]. The value can also be from an enumeration, organized as a [[MeasurementMetholdEnumeration]].

inputs.name: observationAbout
inputs.label: Observation About
inputs.help: The [[observationAbout]] property identifies an entity, often a [[Place]], associated with an [[Observation]].

inputs.name: observationDate
inputs.label: Observation Date
inputs.help: The observationDate of an [[Observation]].

inputs.name: observationPeriod
inputs.label: Observation Period
inputs.help: The length of time an Observation took place over. The format follows `P[0-9]*[Y|M|D|h|m|s]`. For example, P1Y is Period 1 Year, P3M is Period 3 Months, P3h is Period 3 hours.

inputs.name: variableMeasured
inputs.label: Variable Measured
inputs.help: The variableMeasured property can indicate (repeated as necessary) the  variables that are measured in some dataset, either described as text or as pairs of identifier and description using PropertyValue, or more explicitly as a [[StatisticalVariable]].

StatisticalPopulation.name: StatisticalPopulation
StatisticalPopulation.help:
A StatisticalPopulation is a set of instances of a certain given type that satisfy some set of constraints. The property [[populationType]] is used to specify the type. Any property that can be used on instances of that type can appear on the statistical population. For example, a [[StatisticalPopulation]] representing all [[Person]]s with a [[homeLocation]] of East Podunk California would be described by applying the appropriate [[homeLocation]] and [[populationType]] properties to a [[StatisticalPopulation]] item that stands for that set of people.
The properties [[numConstraints]] and [[constraintProperty]] are used to specify which of the populations properties are used to specify the population. Note that the sense of "population" used here is the general sense of a statistical
population, and does not imply that the population consists of people. For example, a [[populationType]] of [[Event]] or [[NewsArticle]] could be used. See also [[Observation]], where a [[populationType]] such as [[Person]] or [[Event]] can be indicated directly. In most cases it may be better to use [[StatisticalVariable]] instead of [[StatisticalPopulation]].

inputs.name: populationType
inputs.label: Population Type
inputs.help: Indicates the populationType common to all members of a [[StatisticalPopulation]] or all cases within the scope of a [[StatisticalVariable]].

PaymentStatusType.name: PaymentStatusType
PaymentStatusType.help: A specific payment status. For example, PaymentDue, PaymentComplete, etc.

CheckOutAction.name: CheckOutAction
CheckOutAction.help:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check-in) or place (e.g. hotel).

Related actions:

* [[CheckInAction]]: The antonym of CheckOutAction.
* [[DepartAction]]: Unlike DepartAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
* [[CancelAction]]: Unlike CancelAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.

CovidTestingFacility.name: CovidTestingFacility
CovidTestingFacility.help:
A CovidTestingFacility is a [[MedicalClinic]] where testing for the COVID-19 Coronavirus
      disease is available. If the facility is being made available from an established [[Pharmacy]], [[Hotel]], or other
      non-medical organization, multiple types can be listed. This makes it easier to re-use existing schema.org information
      about that place, e.g. contact info, address, opening hours. Note that in an emergency, such information may not always be reliable.

inputs.name: downPayment
inputs.label: Down Payment
inputs.help: a type of payment made in cash during the onset of the purchase of an expensive good/service. The payment typically represents only a percentage of the full purchase price.

inputs.name: earlyPrepaymentPenalty
inputs.label: Early Prepayment Penalty
inputs.help: The amount to be paid as a penalty in the event of early payment of the loan.

inputs.name: loanPaymentAmount
inputs.label: Loan Payment Amount
inputs.help: The amount of money to pay in a single payment.

inputs.name: loanPaymentFrequency
inputs.label: Loan Payment Frequency
inputs.help: Frequency of payments due, i.e. number of months between payments. This is defined as a frequency, i.e. the reciprocal of a period of time.

inputs.name: numberOfLoanPayments
inputs.label: Number Of Loan Payments
inputs.help: The number of payments contractually required at origination to repay the loan. For monthly paying loans this is the number of months from the contractual first payment date to the maturity date.

Menu.name: Menu
Menu.help: A structured representation of food or drink items available from a FoodEstablishment.

inputs.name: hasMenuItem
inputs.label: Has Menu Item
inputs.help: A food or drink item contained in a menu or menu section.

inputs.name: hasMenuSection
inputs.label: Has Menu Section
inputs.help: A subgrouping of the menu (by dishes, course, serving time period, etc.).

Muscle.name: Muscle
Muscle.help: A muscle is an anatomical structure consisting of a contractile form of tissue that animals use to effect movement.

inputs.name: antagonist
inputs.label: Antagonist
inputs.help: The muscle whose action counteracts the specified muscle.

inputs.name: bloodSupply
inputs.label: Blood Supply
inputs.help: The blood vessel that carries blood from the heart to the muscle.

inputs.name: insertion
inputs.label: Insertion
inputs.help: The place of attachment of a muscle, or what the muscle moves.

inputs.name: muscleAction
inputs.label: Muscle Action
inputs.help: The movement the muscle generates.

inputs.name: nerve
inputs.label: Nerve
inputs.help: The underlying innervation associated with the muscle.

Accommodation.name: Accommodation
Accommodation.help:
An accommodation is a place that can accommodate human beings, e.g. a hotel room, a camping pitch, or a meeting room. Many accommodations are for overnight stays, but this is not a mandatory requirement. For more specific types of accommodations not defined in schema.org, one can use [[additionalType]] with external vocabularies.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

inputs.name: accommodationCategory
inputs.label: Accommodation Category
inputs.help: Category of an [[Accommodation]], following real estate conventions, e.g. RESO (see [PropertySubType](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/PropertySubType+Field), and [PropertyType](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/PropertyType+Field) fields  for suggested values).

inputs.name: accommodationFloorPlan
inputs.label: Accommodation Floor Plan
inputs.help: A floorplan of some [[Accommodation]].

inputs.name: amenityFeature
inputs.label: Amenity Feature
inputs.help: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

inputs.name: bed
inputs.label: Bed
inputs.help:
The type of bed or beds included in the accommodation. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you use bed directly with a text.
      If you want to indicate the quantity of a certain kind of bed, use an instance of BedDetails. For more detailed information, use the amenityFeature property.

inputs.name: floorLevel
inputs.label: Floor Level
inputs.help:
The floor level for an [[Accommodation]] in a multi-storey building. Since counting
  systems [vary internationally](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storey#Consecutive_number_floor_designations), the local system should be used where possible.

inputs.name: floorSize
inputs.label: Floor Size
inputs.help:
The size of the accommodation, e.g. in square meter or squarefoot.
Typical unit code(s): MTK for square meter, FTK for square foot, or YDK for square yard.

inputs.name: leaseLength
inputs.label: Lease Length
inputs.help: Length of the lease for some [[Accommodation]], either particular to some [[Offer]] or in some cases intrinsic to the property.

inputs.name: numberOfBathroomsTotal
inputs.label: Number Of Bathrooms Total
inputs.help: The total integer number of bathrooms in some [[Accommodation]], following real estate conventions as [documented in RESO](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/BathroomsTotalInteger+Field): "The simple sum of the number of bathrooms. For example for a property with two Full Bathrooms and one Half Bathroom, the Bathrooms Total Integer will be 3.". See also [[numberOfRooms]].

inputs.name: numberOfBedrooms
inputs.label: Number Of Bedrooms
inputs.help: The total integer number of bedrooms in a some [[Accommodation]], [[ApartmentComplex]] or [[FloorPlan]].

inputs.name: numberOfFullBathrooms
inputs.label: Number Of Full Bathrooms
inputs.help: Number of full bathrooms - The total number of full and ¾ bathrooms in an [[Accommodation]]. This corresponds to the [BathroomsFull field in RESO](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/BathroomsFull+Field).

inputs.name: numberOfPartialBathrooms
inputs.label: Number Of Partial Bathrooms
inputs.help: Number of partial bathrooms - The total number of half and ¼ bathrooms in an [[Accommodation]]. This corresponds to the [BathroomsPartial field in RESO](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/BathroomsPartial+Field).

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.label: Number Of Rooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.label: Occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person.

inputs.name: permittedUsage
inputs.label: Permitted Usage
inputs.help: Indications regarding the permitted usage of the accommodation.

inputs.name: petsAllowed
inputs.label: Pets Allowed
inputs.help: Indicates whether pets are allowed to enter the accommodation or lodging business. More detailed information can be put in a text value.

inputs.name: tourBookingPage
inputs.label: Tour Booking Page
inputs.help: A page providing information on how to book a tour of some [[Place]], such as an [[Accommodation]] or [[ApartmentComplex]] in a real estate setting, as well as other kinds of tours as appropriate.

inputs.name: yearBuilt
inputs.label: Year Built
inputs.help: The year an [[Accommodation]] was constructed. This corresponds to the [YearBuilt field in RESO](https://ddwiki.reso.org/display/DDW17/YearBuilt+Field).

Apartment.name: Apartment
Apartment.help: An apartment (in American English) or flat (in British English) is a self-contained housing unit (a type of residential real estate) that occupies only part of a building (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apartment).

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.label: Number Of Rooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.label: Occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person.

DeliveryTimeSettings.name: DeliveryTimeSettings
DeliveryTimeSettings.help: A DeliveryTimeSettings represents re-usable pieces of shipping information, relating to timing. It is designed for publication on an URL that may be referenced via the [[shippingSettingsLink]] property of an [[OfferShippingDetails]]. Several occurrences can be published, distinguished (and identified/referenced) by their different values for [[transitTimeLabel]].

inputs.name: deliveryTime
inputs.label: Delivery Time
inputs.help: The total delay between the receipt of the order and the goods reaching the final customer.

inputs.name: isUnlabelledFallback
inputs.label: Is Unlabelled Fallback
inputs.help: This can be marked 'true' to indicate that some published [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] or [[ShippingRateSettings]] are intended to apply to all [[OfferShippingDetails]] published by the same merchant, when referenced by a [[shippingSettingsLink]] in those settings. It is not meaningful to use a 'true' value for this property alongside a transitTimeLabel (for [[DeliveryTimeSettings]]) or shippingLabel (for [[ShippingRateSettings]]), since this property is for use with unlabelled settings.

inputs.name: shippingDestination
inputs.label: Shipping Destination
inputs.help: indicates (possibly multiple) shipping destinations. These can be defined in several ways, e.g. postalCode ranges.

inputs.name: transitTimeLabel
inputs.label: Transit Time Label
inputs.help: Label to match an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with a [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] (within the context of a [[shippingSettingsLink]] cross-reference).

TherapeuticProcedure.name: TherapeuticProcedure
TherapeuticProcedure.help: A medical procedure intended primarily for therapeutic purposes, aimed at improving a health condition.

inputs.name: adverseOutcome
inputs.label: Adverse Outcome
inputs.help: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or otherwise life-threatening or requiring immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriousAdverseOutcome instead.

inputs.name: doseSchedule
inputs.label: Dose Schedule
inputs.help: A dosing schedule for the drug for a given population, either observed, recommended, or maximum dose based on the type used.

inputs.name: drug
inputs.label: Drug
inputs.help: Specifying a drug or medicine used in a medication procedure.

EnergyConsumptionDetails.name: EnergyConsumptionDetails
EnergyConsumptionDetails.help: EnergyConsumptionDetails represents information related to the energy efficiency of a product that consumes energy. The information that can be provided is based on international regulations such as for example [EU directive 2017/1369](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2017/1369/oj) for energy labeling and the [Energy labeling rule](https://www.ftc.gov/enforcement/rules/rulemaking-regulatory-reform-proceedings/energy-water-use-labeling-consumer) under the Energy Policy and Conservation Act (EPCA) in the US.

inputs.name: energyEfficiencyScaleMax
inputs.label: Energy Efficiency Scale Max
inputs.help: Specifies the most energy efficient class on the regulated EU energy consumption scale for the product category a product belongs to. For example, energy consumption for televisions placed on the market after January 1, 2020 is scaled from D to A+++.

inputs.name: energyEfficiencyScaleMin
inputs.label: Energy Efficiency Scale Min
inputs.help: Specifies the least energy efficient class on the regulated EU energy consumption scale for the product category a product belongs to. For example, energy consumption for televisions placed on the market after January 1, 2020 is scaled from D to A+++.

inputs.name: hasEnergyEfficiencyCategory
inputs.label: Has Energy Efficiency Category
inputs.help: Defines the energy efficiency Category (which could be either a rating out of range of values or a yes/no certification) for a product according to an international energy efficiency standard.

Mountain.name: Mountain
Mountain.help: A mountain, like Mount Whitney or Mount Everest.

Newspaper.name: Newspaper
Newspaper.help: A publication containing information about varied topics that are pertinent to general information, a geographic area, or a specific subject matter (i.e. business, culture, education). Often published daily.

HobbyShop.name: HobbyShop
HobbyShop.help: A store that sells materials useful or necessary for various hobbies.

StatusEnumeration.name: StatusEnumeration
StatusEnumeration.help: Lists or enumerations dealing with status types.

BrokerageAccount.name: BrokerageAccount
BrokerageAccount.help: An account that allows an investor to deposit funds and place investment orders with a licensed broker or brokerage firm.

USNonprofitType.name: USNonprofitType
USNonprofitType.help: USNonprofitType: Non-profit organization type originating from the United States.

Demand.name: Demand
Demand.help: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.

inputs.name: acceptedPaymentMethod
inputs.label: Accepted Payment Method
inputs.help: The payment method(s) that are accepted in general by an organization, or for some specific demand or offer.

inputs.name: advanceBookingRequirement
inputs.label: Advance Booking Requirement
inputs.help: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

inputs.name: areaServed
inputs.label: Area Served
inputs.help: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

inputs.name: asin
inputs.label: Asin
inputs.help:
An Amazon Standard Identification Number (ASIN) is a 10-character alphanumeric unique identifier assigned by Amazon.com and its partners for product identification within the Amazon organization (summary from [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amazon_Standard_Identification_Number)'s article).

Note also that this is a definition for how to include ASINs in Schema.org data, and not a definition of ASINs in general - see documentation from Amazon for authoritative details.
ASINs are most commonly encoded as text strings, but the [asin] property supports URL/URI as potential values too.

inputs.name: availability
inputs.label: Availability
inputs.help: The availability of this item—for example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

inputs.name: availabilityEnds
inputs.label: Availability Ends
inputs.help: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: availabilityStarts
inputs.label: Availability Starts
inputs.help: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: availableAtOrFrom
inputs.label: Available At Or From
inputs.help: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

inputs.name: availableDeliveryMethod
inputs.label: Available Delivery Method
inputs.help: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

inputs.name: businessFunction
inputs.label: Business Function
inputs.help: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

inputs.name: deliveryLeadTime
inputs.label: Delivery Lead Time
inputs.help: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods either leaving the warehouse or being prepared for pickup, in case the delivery method is on site pickup.

inputs.name: eligibleCustomerType
inputs.label: Eligible Customer Type
inputs.help: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

inputs.name: eligibleDuration
inputs.label: Eligible Duration
inputs.help: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

inputs.name: eligibleQuantity
inputs.label: Eligible Quantity
inputs.help: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

inputs.name: eligibleRegion
inputs.label: Eligible Region
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: eligibleTransactionVolume
inputs.label: Eligible Transaction Volume
inputs.help: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

inputs.name: gtin
inputs.label: Gtin
inputs.help:
A Global Trade Item Number ([GTIN](https://www.gs1.org/standards/id-keys/gtin)). GTINs identify trade items, including products and services, using numeric identification codes.

A correct [[gtin]] value should be a valid GTIN, which means that it should be an all-numeric string of either 8, 12, 13 or 14 digits, or a "GS1 Digital Link" URL based on such a string. The numeric component should also have a [valid GS1 check digit](https://www.gs1.org/services/check-digit-calculator) and meet the other rules for valid GTINs. See also [GS1's GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) and [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Trade_Item_Number) for more details. Left-padding of the gtin values is not required or encouraged. The [[gtin]] property generalizes the earlier [[gtin8]], [[gtin12]], [[gtin13]], and [[gtin14]] properties.

The GS1 [digital link specifications](https://www.gs1.org/standards/Digital-Link/) expresses GTINs as URLs (URIs, IRIs, etc.).
Digital Links should be populated into the [[hasGS1DigitalLink]] attribute.

Note also that this is a definition for how to include GTINs in Schema.org data, and not a definition of GTINs in general - see the GS1 documentation for authoritative details.

inputs.name: gtin12
inputs.label: Gtin 12
inputs.help: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: gtin13
inputs.label: Gtin 13
