inputs.help: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: gtin14
inputs.label: Gtin 14
inputs.help: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: gtin8
inputs.label: Gtin 8
inputs.help: The GTIN-8 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: includesObject
inputs.label: Includes Object
inputs.help: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in  an [[Offer]] or [[ProductCollection]].

inputs.name: ineligibleRegion
inputs.label: Ineligible Region
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: inventoryLevel
inputs.label: Inventory Level
inputs.help: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

inputs.name: itemCondition
inputs.label: Item Condition
inputs.help: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition specifying the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer. Also used for product return policies to specify the condition of products accepted for returns.

inputs.name: itemOffered
inputs.label: Item Offered
inputs.help: An item being offered (or demanded). The transactional nature of the offer or demand is documented using [[businessFunction]], e.g. sell, lease etc. While several common expected types are listed explicitly in this definition, others can be used. Using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: mpn
inputs.label: Mpn
inputs.help: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

inputs.name: priceSpecification
inputs.label: Price Specification
inputs.help: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

inputs.name: seller
inputs.label: Seller
inputs.help: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

inputs.name: serialNumber
inputs.label: Serial Number
inputs.help: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

inputs.name: sku
inputs.label: Sku
inputs.help: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.label: Valid From
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.label: Valid Through
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: warranty
inputs.label: Warranty
inputs.help: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

WriteAction.name: WriteAction
WriteAction.help: The act of authoring written creative content.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.label: In Language
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: language
inputs.label: Language
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.

AddAction.name: AddAction
AddAction.help: The act of editing by adding an object to a collection.

Collection.name: Collection
Collection.help: A collection of items, e.g. creative works or products.

inputs.name: collectionSize
inputs.label: Collection Size
inputs.help: The number of items in the [[Collection]].

inputs.name: hasMember
inputs.label: Has Member
inputs.help: Links to a subsidiary Object or Collection. Typically used to link to component parts, such as a book linking to a page.  Note on transitivity: hasMember is   not defined as transitive, but applications may treat it as transitive as local needs   dictate.

inputs.name: memberOf
inputs.label: Member Of
inputs.help: Links from an Object or Collection to a containing Object or Collection.

Patient.name: Patient
Patient.help: A patient is any person recipient of health care services.

inputs.name: diagnosis
inputs.label: Diagnosis
inputs.help: One or more alternative conditions considered in the differential diagnosis process as output of a diagnosis process.

inputs.name: drug
inputs.label: Drug
inputs.help: Specifying a drug or medicine used in a medication procedure.

inputs.name: healthCondition
inputs.label: Health Condition
inputs.help: Specifying the health condition(s) of a patient, medical study, or other target audience.

UserComments.name: UserComments
UserComments.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

inputs.name: commentText
inputs.label: Comment Text
inputs.help: The text of the UserComment.

inputs.name: commentTime
inputs.label: Comment Time
inputs.help: The time at which the UserComment was made.

inputs.name: creator
inputs.label: Creator
inputs.help: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

inputs.name: discusses
inputs.label: Discusses
inputs.help: Specifies the CreativeWork associated with the UserComment.

inputs.name: replyToUrl
inputs.label: Reply To Url
inputs.help: The URL at which a reply may be posted to the specified UserComment.

OrganizeAction.name: OrganizeAction
OrganizeAction.help: The act of manipulating/administering/supervising/controlling one or more objects.

Motorcycle.name: Motorcycle
Motorcycle.help: A motorcycle or motorbike is a single-track, two-wheeled motor vehicle.

DiagnosticLab.name: DiagnosticLab
DiagnosticLab.help: A medical laboratory that offers on-site or off-site diagnostic services.

inputs.name: availableTest
inputs.label: Available Test
inputs.help: A diagnostic test or procedure offered by this lab.

AmpStory.name: AmpStory
AmpStory.help: A creative work with a visual storytelling format intended to be viewed online, particularly on mobile devices.

FilmAction.name: FilmAction
FilmAction.help: The act of capturing sound and moving images on film, video, or digitally.

Comment.name: Comment
Comment.help: A comment on an item - for example, a comment on a blog post. The comment's content is expressed via the [[text]] property, and its topic via [[about]], properties shared with all CreativeWorks.

inputs.name: downvoteCount
inputs.label: Downvote Count
inputs.help: The number of downvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

inputs.name: parentItem
inputs.label: Parent Item
inputs.help: The parent of a question, answer or item in general. Typically used for Q/A discussion threads e.g. a chain of comments with the first comment being an [[Article]] or other [[CreativeWork]]. See also [[comment]] which points from something to a comment about it.

inputs.name: sharedContent
inputs.label: Shared Content
inputs.help: A CreativeWork such as an image, video, or audio clip shared as part of this posting.

inputs.name: upvoteCount
inputs.label: Upvote Count
inputs.help: The number of upvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

Legislation.name: Legislation
Legislation.help: A legal document such as an act, decree, bill, etc. (enforceable or not) or a component of a legal act (like an article).

inputs.name: jurisdiction
inputs.label: Jurisdiction
inputs.help: Indicates a legal jurisdiction, e.g. of some legislation, or where some government service is based.

inputs.name: legislationApplies
inputs.label: Legislation Applies
inputs.help: Indicates that this legislation (or part of a legislation) somehow transfers another legislation in a different legislative context. This is an informative link, and it has no legal value. For legally-binding links of transposition, use the legislationTransposes property. For example an informative consolidated law of a European Union's member state "applies" the consolidated version of the European Directive implemented in it.

inputs.name: legislationChanges
inputs.label: Legislation Changes
inputs.help: Another legislation that this legislation changes. This encompasses the notions of amendment, replacement, correction, repeal, or other types of change. This may be a direct change (textual or non-textual amendment) or a consequential or indirect change. The property is to be used to express the existence of a change relationship between two acts rather than the existence of a consolidated version of the text that shows the result of the change. For consolidation relationships, use the legislationConsolidates property.

inputs.name: legislationConsolidates
inputs.label: Legislation Consolidates
inputs.help: Indicates another legislation taken into account in this consolidated legislation (which is usually the product of an editorial process that revises the legislation). This property should be used multiple times to refer to both the original version or the previous consolidated version, and to the legislations making the change.

inputs.name: legislationDate
inputs.label: Legislation Date
inputs.help: The date of adoption or signature of the legislation. This is the date at which the text is officially aknowledged to be a legislation, even though it might not even be published or in force.

inputs.name: legislationDateVersion
inputs.label: Legislation Date Version
inputs.help: The point-in-time at which the provided description of the legislation is valid (e.g.: when looking at the law on the 2016-04-07 (= dateVersion), I get the consolidation of 2015-04-12 of the "National Insurance Contributions Act 2015")

inputs.name: legislationIdentifier
inputs.label: Legislation Identifier
inputs.help: An identifier for the legislation. This can be either a string-based identifier, like the CELEX at EU level or the NOR in France, or a web-based, URL/URI identifier, like an ELI (European Legislation Identifier) or an URN-Lex.

inputs.name: legislationJurisdiction
inputs.label: Legislation Jurisdiction
inputs.help: The jurisdiction from which the legislation originates.

inputs.name: legislationLegalForce
inputs.label: Legislation Legal Force
inputs.help: Whether the legislation is currently in force, not in force, or partially in force.

inputs.name: legislationPassedBy
inputs.label: Legislation Passed By
inputs.help: The person or organization that originally passed or made the law: typically parliament (for primary legislation) or government (for secondary legislation). This indicates the "legal author" of the law, as opposed to its physical author.

inputs.name: legislationResponsible
inputs.label: Legislation Responsible
inputs.help: An individual or organization that has some kind of responsibility for the legislation. Typically the ministry who is/was in charge of elaborating the legislation, or the adressee for potential questions about the legislation once it is published.

inputs.name: legislationTransposes
inputs.label: Legislation Transposes
inputs.help: Indicates that this legislation (or part of legislation) fulfills the objectives set by another legislation, by passing appropriate implementation measures. Typically, some legislations of European Union's member states or regions transpose European Directives. This indicates a legally binding link between the 2 legislations.

inputs.name: legislationType
inputs.label: Legislation Type
inputs.help: The type of the legislation. Examples of values are "law", "act", "directive", "decree", "regulation", "statutory instrument", "loi organique", "règlement grand-ducal", etc., depending on the country.

inputs.name: codeValue
inputs.label: Code Value
inputs.help: A short textual code that uniquely identifies the value.

inputs.name: inCodeSet
inputs.label: In Code Set
inputs.help: A [[CategoryCodeSet]] that contains this category code.

HowToTip.name: HowToTip
HowToTip.help: An explanation in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It provides supplementary information about a technique, supply, author's preference, etc. It can explain what could be done, or what should not be done, but doesn't specify what should be done (see HowToDirection).

CarUsageType.name: CarUsageType
CarUsageType.help: A value indicating a special usage of a car, e.g. commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi.

PlaceOfWorship.name: PlaceOfWorship
PlaceOfWorship.help: Place of worship, such as a church, synagogue, or mosque.

AMRadioChannel.name: AMRadioChannel
AMRadioChannel.help: A radio channel that uses AM.

Periodical.name: Periodical
Periodical.help: A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended to continue indefinitely, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

QualitativeValue.name: QualitativeValue
QualitativeValue.help: A predefined value for a product characteristic, e.g. the power cord plug type 'US' or the garment sizes 'S', 'M', 'L', and 'XL'.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.label: Additional Property
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristic of the entity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: equal
inputs.label: Equal
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is equal to the object.

inputs.name: greater
inputs.label: Greater
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than the object.

inputs.name: greaterOrEqual
inputs.label: Greater Or Equal
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than or equal to the object.

inputs.name: lesser
inputs.label: Lesser
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than the object.

inputs.name: lesserOrEqual
inputs.label: Lesser Or Equal
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than or equal to the object.

inputs.name: nonEqual
inputs.label: Non Equal
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is not equal to the object.

inputs.name: valueReference
inputs.label: Value Reference
inputs.help: A secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature or a type of measurement.

MenuItem.name: MenuItem
MenuItem.help: A food or drink item listed in a menu or menu section.

inputs.name: menuAddOn
inputs.label: Menu Add On
inputs.help: Additional menu item(s) such as a side dish of salad or side order of fries that can be added to this menu item. Additionally it can be a menu section containing allowed add-on menu items for this menu item.

inputs.name: nutrition
inputs.label: Nutrition
inputs.help: Nutrition information about the recipe or menu item.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.label: Offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: suitableForDiet
inputs.label: Suitable For Diet
inputs.help: Indicates a dietary restriction or guideline for which this recipe or menu item is suitable, e.g. diabetic, halal etc.

MerchantReturnPolicy.name: MerchantReturnPolicy
MerchantReturnPolicy.help: A MerchantReturnPolicy provides information about product return policies associated with an [[Organization]], [[Product]], or [[Offer]].

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.label: Additional Property
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristic of the entity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: applicableCountry
inputs.label: Applicable Country
inputs.help: A country where a particular merchant return policy applies to, for example the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

inputs.name: customerRemorseReturnFees
inputs.label: Customer Remorse Return Fees
inputs.help: The type of return fees if the product is returned due to customer remorse.

inputs.name: customerRemorseReturnLabelSource
inputs.label: Customer Remorse Return Label Source
inputs.help: The method (from an enumeration) by which the customer obtains a return shipping label for a product returned due to customer remorse.

inputs.name: customerRemorseReturnShippingFeesAmount
inputs.label: Customer Remorse Return Shipping Fees Amount
inputs.help: The amount of shipping costs if a product is returned due to customer remorse. Applicable when property [[customerRemorseReturnFees]] equals [[ReturnShippingFees]].

inputs.name: inStoreReturnsOffered
inputs.label: In Store Returns Offered
inputs.help: Are in-store returns offered? (For more advanced return methods use the [[returnMethod]] property.)

inputs.name: itemCondition
inputs.label: Item Condition
inputs.help: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition specifying the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer. Also used for product return policies to specify the condition of products accepted for returns.

inputs.name: itemDefectReturnFees
inputs.label: Item Defect Return Fees
inputs.help: The type of return fees for returns of defect products.

inputs.name: itemDefectReturnLabelSource
inputs.label: Item Defect Return Label Source
inputs.help: The method (from an enumeration) by which the customer obtains a return shipping label for a defect product.

inputs.name: itemDefectReturnShippingFeesAmount
inputs.label: Item Defect Return Shipping Fees Amount
inputs.help: Amount of shipping costs for defect product returns. Applicable when property [[itemDefectReturnFees]] equals [[ReturnShippingFees]].

inputs.name: merchantReturnDays
inputs.label: Merchant Return Days
inputs.help: Specifies either a fixed return date or the number of days (from the delivery date) that a product can be returned. Used when the [[returnPolicyCategory]] property is specified as [[MerchantReturnFiniteReturnWindow]].

inputs.name: merchantReturnLink
inputs.label: Merchant Return Link
inputs.help: Specifies a Web page or service by URL, for product returns.

inputs.name: refundType
inputs.label: Refund Type
inputs.help: A refund type, from an enumerated list.

inputs.name: restockingFee
inputs.label: Restocking Fee
inputs.help: Use [[MonetaryAmount]] to specify a fixed restocking fee for product returns, or use [[Number]] to specify a percentage of the product price paid by the customer.

inputs.name: returnFees
inputs.label: Return Fees
inputs.help: The type of return fees for purchased products (for any return reason).

inputs.name: returnLabelSource
inputs.label: Return Label Source
inputs.help: The method (from an enumeration) by which the customer obtains a return shipping label for a product returned for any reason.

inputs.name: returnMethod
inputs.label: Return Method
inputs.help: The type of return method offered, specified from an enumeration.

inputs.name: returnPolicyCategory
inputs.label: Return Policy Category
inputs.help: Specifies an applicable return policy (from an enumeration).

inputs.name: returnPolicyCountry
inputs.label: Return Policy Country
inputs.help: The country where the product has to be sent to for returns, for example "Ireland" using the [[name]] property of [[Country]]. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1). Note that this can be different from the country where the product was originally shipped from or sent to.

inputs.name: returnPolicySeasonalOverride
inputs.label: Return Policy Seasonal Override
inputs.help: Seasonal override of a return policy.

inputs.name: returnShippingFeesAmount
inputs.label: Return Shipping Fees Amount
inputs.help: Amount of shipping costs for product returns (for any reason). Applicable when property [[returnFees]] equals [[ReturnShippingFees]].

DiagnosticProcedure.name: DiagnosticProcedure
DiagnosticProcedure.help: A medical procedure intended primarily for diagnostic, as opposed to therapeutic, purposes.

PerformingArtsTheater.name: PerformingArtsTheater
PerformingArtsTheater.help: A theater or other performing art center.

ActivateAction.name: ActivateAction
ActivateAction.help: The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).

GeoShape.name: GeoShape
GeoShape.help: The geographic shape of a place. A GeoShape can be described using several properties whose values are based on latitude/longitude pairs. Either whitespace or commas can be used to separate latitude and longitude; whitespace should be used when writing a list of several such points.

inputs.name: address
inputs.label: Address
inputs.help: Physical address of the item.

inputs.name: addressCountry
inputs.label: Address Country
inputs.help: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

inputs.name: box
inputs.label: Box
inputs.help: A box is the area enclosed by the rectangle formed by two points. The first point is the lower corner, the second point is the upper corner. A box is expressed as two points separated by a space character.

inputs.name: circle
inputs.label: Circle
inputs.help: A circle is the circular region of a specified radius centered at a specified latitude and longitude. A circle is expressed as a pair followed by a radius in meters.

inputs.name: elevation
inputs.label: Elevation
inputs.help: The elevation of a location ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)). Values may be of the form 'NUMBER UNIT\_OF\_MEASUREMENT' (e.g., '1,000 m', '3,200 ft') while numbers alone should be assumed to be a value in meters.

inputs.name: line
inputs.label: Line
inputs.help: A line is a point-to-point path consisting of two or more points. A line is expressed as a series of two or more point objects separated by space.

inputs.name: polygon
inputs.label: Polygon
inputs.help: A polygon is the area enclosed by a point-to-point path for which the starting and ending points are the same. A polygon is expressed as a series of four or more space delimited points where the first and final points are identical.

inputs.name: postalCode
inputs.label: Postal Code
inputs.help: The postal code. For example, 94043.

PerformAction.name: PerformAction
PerformAction.help: The act of participating in performance arts.

inputs.name: entertainmentBusiness
inputs.label: Entertainment Business
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The entertainment business where the action occurred.

CollegeOrUniversity.name: CollegeOrUniversity
CollegeOrUniversity.help: A college, university, or other third-level educational institution.

BefriendAction.name: BefriendAction
BefriendAction.help:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone (object) mutually/bidirectionally/symmetrically.

Related actions:

* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, BefriendAction implies that the connection is reciprocal.

FundingScheme.name: FundingScheme
FundingScheme.help:
A FundingScheme combines organizational, project and policy aspects of grant-based funding
    that sets guidelines, principles and mechanisms to support other kinds of projects and activities.
    Funding is typically organized via [[Grant]] funding. Examples of funding schemes: Swiss Priority Programmes (SPPs); EU Framework 7 (FP7); Horizon 2020; the NIH-R01 Grant Program; Wellcome institutional strategic support fund. For large scale public sector funding, the management and administration of grant awards is often handled by other, dedicated, organizations - [[FundingAgency]]s such as ERC, REA, ...

CreateAction.name: CreateAction
CreateAction.help: The act of deliberately creating/producing/generating/building a result out of the agent.

BroadcastEvent.name: BroadcastEvent
BroadcastEvent.help: An over the air or online broadcast event.

inputs.name: broadcastOfEvent
inputs.label: Broadcast Of Event
inputs.help: The event being broadcast such as a sporting event or awards ceremony.

inputs.name: isLiveBroadcast
inputs.label: Is Live Broadcast
inputs.help: True if the broadcast is of a live event.

inputs.name: subtitleLanguage
inputs.label: Subtitle Language
inputs.help: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: videoFormat
inputs.label: Video Format
inputs.help: The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).

ImagingTest.name: ImagingTest
ImagingTest.help: Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes.

inputs.name: imagingTechnique
inputs.label: Imaging Technique
inputs.help: Imaging technique used.

PropertyValue.name: PropertyValue
PropertyValue.help: A property-value pair, e.g. representing a feature of a product or place. Use the 'name' property for the name of the property. If there is an additional human-readable version of the value, put that into the 'description' property.\n\n Always use specific schema.org properties when a) they exist and b) you can populate them. Using PropertyValue as a substitute will typically not trigger the same effect as using the original, specific property.

inputs.name: maxValue
inputs.label: Max Value
inputs.help: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: measurementMethod
inputs.label: Measurement Method
inputs.help: A subproperty of [[measurementTechnique]] that can be used for specifying specific methods, in particular via [[MeasurementMethodEnum]].

inputs.name: measurementTechnique
inputs.label: Measurement Technique
inputs.help:
A technique, method or technology used in an [[Observation]], [[StatisticalVariable]] or [[Dataset]] (or [[DataDownload]], [[DataCatalog]]), corresponding to the method used for measuring the corresponding variable(s) (for datasets, described using [[variableMeasured]]; for [[Observation]], a [[StatisticalVariable]]). Often but not necessarily each [[variableMeasured]] will have an explicit representation as (or mapping to) an property such as those defined in Schema.org, or other RDF vocabularies and "knowledge graphs". In that case the subproperty of [[variableMeasured]] called [[measuredProperty]] is applicable.
    
The [[measurementTechnique]] property helps when extra clarification is needed about how a [[measuredProperty]] was measured. This is oriented towards scientific and scholarly dataset publication but may have broader applicability; it is not intended as a full representation of measurement, but can often serve as a high level summary for dataset discovery. 

For example, if [[variableMeasured]] is: molecule concentration, [[measurementTechnique]] could be: "mass spectrometry" or "nmr spectroscopy" or "colorimetry" or "immunofluorescence". If the [[variableMeasured]] is "depression rating", the [[measurementTechnique]] could be "Zung Scale" or "HAM-D" or "Beck Depression Inventory". 

If there are several [[variableMeasured]] properties recorded for some given data object, use a [[PropertyValue]] for each [[variableMeasured]] and attach the corresponding [[measurementTechnique]]. The value can also be from an enumeration, organized as a [[MeasurementMetholdEnumeration]].

inputs.name: minValue
inputs.label: Min Value
inputs.help: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: propertyID
inputs.label: Property ID
inputs.help:
A commonly used identifier for the characteristic represented by the property, e.g. a manufacturer or a standard code for a property. propertyID can be
(1) a prefixed string, mainly meant to be used with standards for product properties; (2) a site-specific, non-prefixed string (e.g. the primary key of the property or the vendor-specific ID of the property), or (3)
a URL indicating the type of the property, either pointing to an external vocabulary, or a Web resource that describes the property (e.g. a glossary entry).
Standards bodies should promote a standard prefix for the identifiers of properties from their standards.

inputs.name: unitCode
inputs.label: Unit Code
inputs.help: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

inputs.name: unitText
inputs.label: Unit Text
inputs.help: A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for unitCode.

inputs.name: value
inputs.label: Value
inputs.help:
The value of a [[QuantitativeValue]] (including [[Observation]]) or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: valueReference
inputs.label: Value Reference
inputs.help: A secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature or a type of measurement.

inputs.name: screenCount
inputs.label: Screen Count
inputs.help: The number of screens in the movie theater.

MedicalTrialDesign.name: MedicalTrialDesign
MedicalTrialDesign.help: Design models for medical trials. Enumerated type.

DislikeAction.name: DislikeAction
DislikeAction.help: The act of expressing a negative sentiment about the object. An agent dislikes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

SportsActivityLocation.name: SportsActivityLocation
SportsActivityLocation.help: A sports location, such as a playing field.

OnlineBusiness.name: OnlineBusiness
OnlineBusiness.help: A particular online business, either standalone or the online part of a broader organization. Examples include an eCommerce site, an online travel booking site, an online learning site, an online logistics and shipping provider, an online (virtual) doctor, etc.

AuthorizeAction.name: AuthorizeAction
AuthorizeAction.help: The act of granting permission to an object.

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.label: Recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

MortgageLoan.name: MortgageLoan
MortgageLoan.help: A loan in which property or real estate is used as collateral. (A loan securitized against some real estate.)

inputs.name: domiciledMortgage
inputs.label: Domiciled Mortgage
inputs.help: Whether borrower is a resident of the jurisdiction where the property is located.

inputs.name: loanMortgageMandateAmount
inputs.label: Loan Mortgage Mandate Amount
inputs.help: Amount of mortgage mandate that can be converted into a proper mortgage at a later stage.

ExerciseAction.name: ExerciseAction
ExerciseAction.help: The act of participating in exertive activity for the purposes of improving health and fitness.

inputs.name: course
inputs.label: Course
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The course where this action was taken.

inputs.name: diet
inputs.label: Diet
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The diet used in this action.

inputs.name: distance
inputs.label: Distance
inputs.help: The distance travelled, e.g. exercising or travelling.

inputs.name: exerciseCourse
inputs.label: Exercise Course
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The course where this action was taken.

inputs.name: exercisePlan
inputs.label: Exercise Plan
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The exercise plan used on this action.

inputs.name: exerciseRelatedDiet
inputs.label: Exercise Related Diet
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The diet used in this action.

inputs.name: exerciseType
inputs.label: Exercise Type
inputs.help: Type(s) of exercise or activity, such as strength training, flexibility training, aerobics, cardiac rehabilitation, etc.

inputs.name: fromLocation
inputs.label: From Location
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

inputs.name: opponent
inputs.label: Opponent
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The opponent on this action.

inputs.name: sportsActivityLocation
inputs.label: Sports Activity Location
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The sports activity location where this action occurred.

inputs.name: sportsEvent
inputs.label: Sports Event
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The sports event where this action occurred.

inputs.name: sportsTeam
inputs.label: Sports Team
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The sports team that participated on this action.

inputs.name: toLocation
inputs.label: To Location
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

TheaterGroup.name: TheaterGroup
TheaterGroup.help: A theater group or company, for example, the Royal Shakespeare Company or Druid Theatre.

DrugCost.name: DrugCost
DrugCost.help: The cost per unit of a medical drug. Note that this type is not meant to represent the price in an offer of a drug for sale; see the Offer type for that. This type will typically be used to tag wholesale or average retail cost of a drug, or maximum reimbursable cost. Costs of medical drugs vary widely depending on how and where they are paid for, so while this type captures some of the variables, costs should be used with caution by consumers of this schema's markup.

inputs.name: applicableLocation
inputs.label: Applicable Location
inputs.help: The location in which the status applies.

inputs.name: costCategory
inputs.label: Cost Category
inputs.help: The category of cost, such as wholesale, retail, reimbursement cap, etc.

inputs.name: costCurrency
inputs.label: Cost Currency
inputs.help: The currency (in 3-letter) of the drug cost. See: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217.

inputs.name: costOrigin
inputs.label: Cost Origin
inputs.help: Additional details to capture the origin of the cost data. For example, 'Medicare Part B'.

inputs.name: costPerUnit
inputs.label: Cost Per Unit
inputs.help: The cost per unit of the drug.

inputs.name: drugUnit
inputs.label: Drug Unit
inputs.help: The unit in which the drug is measured, e.g. '5 mg tablet'.

MotorizedBicycle.name: MotorizedBicycle
MotorizedBicycle.help: A motorized bicycle is a bicycle with an attached motor used to power the vehicle, or to assist with pedaling.

MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.name: MedicalObservationalStudyDesign
MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.help: Design models for observational medical studies. Enumerated type.

MedicalGuidelineContraindication.name: MedicalGuidelineContraindication
MedicalGuidelineContraindication.help: A guideline contraindication that designates a process as harmful and where quality of the data supporting the contraindication is sound.

OpinionNewsArticle.name: OpinionNewsArticle
OpinionNewsArticle.help: An [[OpinionNewsArticle]] is a [[NewsArticle]] that primarily expresses opinions rather than journalistic reporting of news and events. For example, a [[NewsArticle]] consisting of a column or [[Blog]]/[[BlogPosting]] entry in the Opinions section of a news publication.

Vehicle.name: Vehicle
Vehicle.help: A vehicle is a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space.

inputs.name: accelerationTime
inputs.label: Acceleration Time
inputs.help:
The time needed to accelerate the vehicle from a given start velocity to a given target velocity.

Typical unit code(s): SEC for seconds

* Note: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for seconds/0..100 km/h or seconds/0..60 mph. Simply use "SEC" for seconds and indicate the velocities in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]], or use [[valueReference]] with a [[QuantitativeValue]] of 0..60 mph or 0..100 km/h to specify the reference speeds.

inputs.name: bodyType
inputs.label: Body Type
inputs.help: Indicates the design and body style of the vehicle (e.g. station wagon, hatchback, etc.).

inputs.name: callSign
inputs.label: Call Sign
inputs.help: A [callsign](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_sign), as used in broadcasting and radio communications to identify people, radio and TV stations, or vehicles.

inputs.name: cargoVolume
inputs.label: Cargo Volume
inputs.help:
The available volume for cargo or luggage. For automobiles, this is usually the trunk volume.

Typical unit code(s): LTR for liters, FTQ for cubic foot/feet

Note: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: dateVehicleFirstRegistered
inputs.label: Date Vehicle First Registered
inputs.help: The date of the first registration of the vehicle with the respective public authorities.

inputs.name: driveWheelConfiguration
inputs.label: Drive Wheel Configuration
inputs.help: The drive wheel configuration, i.e. which roadwheels will receive torque from the vehicle's engine via the drivetrain.

inputs.name: emissionsCO2
inputs.label: Emissions CO 2
inputs.help: The CO2 emissions in g/km. When used in combination with a QuantitativeValue, put "g/km" into the unitText property of that value, since there is no UN/CEFACT Common Code for "g/km".

inputs.name: fuelCapacity
inputs.label: Fuel Capacity
inputs.help: The capacity of the fuel tank or in the case of electric cars, the battery. If there are multiple components for storage, this should indicate the total of all storage of the same type.\n\nTypical unit code(s): LTR for liters, GLL of US gallons, GLI for UK / imperial gallons, AMH for ampere-hours (for electrical vehicles).

inputs.name: fuelConsumption
inputs.label: Fuel Consumption
inputs.help:
The amount of fuel consumed for traveling a particular distance or temporal duration with the given vehicle (e.g. liters per 100 km).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for liters per 100 km.  Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. L/100 km.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel consumption to another value.

inputs.name: fuelEfficiency
inputs.label: Fuel Efficiency
inputs.help:
The distance traveled per unit of fuel used; most commonly miles per gallon (mpg) or kilometers per liter (km/L).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for miles per gallon or kilometers per liter. Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. mpg or km/L.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel economy to another value.

inputs.name: fuelType
inputs.label: Fuel Type
inputs.help: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

inputs.name: knownVehicleDamages
inputs.label: Known Vehicle Damages
inputs.help: A textual description of known damages, both repaired and unrepaired.

inputs.name: meetsEmissionStandard
inputs.label: Meets Emission Standard
inputs.help: Indicates that the vehicle meets the respective emission standard.

inputs.name: mileageFromOdometer
inputs.label: Mileage From Odometer
inputs.help: The total distance travelled by the particular vehicle since its initial production, as read from its odometer.\n\nTypical unit code(s): KMT for kilometers, SMI for statute miles.

inputs.name: modelDate
inputs.label: Model Date
inputs.help: The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).

inputs.name: numberOfAirbags
inputs.label: Number Of Airbags
inputs.help: The number or type of airbags in the vehicle.

inputs.name: numberOfAxles
inputs.label: Number Of Axles
inputs.help: The number of axles.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62.

inputs.name: numberOfDoors
inputs.label: Number Of Doors
inputs.help: The number of doors.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62.

inputs.name: numberOfForwardGears
inputs.label: Number Of Forward Gears
inputs.help: The total number of forward gears available for the transmission system of the vehicle.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62.

inputs.name: numberOfPreviousOwners
inputs.label: Number Of Previous Owners
inputs.help: The number of owners of the vehicle, including the current one.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62.

inputs.name: payload
inputs.label: Payload
inputs.help:
The permitted weight of passengers and cargo, EXCLUDING the weight of the empty vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: Many databases specify the permitted TOTAL weight instead, which is the sum of [[weight]] and [[payload]]
* Note 2: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 3: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 4: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: productionDate
inputs.label: Production Date
inputs.help: The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.

inputs.name: purchaseDate
inputs.label: Purchase Date
inputs.help: The date the item, e.g. vehicle, was purchased by the current owner.

inputs.name: seatingCapacity
inputs.label: Seating Capacity
inputs.help: The number of persons that can be seated (e.g. in a vehicle), both in terms of the physical space available, and in terms of limitations set by law.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62 for persons.

inputs.name: speed
inputs.label: Speed
inputs.help:
The speed range of the vehicle. If the vehicle is powered by an engine, the upper limit of the speed range (indicated by [[maxValue]]) should be the maximum speed achievable under regular conditions.

Typical unit code(s): KMH for km/h, HM for mile per hour (0.447 04 m/s), KNT for knot

*Note 1: Use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate the range. Typically, the minimal value is zero.
* Note 2: There are many different ways of measuring the speed range. You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the [[valueReference]] property.

inputs.name: steeringPosition
inputs.label: Steering Position
inputs.help: The position of the steering wheel or similar device (mostly for cars).

inputs.name: tongueWeight
inputs.label: Tongue Weight
inputs.help:
The permitted vertical load (TWR) of a trailer attached to the vehicle. Also referred to as Tongue Load Rating (TLR) or Vertical Load Rating (VLR).

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: trailerWeight
inputs.label: Trailer Weight
inputs.help:
The permitted weight of a trailer attached to the vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound
* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: vehicleConfiguration
inputs.label: Vehicle Configuration
inputs.help: A short text indicating the configuration of the vehicle, e.g. '5dr hatchback ST 2.5 MT 225 hp' or 'limited edition'.

inputs.name: vehicleEngine
inputs.label: Vehicle Engine
inputs.help: Information about the engine or engines of the vehicle.

inputs.name: vehicleIdentificationNumber
inputs.label: Vehicle Identification Number
inputs.help: The Vehicle Identification Number (VIN) is a unique serial number used by the automotive industry to identify individual motor vehicles.

inputs.name: vehicleInteriorColor
inputs.label: Vehicle Interior Color
inputs.help: The color or color combination of the interior of the vehicle.

inputs.name: vehicleInteriorType
inputs.label: Vehicle Interior Type
inputs.help: The type or material of the interior of the vehicle (e.g. synthetic fabric, leather, wood, etc.). While most interior types are characterized by the material used, an interior type can also be based on vehicle usage or target audience.

inputs.name: vehicleModelDate
inputs.label: Vehicle Model Date
inputs.help: The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).

inputs.name: vehicleSeatingCapacity
inputs.label: Vehicle Seating Capacity
inputs.help: The number of passengers that can be seated in the vehicle, both in terms of the physical space available, and in terms of limitations set by law.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62 for persons.

inputs.name: vehicleSpecialUsage
inputs.label: Vehicle Special Usage
inputs.help: Indicates whether the vehicle has been used for special purposes, like commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi. The legislation in many countries requires this information to be revealed when offering a car for sale.

inputs.name: vehicleTransmission
inputs.label: Vehicle Transmission
inputs.help: The type of component used for transmitting the power from a rotating power source to the wheels or other relevant component(s) ("gearbox" for cars).

inputs.name: weightTotal
inputs.label: Weight Total
inputs.help:
The permitted total weight of the loaded vehicle, including passengers and cargo and the weight of the empty vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: wheelbase
inputs.label: Wheelbase
inputs.help: The distance between the centers of the front and rear wheels.\n\nTypical unit code(s): CMT for centimeters, MTR for meters, INH for inches, FOT for foot/feet.

OpeningHoursSpecification.name: OpeningHoursSpecification
OpeningHoursSpecification.help:
A structured value providing information about the opening hours of a place or a certain service inside a place.


The place is __open__ if the [[opens]] property is specified, and __closed__ otherwise.

If the value for the [[closes]] property is less than the value for the [[opens]] property then the hour range is assumed to span over the next day.

inputs.name: closes
inputs.label: Closes
inputs.help: The closing hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.

inputs.name: dayOfWeek
inputs.label: Day Of Week
inputs.help: The day of the week for which these opening hours are valid.

inputs.name: opens
inputs.label: Opens
inputs.help: The opening hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.label: Valid From
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.label: Valid Through
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

MedicalAudience.name: MedicalAudience
MedicalAudience.help: Target audiences for medical web pages.

Code.name: Code
Code.help: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

RsvpAction.name: RsvpAction
RsvpAction.help: The act of notifying an event organizer as to whether you expect to attend the event.

inputs.name: additionalNumberOfGuests
inputs.label: Additional Number Of Guests
inputs.help: If responding yes, the number of guests who will attend in addition to the invitee.

inputs.name: comment
inputs.label: Comment
inputs.help: Comments, typically from users.

inputs.name: rsvpResponse
inputs.label: Rsvp Response
inputs.help: The response (yes, no, maybe) to the RSVP.

LoseAction.name: LoseAction
LoseAction.help: The act of being defeated in a competitive activity.

inputs.name: winner
inputs.label: Winner
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The winner of the action.

DrugPregnancyCategory.name: DrugPregnancyCategory
DrugPregnancyCategory.help: Categories that represent an assessment of the risk of fetal injury due to a drug or pharmaceutical used as directed by the mother during pregnancy.

SizeSystemEnumeration.name: SizeSystemEnumeration
SizeSystemEnumeration.help: Enumerates common size systems for different categories of products, for example "EN-13402" or "UK" for wearables or "Imperial" for screws.

FollowAction.name: FollowAction
FollowAction.help:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from.

Related actions:

* [[BefriendAction]]: Unlike BefriendAction, FollowAction implies that the connection is *not* necessarily reciprocal.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, FollowAction implies that the follower acts as an active agent constantly/actively polling for updates.
* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in getting updates from the object.
* [[TrackAction]]: Unlike TrackAction, FollowAction refers to the polling of updates of all aspects of animate objects rather than the location of inanimate objects (e.g. you track a package, but you don't follow it).

inputs.name: followee
inputs.label: Followee
inputs.help: A sub property of object. The person or organization being followed.

BedDetails.name: BedDetails
BedDetails.help: An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also [[BedType]] (under development).

inputs.name: numberOfBeds
inputs.label: Number Of Beds
inputs.help: The quantity of the given bed type available in the HotelRoom, Suite, House, or Apartment.

inputs.name: typeOfBed
inputs.label: Type Of Bed
inputs.help: The type of bed to which the BedDetail refers, i.e. the type of bed available in the quantity indicated by quantity.

Suite.name: Suite
Suite.help:
A suite in a hotel or other public accommodation, denotes a class of luxury accommodations, the key feature of which is multiple rooms (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suite_(hotel)).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

inputs.name: bed
inputs.label: Bed
inputs.help:
The type of bed or beds included in the accommodation. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you use bed directly with a text.
      If you want to indicate the quantity of a certain kind of bed, use an instance of BedDetails. For more detailed information, use the amenityFeature property.

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.label: Number Of Rooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.label: Occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person.

PaymentService.name: PaymentService
PaymentService.help: A Service to transfer funds from a person or organization to a beneficiary person or organization.

GovernmentOffice.name: GovernmentOffice
GovernmentOffice.help: A government office—for example, an IRS or DMV office.

InfectiousDisease.name: InfectiousDisease
InfectiousDisease.help: An infectious disease is a clinically evident human disease resulting from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, like pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. To be considered an infectious disease, such pathogens are known to be able to cause this disease.

inputs.name: infectiousAgent
inputs.label: Infectious Agent
inputs.help: The actual infectious agent, such as a specific bacterium.

inputs.name: infectiousAgentClass
inputs.label: Infectious Agent Class
inputs.help: The class of infectious agent (bacteria, prion, etc.) that causes the disease.

inputs.name: transmissionMethod
inputs.label: Transmission Method
inputs.help: How the disease spreads, either as a route or vector, for example 'direct contact', 'Aedes aegypti', etc.

PublicToilet.name: PublicToilet
PublicToilet.help: A public toilet is a room or small building containing one or more toilets (and possibly also urinals) which is available for use by the general public, or by customers or employees of certain businesses.

DrugClass.name: DrugClass
DrugClass.help: A class of medical drugs, e.g., statins. Classes can represent general pharmacological class, common mechanisms of action, common physiological effects, etc.

inputs.name: drug
inputs.label: Drug
inputs.help: Specifying a drug or medicine used in a medication procedure.

EngineSpecification.name: EngineSpecification
EngineSpecification.help: Information about the engine of the vehicle. A vehicle can have multiple engines represented by multiple engine specification entities.

inputs.name: engineDisplacement
inputs.label: Engine Displacement
inputs.help:
The volume swept by all of the pistons inside the cylinders of an internal combustion engine in a single movement. 

Typical unit code(s): CMQ for cubic centimeter, LTR for liters, INQ for cubic inches
* Note 1: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the [[valueReference]] property.
* Note 2: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: enginePower
inputs.label: Engine Power
inputs.help:
The power of the vehicle's engine.
    Typical unit code(s): KWT for kilowatt, BHP for brake horsepower, N12 for metric horsepower (PS, with 1 PS = 735,49875 W)

* Note 1: There are many different ways of measuring an engine's power. For an overview, see  [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horsepower#Engine\_power\_test\_codes](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horsepower#Engine_power_test_codes).
* Note 2: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the [[valueReference]] property.
* Note 3: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: engineType
inputs.label: Engine Type
inputs.help: The type of engine or engines powering the vehicle.

inputs.name: fuelType
inputs.label: Fuel Type
inputs.help: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

inputs.name: torque
inputs.label: Torque
inputs.help:
The torque (turning force) of the vehicle's engine.

Typical unit code(s): NU for newton metre (N m), F17 for pound-force per foot, or F48 for pound-force per inch

* Note 1: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined (e.g. reference RPM) using the [[valueReference]] property.
* Note 2: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

WebContent.name: WebContent
WebContent.help: WebContent is a type representing all [[WebPage]], [[WebSite]] and [[WebPageElement]] content. It is sometimes the case that detailed distinctions between Web pages, sites and their parts are not always important or obvious. The  [[WebContent]] type makes it easier to describe Web-addressable content without requiring such distinctions to always be stated. (The intent is that the existing types [[WebPage]], [[WebSite]] and [[WebPageElement]] will eventually be declared as subtypes of [[WebContent]].)

Conversation.name: Conversation
Conversation.help: One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.

Manuscript.name: Manuscript
Manuscript.help: A book, document, or piece of music written by hand rather than typed or printed.

Substance.name: Substance
Substance.help: Any matter of defined composition that has discrete existence, whose origin may be biological, mineral or chemical.

inputs.name: activeIngredient
inputs.label: Active Ingredient
inputs.help: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

inputs.name: maximumIntake
inputs.label: Maximum Intake
inputs.help: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

RadioEpisode.name: RadioEpisode
RadioEpisode.help: A radio episode which can be part of a series or season.

IPTCDigitalSourceEnumeration.name: IPTCDigitalSourceEnumeration
IPTCDigitalSourceEnumeration.help: IPTC "Digital Source" codes for use with the [[digitalSourceType]] property, providing information about the source for a digital media object. In general these codes are not declared here to be mutually exclusive, although some combinations would be contradictory if applied simultaneously, or might be considered mutually incompatible by upstream maintainers of the definitions. See the IPTC documentation for detailed definitions of all terms.

Ligament.name: Ligament
Ligament.help: A short band of tough, flexible, fibrous connective tissue that functions to connect multiple bones, cartilages, and structurally support joints.

Protein.name: Protein
Protein.help: Protein is here used in its widest possible definition, as classes of amino acid based molecules. Amyloid-beta Protein in human (UniProt P05067), eukaryota (e.g. an OrthoDB group) or even a single molecule that one can point to are all of type :Protein. A protein can thus be a subclass of another protein, e.g. :Protein as a UniProt record can have multiple isoforms inside it which would also be :Protein. They can be imagined, synthetic, hypothetical or naturally occurring.

inputs.name: hasBioPolymerSequence
inputs.label: Has Bio Polymer Sequence
inputs.help: A symbolic representation of a BioChemEntity. For example, a nucleotide sequence of a Gene or an amino acid sequence of a Protein.

SuspendAction.name: SuspendAction
SuspendAction.help: The act of momentarily pausing a device or application (e.g. pause music playback or pause a timer).

HyperToc.name: HyperToc
HyperToc.help: A HyperToc represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as [[VideoObject]], [[AudioObject]]. Items in the table of contents are indicated using the [[tocEntry]] property, and typed [[HyperTocEntry]]. For cases where the same larger work is split into multiple files, [[associatedMedia]] can be used on individual [[HyperTocEntry]] items.

inputs.name: associatedMedia
inputs.label: Associated Media
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

inputs.name: tocEntry
inputs.label: Toc Entry
inputs.help: Indicates a [[HyperTocEntry]] in a [[HyperToc]].

DoseSchedule.name: DoseSchedule
DoseSchedule.help: A specific dosing schedule for a drug or supplement.

inputs.name: doseUnit
inputs.label: Dose Unit
inputs.help: The unit of the dose, e.g. 'mg'.

inputs.name: doseValue
inputs.label: Dose Value
inputs.help: The value of the dose, e.g. 500.

inputs.name: frequency
inputs.label: Frequency
inputs.help: How often the dose is taken, e.g. 'daily'.

inputs.name: targetPopulation
inputs.label: Target Population
inputs.help: Characteristics of the population for which this is intended, or which typically uses it, e.g. 'adults'.

MathSolver.name: MathSolver
MathSolver.help: A math solver which is capable of solving a subset of mathematical problems.

inputs.name: mathExpression
inputs.label: Math Expression
inputs.help: A mathematical expression (e.g. 'x^2-3x=0') that may be solved for a specific variable, simplified, or transformed. This can take many formats, e.g. LaTeX, Ascii-Math, or math as you would write with a keyboard.

AchieveAction.name: AchieveAction
AchieveAction.help: The act of accomplishing something via previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing process.

BoardingPolicyType.name: BoardingPolicyType
BoardingPolicyType.help: A type of boarding policy used by an airline.

Specialty.name: Specialty
Specialty.help: Any branch of a field in which people typically develop specific expertise, usually after significant study, time, and effort.

InfectiousAgentClass.name: InfectiousAgentClass
InfectiousAgentClass.help: Classes of agents or pathogens that transmit infectious diseases. Enumerated type.

MedicalObservationalStudy.name: MedicalObservationalStudy
MedicalObservationalStudy.help: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

inputs.name: studyDesign
inputs.label: Study Design
inputs.help: Specifics about the observational study design (enumerated).

JoinAction.name: JoinAction
JoinAction.help:
An agent joins an event/group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, JoinAction refers to joining a group/team of people.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, JoinAction does not imply that you'll be receiving updates.
* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, JoinAction does not imply that you'll be polling for updates.

inputs.name: event
inputs.label: Event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

Bone.name: Bone
Bone.help: Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.

UnitPriceSpecification.name: UnitPriceSpecification
UnitPriceSpecification.help: The price asked for a given offer by the respective organization or person.

inputs.name: billingDuration
inputs.label: Billing Duration
inputs.help: Specifies for how long this price (or price component) will be billed. Can be used, for example, to model the contractual duration of a subscription or payment plan. Type can be either a Duration or a Number (in which case the unit of measurement, for example month, is specified by the unitCode property).

inputs.name: billingIncrement
inputs.label: Billing Increment
inputs.help: This property specifies the minimal quantity and rounding increment that will be the basis for the billing. The unit of measurement is specified by the unitCode property.

inputs.name: billingStart
inputs.label: Billing Start
inputs.help: Specifies after how much time this price (or price component) becomes valid and billing starts. Can be used, for example, to model a price increase after the first year of a subscription. The unit of measurement is specified by the unitCode property.

inputs.name: priceComponentType
inputs.label: Price Component Type
inputs.help: Identifies a price component (for example, a line item on an invoice), part of the total price for an offer.

inputs.name: priceType
inputs.label: Price Type
inputs.help: Defines the type of a price specified for an offered product, for example a list price, a (temporary) sale price or a manufacturer suggested retail price. If multiple prices are specified for an offer the [[priceType]] property can be used to identify the type of each such specified price. The value of priceType can be specified as a value from enumeration PriceTypeEnumeration or as a free form text string for price types that are not already predefined in PriceTypeEnumeration.

inputs.name: referenceQuantity
inputs.label: Reference Quantity
inputs.help: The reference quantity for which a certain price applies, e.g. 1 EUR per 4 kWh of electricity. This property is a replacement for unitOfMeasurement for the advanced cases where the price does not relate to a standard unit.

inputs.name: unitCode
inputs.label: Unit Code
inputs.help: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

inputs.name: unitText
inputs.label: Unit Text
inputs.help: A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for unitCode.

WarrantyScope.name: WarrantyScope
WarrantyScope.help:
A range of services that will be provided to a customer free of charge in case of a defect or malfunction of a product.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Labor-BringIn
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-BringIn
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-PickUp

Resort.name: Resort
Resort.help:
A resort is a place used for relaxation or recreation, attracting visitors for holidays or vacations. Resorts are places, towns or sometimes commercial establishments operated by a single company (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resort).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

EmployerReview.name: EmployerReview
EmployerReview.help: An [[EmployerReview]] is a review of an [[Organization]] regarding its role as an employer, written by a current or former employee of that organization.

TaxiService.name: TaxiService
TaxiService.help: A service for a vehicle for hire with a driver for local travel. Fares are usually calculated based on distance traveled.

DateTime.name: DateTime
DateTime.help: A combination of date and time of day in the form [-]CCYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss[Z|(+|-)hh:mm] (see Chapter 5.4 of ISO 8601).

Relation.name: Relation
Relation.help: The top level relation class. It connects at least two Things. An instance of a Relation may have some datatype and object properties: a general description (datatype property) like any Thing; a certainty (for 'certain', 'quite probable', 'uncertain','unknown'); a date (use either the date datatype property or the Date class and isAssociatedWithDate object property); a state (relationState); a location (use the Place class and isAssociatedWithPlace object property); a source of information that can be used as an evidence for it (use either source datatype property or hasSource object property). This Relation is the most generic one; it is not oriented.

inputs.name: isEvidencedBy
inputs.label: Is Evidenced By
inputs.help: Connects a Relation to a Record Resource that is used for proving is existence or describing it.

inputs.name: relationConnects
inputs.label: Relation Connects
inputs.help: Connects an n-ary Relation to any of the Things involved.

inputs.name: relationHasSource
inputs.label: Relation Has Source
inputs.help: Connects an n-ary Relation to a Thing that is its source.

inputs.name: relationHasTarget
inputs.label: Relation Has Target
inputs.help: Connects an n-ary Relation to a Thing that is its target.

inputs.name: relationState
inputs.label: Relation State
inputs.help: Used to qualify the state of a Relation (e. g. present, past, ongoing, unknown).

Object.name: Object
Object.help: An Object is an intellectual entity, sometimes called a "work", "digital object", etc. Objects have descriptive metadata, access metadata, may contain files and other Objects as member "components". Each level of a work is therefore represented by an Object instance, and is capable of standing on its own, being linked to from Collections and other Objects. Member Objects can be ordered using the ORE Proxy class.

inputs.name: hasFile
inputs.label: Has File
inputs.help: Links to a File contained by this Object.

inputs.name: hasMember
inputs.label: Has Member
inputs.help: Links to a subsidiary Object or Collection. Typically used to link to component parts, such as a book linking to a page.  Note on transitivity: hasMember is   not defined as transitive, but applications may treat it as transitive as local needs   dictate.

inputs.name: memberOf
inputs.label: Member Of
inputs.help: Links from an Object or Collection to a containing Object or Collection.

ComputationalWorkflow.name: ComputationalWorkflow
ComputationalWorkflow.help: A computational workflow consists of an orchestrated and repeatable  pattern of activity enabled by the systematic organization of resources  into processes that transform materials, provide services, or process information (source Wikipedia.org). It is executed by a computational process and is thus distinct from laboratory or business workflows.

inputs.name: input
inputs.label: Computational Workflow Input
inputs.help: An input required to use the computational workflow (eg. Excel spreadsheet, BAM file)

inputs.name: output
inputs.label: Computational Workflow Output
inputs.help: An output produced by the computational workflow

FormalParameter.name: FormalParameter
FormalParameter.help: A FormalParameter is an identified variable used to stand for the actual value(s) that are consumed/produced by a set of steps

File.name: File
File.help: A media object, such as an image, video, audio, or text object embedded in a web page or a downloadable dataset i.e. DataDownload. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObject's).

inputs.name: associatedArticle
inputs.label: Associated Article
inputs.help: A NewsArticle associated with the Media Object.

inputs.name: bitrate
inputs.label: Bitrate
inputs.help: The bitrate of the media object.

inputs.name: contentSize
inputs.label: Content Size
inputs.help: File size in (mega/kilo)bytes.

inputs.name: contentUrl
inputs.label: Content Url
inputs.help: Actual bytes of the media object, for example the image file or video file.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.label: Duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: embedUrl
inputs.label: Embed Url
inputs.help: A URL pointing to a player for a specific video. In general, this is the information in the ```src``` element of an ```embed``` tag and should not be the same as the content of the ```loc``` tag.

inputs.name: encodesCreativeWork
inputs.label: Encodes Creative Work
inputs.help: The CreativeWork encoded by this media object.

inputs.name: encodingFormat
inputs.label: Encoding Format
inputs.help:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml) and [MDN reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types)), e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.

In cases where a [[CreativeWork]] has several media type representations, [[encoding]] can be used to indicate each [[MediaObject]] alongside particular [[encodingFormat]] information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.label: End Time
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: fileOf
inputs.label: File Of
inputs.help: Links from a File to its containing Object.

inputs.name: height
inputs.label: Height
inputs.help: The height of the item.

inputs.name: ineligibleRegion
inputs.label: Ineligible Region
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: interpretedAsClaim
inputs.label: Interpreted As Claim
inputs.help: Used to indicate a specific claim contained, implied, translated or refined from the content of a [[MediaObject]] or other [[CreativeWork]]. The interpreting party can be indicated using [[claimInterpreter]].

inputs.name: playerType
inputs.label: Player Type
inputs.help: Player type required—for example, Flash or Silverlight.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.label: Production Company
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item, e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: regionsAllowed
inputs.label: Regions Allowed
inputs.help: The regions where the media is allowed. If not specified, then it's assumed to be allowed everywhere. Specify the countries in [ISO 3166 format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166).

inputs.name: requiresSubscription
inputs.label: Requires Subscription
inputs.help: Indicates if use of the media require a subscription  (either paid or free). Allowed values are ```true``` or ```false``` (note that an earlier version had 'yes', 'no').

inputs.name: sha256
inputs.label: Sha 256
inputs.help: The [SHA-2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2) SHA256 hash of the content of the item. For example, a zero-length input has value 'e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb92427ae41e4649b934ca495991b7852b855'.

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.label: Start Time
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. E.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: uploadDate
inputs.label: Upload Date
inputs.help: Date (including time if available) when this media object was uploaded to this site.

inputs.name: width
inputs.label: Width
inputs.help: The width of the item.

RepositoryFile.name: File
RepositoryFile.help: A File is a sequence of binary data and is described by some accompanying metadata. The metadata typically includes at least basic technical metadata (size, content type, modification date, etc.), but can also include properties related to preservation, digitization process, provenance, etc. Files MUST be contained by exactly one Object.

Standard.name: Standard
Standard.help: A reference point against which other things can be evaluated or compared.

inputs.name: asWKT
inputs.label: As WKT
inputs.help: The WKT serialization of a Geometry

RepositoryCollection.name: RepositoryCollection
RepositoryCollection.help: A collection of items, e.g. creative works or products.

inputs.name: collectionSize
inputs.label: Collection Size
inputs.help: The number of items in the [[Collection]].

inputs.name: hasMember
inputs.label: Has Member
inputs.help: Links to a subsidiary Object or Collection. Typically used to link to component parts, such as a book linking to a page.  Note on transitivity: hasMember is   not defined as transitive, but applications may treat it as transitive as local needs   dictate.

inputs.name: memberOf
inputs.label: Member Of
inputs.help: Links from an Object or Collection to a containing Object or Collection.

Journal.name: Journal
Journal.help: A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended to continue indefinitely, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

RepositoryObject.name: RepositoryObject
RepositoryObject.help: An Object is an intellectual entity, sometimes called a "work", "digital object", etc. Objects have descriptive metadata, access metadata, may contain files and other Objects as member "components". Each level of a work is therefore represented by an Object instance, and is capable of standing on its own, being linked to from Collections and other Objects. Member Objects can be ordered using the ORE Proxy class.

inputs.name: hasFile
inputs.label: Has File
inputs.help: Links to a File contained by this Object.

inputs.name: hasMember
inputs.label: Has Member
inputs.help: Links to a subsidiary Object or Collection. Typically used to link to component parts, such as a book linking to a page.  Note on transitivity: hasMember is   not defined as transitive, but applications may treat it as transitive as local needs   dictate.

inputs.name: memberOf
inputs.label: Member Of
inputs.help: Links from an Object or Collection to a containing Object or Collection.
